eith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Indian"}
{"title_page": "Housebreaking", "text_new": "{{about|animal training|comparable training of small children|toilet training|the crime of housebreaking|burglary}}\n{{Redirect|House training|the episode of TV series House|House Training}}\n[[File:Peepee time for little puppy.jpg|thumb|A dog trained to urinate outdoors rather than in its human owners' house]]\n'''Housebreaking''' (American English) or '''house-training''' (British English) is the process of training a [[domesticated]] [[animal]] that lives with its [[human]] owners in a house or other residence to [[excrete]] ([[urinate]] and [[defecate]]) outdoors, or in a designated indoor area (such as an absorbent pad or a [[litter box]]), rather than randomly inside the house following its instinctive behaviour. \n\nThe process of housebreaking or house-training requires patience and consistency from the human. Accidents are a part of the process and reacting negatively could discourage the animal, and slow down the training as a whole. \n\n== Dogs ==\nThe first step in housebreaking or house-training a new puppy is creating a '''routine''' or '''schedule'''. Young puppies aren't able to control their bladder as well as older dogs and should be taken out frequently. A general rule of thumb to follow is that puppies can hold their bladder one hour for every month; if a puppy is two months they can hold their urine for around two hours<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanesociety.org/resources/how-housetrain-your-dog-or-puppy|title=How to housetrain your dog or puppy|website=The Humane Society of the United States|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>. When taking the puppy outside their owner should take them to a '''designated spot''' every time. Using a word as they excrete, such as \"outside\" or \"bathroom,\" can be used as a way to remind the puppy what to do in the future once they are trained. '''Rewarding''' the puppy after they are done excreting helps the puppy recognize outdoors is the proper place to urinate and defecate. \n\n[[Crate training]] should be used when the human isn't able to take the dog out within its scheduled time. The crate should be big enough for the puppy to be comfortable, but small enough for them to not want to excrete inside of the crate. \n\nYASSSS\n\n== Cats ==\nThe process of housebreaking or house-training a kitten is vastly different from doing so for a puppy. Rather than a designated area outside, the designated area is '''indoors''' within a [[litter box]]. A cat's instinct is to excrete within a substrate, and then scratch and dig to hide the excretion; litter boxes support this '''natural behavior'''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texvetpets.org/article/litter-box-training-new-kitten/|title=Litter Box Training Your New Kitten {{!}} Feline Behavioral Health|last=says|first=Lorraine chaussee|website=TexVetPets|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>. There are a variety of options for what substrate (or litter) to put within a litter box but most veterinarians agree a scent-free clumping clay substrate is what cats prefer<ref name=\":0\" />. It is important to pick the right litter box whether it be smaller, bigger, have high walls, or if there should be a lid. In addition to what kind of litter box, '''location''' of the litter box matters. The litter box should be located in a quiet area so the kitten feels comfortable enough to use it whenever it pleases. \n[[File:Japanese litter box in use.jpg|thumb|213x213px|A cat prefers its litter box to be in a quiet, undisturbed area of the home]]\nIn the beginning, the kitten should be placed in the box to '''learn''' where it is and what the substrate feels like. The kitten should be placed in the box again after it has eaten as that is when the urge to excrete is the '''strongest'''<ref name=\":0\" />. Most kittens take to litter boxes immediately if the substrate is to their liking. All cats have different preferences and some may prefer a separate litter box for urine and feces.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Crate training]]\n*[[Litter box]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dog nav}}\n\n[[Category:Dog training and behavior]]\n[[Category:Cats as pets]]\n[[Category:Urine]]\n[[Category:Feces]]\n\n{{dog-stub}}\n{{feline-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|animal training|comparable training of small children|toilet training|the crime of housebreaking|burglary}}\n{{Redirect|House training|the episode of TV series House|House Training}}\n[[File:Peepee time for little puppy.jpg|thumb|A dog trained to urinate outdoors rather than in its human owners' house]]\n'''Housebreaking''' (American English) or '''house-training''' (British English) is the process of training a [[domesticated]] [[animal]] that lives with its [[human]] owners in a house or other residence to [[excrete]] ([[urinate]] and [[defecate]]) outdoors, or in a designated indoor area (such as an absorbent pad or a [[litter box]]), rather than randomly inside the house following its instinctive behaviour. \n\nThe process of housebreaking or house-training requires patience and consistency from the human. Accidents are a part of the process and reacting negatively could discourage the animal, and slow down the training as a whole. \n\n== Dogs ==\nThe first step in housebreaking or house-training a new puppy is creating a '''routine''' or '''schedule'''. Young puppies aren't able to control their bladder as well as older dogs and should be taken out frequently. A general rule of thumb to follow is that puppies can hold their bladder one hour for every month; if a puppy is two months they can hold their urine for around two hours<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.humanesociety.org/resources/how-housetrain-your-dog-or-puppy|title=How to housetrain your dog or puppy|website=The Humane Society of the United States|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>. When taking the puppy outside their owner should take them to a '''designated spot''' every time. Using a word as they excrete, such as \"outside\" or \"bathroom,\" can be used as a way to remind the puppy what to do in the future once they are trained. '''Rewarding''' the puppy after they are done excreting helps the puppy recognize outdoors is the proper place to urinate and defecate. \n\n[[Crate training]] should be used when the human isn't able to take the dog out within its scheduled time. The crate should be big enough for the puppy to be comfortable, but small enough for them to not want to excrete inside of the crate.\n\n== Cats ==\nThe process of housebreaking or house-training a kitten is vastly different from doing so for a puppy. Rather than a designated area outside, the designated area is '''indoors''' within a [[litter box]]. A cat's instinct is to excrete within a substrate, and then scratch and dig to hide the excretion; litter boxes support this '''natural behavior'''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texvetpets.org/article/litter-box-training-new-kitten/|title=Litter Box Training Your New Kitten {{!}} Feline Behavioral Health|last=says|first=Lorraine chaussee|website=TexVetPets|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>. There are a variety of options for what substrate (or litter) to put within a litter box but most veterinarians agree a scent-free clumping clay substrate is what cats prefer<ref name=\":0\" />. It is important to pick the right litter box whether it be smaller, bigger, have high walls, or if there should be a lid. In addition to what kind of litter box, '''location''' of the litter box matters. The litter box should be located in a quiet area so the kitten feels comfortable enough to use it whenever it pleases. \n[[File:Japanese litter box in use.jpg|thumb|213x213px|A cat prefers its litter box to be in a quiet, undisturbed area of the home]]\nIn the beginning, the kitten should be placed in the box to '''learn''' where it is and what the substrate feels like. The kitten should be placed in the box again after it has eaten as that is when the urge to excrete is the '''strongest'''<ref name=\":0\" />. Most kittens take to litter boxes immediately if the substrate is to their liking. All cats have different preferences and some may prefer a separate litter box for urine and feces.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Crate training]]\n*[[Litter box]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dog nav}}\n\n[[Category:Dog training and behavior]]\n[[Category:Cats as pets]]\n[[Category:Urine]]\n[[Category:Feces]]\n\n{{dog-stub}}\n{{feline-stub}}\n", "name_user": "174.100.160.67", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDogs)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Housebreaking"}
{"title_page": "Garcia Live Volume Five", "text_new": "{{short description|live album by Jerry Garcia Band}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Garcia Live Volume Five\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[Jerry Garcia Band]]\n| cover      = Garcia_Live_Volume_5.jpg\n| alt        = Jerry Garcia's Travis Bean TB1000A guitar\n| released   = October 21, 2014\n| recorded   = December 31, 1975\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[rhythm and blues]]\n| length     = 123:28\n| label      = [[ATO Records|ATO]]\n| producer   = Marc Allan<br>Joe Gastwirt\n| prev_title = [[Garcia Live Volume Four]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[On Broadway: Act One \u2013 October 28th, 1987]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Jerry Garcia]]\n | type       = live\n | prev_title = [[Garcia Live Volume Four]]\n | prev_year  = 2014\n | title      = Garcia Live Volume Five\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title = [[On Broadway: Act One \u2013 October 28th, 1987]]\n | next_year  = 2015\n}}\n}}\n'''''Garcia Live Volume Five''''' is a two-CD live album by the [[Jerry Garcia Band]].  It contains the complete concert recorded at the [[Keystone (Berkeley, California)|Keystone]] in [[Berkeley, California]] on December 31, 1975.  It was released by [[ATO Records]] on October 21, 2014.<ref name=Jambands/><ref name=JamBase/><ref name=L4LM/><ref name=DeadDisc/>\n\nThe lineup of the Jerry Garcia Band for this concert was [[Jerry Garcia]] on guitar and vocals, [[Nicky Hopkins]] on keyboards, [[John Kahn]] on bass, and [[Greg Errico]] on drums.  The show also featured performances by guest musicians [[Bob Weir]], [[Mickey Hart]], and [[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matthew Kelly]].\n\n==Recording and production==\nThe back cover of ''Garcia Live Volume Five'' includes a notice which reads in part, \"Originally captured to analog reels and later transferred to digital audio tape, the enclosed recordings have been meticulously mastered for release.  While certain minor sonic imperfections impervious to even the latest in digital wizardry remain, rest assured this vibrant performance transcends any inherent limitation in fidelity.\"\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[All About Jazz]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=AllMusic/>\n}}\nOn [[AllMusic]], Fred Thomas said, \"A particularly loose, appropriately celebratory feeling flows through much of the sets as the band wanders through seemingly completely unrehearsed instrumental interludes... When they do get cooking, it's on extended 12-bar blues vamps in the first set like \"It Ain't No Use\" and \"Pig's Boogie\", while the second set tends toward laid-back jams like \"Catfish John\" or shuffling electric blues workouts like \"Tore Up Over You\". The band takes some time to truly get in a groove on this date, finally settling into some of the best material near the end of the recording.\"<ref name=AllMusic/>\n\nIn ''[[All About Jazz]]'', Doug Collette wrote, \"The fact of the matter is everyone in the group gets their own chance to shine, but these abbreviated solo intervals don't interrupt the seamless flow of the collective interaction.... Kudos to Betty Cantor-Jackson for capturing the goings-on with such clarity, but also to Joe Gastwirt who in both mastering and curating this archive title deserves his co-production credit.... It's no small accomplishment to do perfect justice to the towering figure that is Jerry Garcia, even if the content is as deceptively down-to-earth as ''December 31st, Keystone Berkeley''.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n\n==Track listing==\n;Disc 1\n:''First set:''\n#\"[[Let It Rock (Chuck Berry song)|Let It Rock]]\" ([[Chuck Berry]]) \u2013 13:00\n#\"[[Mother Nature's Son]]\" ([[John Lennon]], [[Paul McCartney]]) \u2013 2:00\n#\"It Ain't No Use\" ([[Swamp Dogg|Jerry Williams]], [[Gary U.S. Bonds|Gary Bonds]], Don Hollinger) \u2013 11:36\n#\"[[God Save the Queen]]\" (traditional) \u2013 0:48\n#\"They Love Each Other\" ([[Jerry Garcia]], [[Robert Hunter (lyricist)|Robert Hunter]]) \u2013 7:49\n#\"Pig's Boogie\" ([[Nicky Hopkins]]) \u2013 10:41\n;Disc 2\n:''Second set:''\n#New Year's countdown \u2013 1:51\n#\"[[How Sweet It Is (To Be Loved by You)]]\" ([[Brian Holland]], [[Lamont Dozier]], [[Eddie Holland]]) \u2013 8:25\n#\"[[Catfish John]]\" ([[Bob McDill]], [[Allen Reynolds]]) \u2013 15:29\n#\"[[Mystery Train]]\" ([[Junior Parker]], [[Sam Phillips]]) \u2013 7:08\n#\"Drums\" -> \"New Year's Jam\" (Garcia, [[John Kahn]], Hopkins, [[Greg Errico]], [[Bob Weir]], [[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matthew Kelly]], [[Mickey Hart]]) \u2013 13:14\n#\"Mystery Train\" (Parker, Phillips) \u2013 1:48\n:''Third set:''\n#<li value=7>\"Tore Up over You\" ([[Hank Ballard]]) \u2013 10:46\n#Tuning \u2013 0:48\n#\"[[See See Rider|C.C. Rider]]\" (traditional) \u2013 8:20\n#\"(I'm a) Road Runner\" (Holland, Dozier, Holland) \u2013 9:43\n\n==Personnel==\n;Jerry Garcia Band\n*[[Jerry Garcia]] \u2013 [[electric guitar|guitar]], [[singing|vocals]]\n*[[Nicky Hopkins]] \u2013 [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]], vocals\n*[[John Kahn]] \u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]]\n*[[Greg Errico]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n;Additional musicians\n*[[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matthew Kelly]] \u2013 [[harmonica]], guitar (\"It Ain't No Use\", \"They Love Each Other\", \"Pig's Boogie\", second and third sets)\n*[[Mickey Hart]] \u2013 drums (second and third sets)\n*[[Bob Weir]] \u2013 guitar, vocals (second and third sets)\n;Production\n*Produced for release by Marc Allan, Joe Gastwirt\n*Original recordings produced by Jerry Garcia\n*Associate producer: Kevin Monty\n*Recording: [[Betty Cantor-Jackson]]\n*Mastering: Joe Gastwirt\n*Liner notes essay: [[David Gans (musician)|David Gans]]\n*Art direction, design, illustration: Ryan Corey\n*Photography: Ed Perlstein, Bob Minkin\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Jambands>[http://www.jambands.com/news/2014/08/25/garcialive-volume-five-december-31-1975-at-keystone-berkeley \"''GarciaLive Volume Five'': December 31, 1975 at Keystone Berkeley\"], Jambands.com, August 25, 2014. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=JamBase>[http://www.jambase.com/Articles/122510/GarciaLive-Volume-5-Lone-Jerry-Garcia-Band-New-Year%27s-Show \"''GarciaLive Volume 5'': Lone Jerry Garcia Band New Year's Show\"], JamBase, August 25, 2014. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=L4LM>[http://liveforlivemusic.com/news/garcialive-volume-5-to-showcase-jgbs-only-new-years-show-release-date-set-for-october/ \"''GarciaLive Volume 5'' to Showcase JGB's Only New Years Show, Release Date Set for October\"], Live for Live Music, September 24, 2014. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=DeadDisc>[http://www.deaddisc.com/disc/Garcia_Live_5.htm \"''Garcia Live: Volume Five'': December 31st, 1975, Keystone, Berkeley\"], Grateful Dead Family Discography. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=AllAboutJazz>Collette, Doug (December 7, 2014). [https://www.allaboutjazz.com/garcia-live-volume-five-keystone-berkeley-december-31-1975-by-doug-collette.php ''Garcia Live Volume Five'': Keystone Berkeley December 31, 1975], ''All About Jazz''. Retrieved July 4, 2016.</ref>\n<ref name=AllMusic>Thomas, Fred. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/garcia-live-vol-5-december-31st-1975-keystone-berkeley-mw0002717729 ''Garcia Live Volume Five''] at [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved November 11, 2014.</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garcia Live Volume 05}}\n{{Jerry Garcia Band}}\n{{Jerry Garcia}}\n[[Category:Jerry Garcia Band live albums]]\n[[Category:2014 live albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|live album by Jerry Garcia Band}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Garcia Live Volume Five\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[Jerry Garcia Band]]\n| cover      = Garcia_Live_Volume_5.jpg\n| alt        = Jerry Garcia's Travis Bean TB1000A guitar\n| released   = October 21, 2014\n| recorded   = December 31, 1975\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[rhythm and blues]]\n| length     = 123:28\n| label      = [[ATO Records|ATO]]\n| producer   = Marc Allan<br>Joe Gastwirt\n| prev_title = [[Garcia Live Volume Four]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[On Broadway: Act One \u2013 October 28th, 1987]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Jerry Garcia]]\n | type       = live\n | prev_title = [[Garcia Live Volume Four]]\n | prev_year  = 2014\n | title      = Garcia Live Volume Five\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title = [[On Broadway: Act One \u2013 October 28th, 1987]]\n | next_year  = 2015\n}}\n}}\n'''''Garcia Live Volume Five''''' is a two-CD live album by the [[Jerry Garcia Band]].  It contains the complete concert recorded at the [[Keystone (Berkeley, California)|Keystone]] in [[Berkeley, California]] on December 31, 1975.  It was released by [[ATO Records]] on October 21, 2014.<ref name=Jambands/><ref name=JamBase/><ref name=L4LM/><ref name=DeadDisc/>\n\nThe lineup of the Jerry Garcia Band for this concert was [[Jerry Garcia]] on guitar and vocals, [[Nicky Hopkins]] on keyboards, [[John Kahn]] on bass, and [[Greg Errico]] on drums.  The show also featured performances by guest musicians [[Bob Weir]], [[Mickey Hart]], and [[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matthew Kelly]].\n\n==Recording and production==\nThe back cover of ''Garcia Live Volume Five'' includes a notice which reads in part, \"Originally captured to analog reels and later transferred to digital audio tape, the enclosed recordings have been meticulously mastered for release.  While certain minor sonic imperfections impervious to even the latest in digital wizardry remain, rest assured this vibrant performance transcends any inherent limitation in fidelity.\"\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[All About Jazz]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=AllMusic/>\n}}\nOn [[AllMusic]], Fred Thomas said, \"A particularly loose, appropriately celebratory feeling flows through much of the sets as the band wanders through seemingly completely unrehearsed instrumental interludes... When they do get cooking, it's on extended 12-bar blues vamps in the first set like \"It Ain't No Use\" and \"Pig's Boogie\", while the second set tends toward laid-back jams like \"Catfish John\" or shuffling electric blues workouts like \"Tore Up Over You\". The band takes some time to truly get in a groove on this date, finally settling into some of the best material near the end of the recording.\"<ref name=AllMusic/>\n\nIn ''[[All About Jazz]]'', Doug Collette wrote, \"The fact of the matter is everyone in the group gets their own chance to shine, but these abbreviated solo intervals don't interrupt the seamless flow of the collective interaction.... Kudos to Betty Cantor-Jackson for capturing the goings-on with such clarity, but also to Joe Gastwirt who in both mastering and curating this archive title deserves his co-production credit.... It's no small accomplishment to do perfect justice to the towering figure that is Jerry Garcia, even if the content is as deceptively down-to-earth as ''December 31st, Keystone Berkeley''.\"<ref name=AllAboutJazz/>\n\n==Track listing==\n;Disc 1\n:''First set:''\n#\"[[Let It Rock (Chuck Berry song)|Let It Rock]]\" ([[Chuck Berry]]) \u2013 13:00\n#\"[[Mother Nature's Son]]\" ([[John Lennon]], [[Paul McCartney]]) \u2013 2:00\n#\"It Ain't No Use\" ([[Swamp Dogg|Jerry Williams]], [[Gary U.S. Bonds|Gary Bonds]], Don Hollinger) \u2013 11:36\n#\"[[God Save the Queen]]\" (traditional) \u2013 0:48\n#\"They Love Each Other\" ([[Jerry Garcia]], [[Robert Hunter (lyricist)|Robert Hunter]]) \u2013 7:49\n#\"Pig's Boogie\" ([[Nicky Hopkins]]) \u2013 10:41\n;Disc 2\n:''Second set:''\n#New Year's countdown \u2013 1:51\n#\"[[How Sweet It Is (To Be Loved by You)]]\" ([[Brian Holland]], [[Lamont Dozier]], [[Eddie Holland]]) \u2013 8:25\n#\"[[Catfish John]]\" ([[Bob McDill]], [[Allen Reynolds]]) \u2013 15:29\n#\"[[Mystery Train]]\" ([[Junior Parker]], [[Sam Phillips]]) \u2013 7:08\n#\"Drums\" -> \"New Year's Jam\" (Garcia, [[John Kahn]], Hopkins, [[Greg Errico]], [[Bob Weir]], [[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matthew Kelly]], [[Mickey Hart]]) \u2013 13:14\n#\"Mystery Train\" (Parker, Phillips) \u2013 1:48\n:''Third set:''\n#<li value=7>\"Tore Up over You\" ([[Hank Ballard]]) \u2013 10:46\n#Tuning \u2013 0:48\n#\"[[See See Rider|C.C. Rider]]\" (traditional) \u2013 8:20\n#\"(I'm a) Road Runner\" (Holland, Dozier, Holland) \u2013 9:43\n\n==Personnel==\n;Jerry Garcia Band\n*[[Jerry Garcia]] \u2013 [[electric guitar|guitar]], [[singing|vocals]]\n*[[Nicky Hopkins]] \u2013 [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]], vocals\n*[[John Kahn]] \u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]]\n*[[Greg Errico]] \u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n;Additional musicians\n*[[Matthew Kelly (musician)|Matthew Kelly]] \u2013 [[harmonica]], guitar (\"It Ain't No Use\", \"They Love Each Other\", \"Pig's Boogie\", second and third sets)\n*[[Mickey Hart]] \u2013 drums (second and third sets)\n*[[Bob Weir]] \u2013 guitar, vocals (second and third sets)\n;Production\n*Produced for release by Marc Allan, Joe Gastwirt\n*Original recordings produced by Jerry Garcia\n*Associate producer: Kevin Monty\n*Recording: [[Betty Cantor-Jackson]]\n*Mastering: Joe Gastwirt\n*Liner notes essay: [[David Gans (musician)|David Gans]]\n*Art direction, design, illustration: Ryan Corey\n*Photography: Ed Perlstein, Bob Minkin\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Jambands>[http://www.jambands.com/news/2014/08/25/garcialive-volume-five-december-31-1975-at-keystone-berkeley \"''GarciaLive Volume Five'': December 31, 1975 at Keystone Berkeley\"], Jambands.com, August 25, 2014. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=JamBase>[http://www.jambase.com/Articles/122510/GarciaLive-Volume-5-Lone-Jerry-Garcia-Band-New-Year%27s-Show \"''GarciaLive Volume 5'': Lone Jerry Garcia Band New Year's Show\"], JamBase, August 25, 2014. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=L4LM>[http://liveforlivemusic.com/news/garcialive-volume-5-to-showcase-jgbs-only-new-years-show-release-date-set-for-october/ \"''GarciaLive Volume 5'' to Showcase JGB's Only New Years Show, Release Date Set for October\"], Live for Live Music, September 24, 2014. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=DeadDisc>[http://www.deaddisc.com/disc/Garcia_Live_5.htm \"''Garcia Live: Volume Five'': December 31st, 1975, Keystone, Berkeley\"], Grateful Dead Family Discography. Retrieved October 11, 2014.</ref>\n<ref name=AllAboutJazz>Collette, Doug (December 7, 2014). [https://www.allaboutjazz.com/garcia-live-volume-five-keystone-berkeley-december-31-1975-by-doug-collette.php ''Garcia Live Volume Five'': Keystone Berkeley December 31, 1975], ''All About Jazz''. Retrieved July 4, 2016.</ref>\n<ref name=AllMusic>Thomas, Fred. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/garcia-live-vol-5-december-31st-1975-keystone-berkeley-mw0002717729 ''Garcia Live Volume Five''] at [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved November 11, 2014.</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Jerry Garcia Band}}\n{{Jerry Garcia}}\n[[Category:Jerry Garcia Band live albums]]\n[[Category:2014 live albums]]\n", "name_user": "Mudwater", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adjusted category sort.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garcia_Live_Volume_Five"}
{"title_page": "Niemcza", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Niemcza\n| image_skyline = 2016 Rynek w Niemczy 02.jpg\n| image_caption = Market Square (''Rynek'')\n| image_flag = POL Niemcza flag.svg\n| image_shield = POL Niemcza COA.svg\n| subdivision_type  = Country\n| subdivision_name  = {{POL}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Lower Silesian]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Powiat|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w County|Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w]]\n| subdivision_type3 = [[Gmina]]\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Gmina Niemcza|Niemcza]]\n| leader_title      = Mayor\n| leader_name       = Jaros\u0142aw W\u0119g\u0142owski\n| established_title = Town rights\n| established_date  = 1282\n| coordinates       = {{coord|50|43|N|16|50|E|region:PL|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Poland\n| area_total_km2 = 19.81\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_as_of = 2019-06-30<ref>{{cite web |title=Population. Size and structure and vital statistics in Poland by territorial divison in 2019. As of 30th June|url=https://stat.gov.pl/en/topics/population/population/population-size-and-structure-and-vital-statistics-in-poland-by-territorial-divison-in-2019-as-of-30th-june,3,26.html|website=stat.gov.pl|publisher=Statistics Poland|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n| population_total = 2965\n| timezone = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset = +1\n| timezone_DST = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +2\n| postal_code_type = Postal code\n| postal_code = 58-230\n| area_code = +48 74\n| registration_plate = DDZ\n| website = http://www.um.niemcza.pl }}\n\n'''Niemcza''' {{IPAc-pl|'|\u0144|e1|m|cz|a}} ({{lang-de|Nimptsch}}) is a town in [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w County]], [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship]], in south-western [[Poland]]. It is the seat of the administrative district ([[gmina]]) called [[Gmina Niemcza]].\n\nThe town lies on the [[\u015al\u0119za River]], approximately {{convert|20|km|mi|0}} east of [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w]], and {{convert|48|km|mi|0}} south of the regional capital [[Wroc\u0142aw]].\n\nFrom 1975 to 1998 Niemcza was in [[Wa\u0142brzych Voivodeship]].\n\n==History==\nNiemcza is historically one of the most important towns of Silesia.<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.361\">Weczerka, p.361</ref><ref name=\"Niemcza\">[http://www.um.niemcza.pl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=458&Itemid=123 \"Official website of the city]</ref> The oldest traces date back to the [[Bronze Age]]. Between 1000 and 800 B.C. people of the [[Lusatian culture]] fortified the so-called \"city hill\" and incorporated this fortification into their Silesian defence system. This fort was probably destroyed during a battle against the [[Scythian]] around 500 BC. Members of the Germanic [[Silingi]] tribe who did not participate in the [[Migration Period]] but stayed in Silesia chose the place in the 4th century as their fortified center of a Germanic settlement area between \"mons Silencii\" ([[Mount \u015al\u0119\u017ca|\u015al\u0119\u017ca]]) and the river \"Selenca\" ([[\u015al\u0119za]]).<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.361\"/> [[Slavs]] arrived after the 6th century and called this place \"Nemci\" ( = mute, metaphorically \"those who do not speak our language\").<ref name=\"Niemcza\"/><ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\">Weczerka, p.362</ref> [[Thietmar of Merseburg]] later described \"Nemzi\" as \"eo quod a nostris olim sitcondita, dicta\" (Nemzi is called like that because it is, according to reports, founded by our people).<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\"/><ref>Petry, p.76</ref> The settlement was expanded and evolved into the center of the [[\u015al\u0119\u017canie]] district.\n[[File:Niemcza, deska na n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed.jpg|thumb|left|A monument commemorating the [[Siege of Niemcza|Polish defense of Niemcza]] in 1017 at the Market Square]]\nIn early times Niemcza became an important base in [[Bohemia]]s fight for Silesia. After 990 it was seized by [[Poland]] under first historic ruler [[Mieszko I of Poland]] and withstood both emperor [[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry II.]] in 1017 ([[Siege of Niemcza]]) and a major offensive of Bohemia in 1093.<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\">Weczerka, p.362</ref> In 1137, the Polish and Czech rulers, [[Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]] and [[Sob\u011bslav I, Duke of Bohemia|Sob\u011bslav I]], met in Niemcza.<ref name=UM>{{cite web|url=http://www.um.niemcza.pl/turysci/historia-2|title=Historia|website=Urz\u0105d Miasta i Gminy Niemcza|accessdate=19 October 2019|language=Polish}}</ref><ref name=MN>{{cite web|url=https://muzeumniemcza.pl/historia/kalendarium/|title=Historia / Kalendarium|website=Wirtualne Muzeum Ziemi Niemcza\u0144skiej|accessdate=19 October 2019|language=Polish}}</ref> In 1152 the overthrown Polish ruler [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw II the Exile]] stayed in Niemcza.<ref name=UM/> After 1155 it became the center of a [[Piast]] castellany district. This preurban civitas consisted of a settlement enclosed by imposing ramparts in [[Great Moravia|great-moravian]] design (the only one in Silesia), the castellany castle with St. Peter chapel, first mentioned in 1288/95, and a market place around St. Adalbert church, one of the oldest churches of Silesia, outside and to the west of the ramparts. The area was surrounded by several manors.\n\nThe German [[Ostsiedlung]] reached Niemcza and the surrounding area already in 1210.<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\"/> The settlement however grew only slow as the new German town was founded directly on the soil of the cramped old Polish urbs, whereas the more spacious market place around St. Adalbert was remodeled to a village. In 1282, Duke [[Henry IV Probus]] granted Niemcza [[town rights]], although it is possible that town rights were granted earlier.<ref name=UM/> Remarkable was the establishment of the parish church St. Marien, which in 1295 was assigned to both Poles and Germans for shared and separate usage. Before 1300 a new city wall was built, which is in parts preserved. At the same time the wooden castellany castle was replaced by a stone castle, and a city hall was first mentioned in 1474.\n[[File:2016 Brama Dolna w Niemczy 01.jpg|thumb|The historical fortifications and gate near the entrance to the Old Town]]\n\nWith the partition of the [[Duchy of Silesia|Duchy of Wroc\u0142aw]] in 1311 the town passed to the [[Duchy of Brzeg]]. In 1322 both the town and municipal area (Weichbild) became a pledged possession of the Duchy of \u015awidnica, whose duke [[Bolko I the Strict|Bolko I.]] used the strategic position of Niemcza in his fight against [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]]. In 1331 Niemcza was successfully defended during the Czech invasion of King [[John of Bohemia]].<ref name=UM/> After 1392 the duchy of \u015awidnica was dissolved, Niemcza came back to the duchy of Brzeg, which in 1419 was reunited with the [[Duchy of Legnica]] and remained under the rule of the [[Piast dynasty]] until 1675, although under Bohemian suzerainty. The [[Hussite]]s seized Niemcza/Nimptsch in 1430 and held the town for several years. After six unsuccessful sieges it was returned in 1434 and razed to the ground by the burghers of [[Wroc\u0142aw]]. In 1455 duchess [[Hedwig of Legnica]] confirmed the town rights of Niemcza.<ref name=MN/>\n\n[[File:Niemcza by Werner.jpg|left|thumb|220px|Nimptsch in 1752, drawing by Friedrich Bernhard Werner]]\nIn 1481 the administration of the municipal area was moved to [[Bia\u0142obrzezie]].<ref name=MN/> Nimptsch, which was equipped below average, enclosed by noble properties, on the periphery of the municipal area, in the extreme western corner of the duchy and close to the far more successful foundations of [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w|Reichenbach]] (Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w) and [[Z\u0105bkowice \u015al\u0105skie|Frankenstein]] (Z\u0105bkowice \u015al\u0105skie), could never overcome such backlashes. A moderate recovery, marked by the reconstruction of the town wall, the modernisation of the,never used, ducal residence, the rebuilding of St. Adalbert as the Protestant church St. George in 1612 and the awarding of several town rights, was stopped by the [[Thirty Years' War]]. During the war, in 1625 a plague epidemic broke out, and in the 1630s the town was destroyed and plundered by foreign troops.<ref name=MN/> In 1635 [[Daniel Casper von Lohenstein]] was born in the residence, the only building not destroyed during this war. Only 12 out of 103 landlords of Nimpsch survived firestorm and pest. In 1642 the town hall was rebuilt.<ref name=MN/>\n\nThe slow rebuilding, with the help of immigrated Bohemians, was again stopped by several major fires, which destroyed the town hall and parts of the residence. After the extinction of the local Piasts in 1675 the [[counter-reformation]] obtained the tension-filled reestablishment of a Catholic commune. At the same time Nimptsch became a center of sacred music thanks to Protestant cantor Johann Heinrich Quiel.\n\n{{multiple image |align=right |perrow=3 |total_width=350 |header=Historic sights of Niemcza (examples)\n| image1=2016 Niemcza, pl. Rynek 10 01.jpg\n| image2=Niemcza, kostel.jpg\n| image3=2016 Baszta Bramy G\u00f3rnej w Niemczy 02.jpg\n| image4=Niemcza kamienica Rynek 37.jpg\n| image5=2016 Niemcza, pl. Rynek 34 02.jpg\n| image6=2016 Niemcza, pl. Rynek 5 01.jpg\n| footer=Top, left to right: Town hall, Immaculate Conception church, Tower of the Upper Gate; bottom: historic townhouses at the Market Square\n}}\nIn 1742 it was annexed by [[Kingdom of Prussia]], and from 1871 to 1945 it was part of Germany. In 1832 and 1846, Protestant and Catholic schools were built.<ref name=MN/> In 1940, the Germans established a [[Forced labour under German rule during World War II|forced labour]] camp in the town,<ref name=MN/> and in 1944 also the ''AL Nimptsch'' subcamp of the [[Gro\u00df-Rosen concentration camp]], whose prisoners were mostly Poles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.gross-rosen.eu/historia-kl-gross-rosen/filie-obozu-gross-rosen/|title=Subcamps of KL Gross- Rosen|website=Gross-Rosen Museum in Rogo\u017anica|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> After the defeat of [[Nazi Germany]] Nimptsch passed to [[Poland]] and the historic Polish name ''Niemcza'' was restored. The German inhabitants were expelled<ref>''Die vollst\u00e4ndige Entfernung der deutschen Bev\u00f6lkerung aus Polen war nur auf dem Weg der organisierten Massenaussiedlung zu erreichen. Sie begann im Winter 1945/46 und brachte bis Ende 1945 \u00fcber 3 Millionen Menschen in die britische und sowjetische Besatzungszone. Ende 1947 war die Aussiedlung im Wesentlichen abgeschlossen, auch wenn 1948 bis 1950 noch einmal rund 140.000 Deutsche aus Polen ausgesiedelt wurden - vor allem jene, denen als unentbehrliche Arbeitskr\u00e4fte die Ausreise bis dahin verweigert worden war.'' Thum, p.118</ref> and the town was resettled with Poles, many of whom where themselves expelled from [[Kresy|former eastern Polish territories]], annexed by the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=UM/> Also [[Greeks in Poland|Greeks]], refugees of the [[Greek Civil War]], settled in Niemcza in the 1950s.<ref name=MN/><ref>Izabela Kubasiewicz, ''Emigranci z Grecji w Polsce Ludowej. Wybrane aspekty z \u017cycia mniejszo\u015bci'', p. 117 (in Polish)</ref> The town wasn't destroyed in [[World War II]]. Of the three preserved historical buildings at that time the [[Renaissance]] octagon of the residence and the Catholic Church are decayed and demolished. St. George is preserved, as well as the late Baroque residential buildings on the market place (''Rynek'').\n\nThe town suffered in the [[1997 Central European flood]].<ref name=MN/>\n\n==Population==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! year !! population\n|-\n| 1740 || 1150\n|-\n| 1787 || 1256\n|-\n| 1825 || 2182\n|-\n| 1905 || 2216\n|-\n| 1939 || 3523 (16,24&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n|-\n| 1961 || 3557 (19,25&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n|-\n| 1970 || 3772\n|-\n| 2006 || 3121\n|-\n| 2007 || 3085\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Friedrich von Logau]]\n* [[Daniel Casper von Lohenstein]]\n* [[Sigmar Wittig]]\n* [[Jo Brauner]]\n* [[Pawe\u0142 Sibik]]\n* [[Krzysztof Piatek]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\nSee [[Gmina Niemcza#Twin_towns_\u2013_sister_cities|twin towns of Gmina Niemcza]].\n\n==Surroundings==\n* '''[[Gola Dzier\u017coniowska Castle]]'''\n* Cistercian monastery at [[Henryk\u00f3w, Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Henryk\u00f3w]]\n\n==References==\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book\n  |title= Handbuch der historischen St\u00e4tten: Schlesien \n  |last= Weczerka \n  |first= Hugo \n  |year= 2003 \n  |publisher= Alfred Kr\u00f6ner Verlag \n  |location= Stuttgart \n  |isbn= 3-520-31602-1}}\n*{{cite book\n  |title= Geschichte Schlesiens. Band 1: Von der Urzeit bis zum Jahre 1526 \n  |last= Petry\n  |first= Ludwig\n  |author2=Josef Joachim Menzel |author3=Winfried Irgang\n   |year= 2000 \n  |publisher= Jan Thorbecke Verlag Stuttgart \n  |location= Stuttgart \n  |isbn= 3-7995-6341-5}}\n*{{cite book\n  |title= Die fremde Stadt. Breslau nach 1945 \n  |last= Thum\n  |first= Gregor\n  |year= 2006 \n  |publisher= [[Random House]] \n  |location= M\u00fcnchen\n  |isbn= 3-570-55017-6}}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{commons category|Niemcza}}\n\n{{Gmina Niemcza}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Lower Silesian Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w County]]\n[[Category:Cities in Silesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Niemcza\n| image_skyline = 2016 Rynek w Niemczy 02.jpg\n| image_caption = Market Square (''Rynek'')\n| image_flag = POL Niemcza flag.svg\n| image_shield = POL Niemcza COA.svg\n| subdivision_type  = Country\n| subdivision_name  = {{POL}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Lower Silesian]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Powiat|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w County|Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w]]\n| subdivision_type3 = [[Gmina]]\n| subdivision_name3 = [[Gmina Niemcza|Niemcza]]\n| leader_title      = Mayor\n| leader_name       = Jaros\u0142aw W\u0119g\u0142owski\n| established_title = Town rights\n| established_date  = 1282\n| coordinates       = {{coord|50|43|N|16|50|E|region:PL|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Poland\n| area_total_km2 = 19.81\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_as_of = 2019-06-30<ref>{{cite web |title=Population. Size and structure and vital statistics in Poland by territorial divison in 2019. As of 30th June|url=https://stat.gov.pl/en/topics/population/population/population-size-and-structure-and-vital-statistics-in-poland-by-territorial-divison-in-2019-as-of-30th-june,3,26.html|website=stat.gov.pl|publisher=Statistics Poland|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n| population_total = 2965\n| timezone = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset = +1\n| timezone_DST = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +2\n| postal_code_type = Postal code\n| postal_code = 58-230\n| area_code = +48 74\n| registration_plate = DDZ\n| website = http://www.um.niemcza.pl }}\n\n'''Niemcza''' {{IPAc-pl|'|\u0144|e1|m|cz|a}} ({{lang-de|Nimptsch}}) is a town in [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w County]], [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship]], in south-western [[Poland]]. It is the seat of the administrative district ([[gmina]]) called [[Gmina Niemcza]].\n\nThe town lies on the [[\u015al\u0119za River]], approximately {{convert|20|km|mi|0}} east of [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w]], and {{convert|48|km|mi|0}} south of the regional capital [[Wroc\u0142aw]].\n\nFrom 1975 to 1998 Niemcza was in [[Wa\u0142brzych Voivodeship]].\n\n==History==\nNiemcza is historically one of the most important towns of Silesia.<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.361\">Weczerka, p.361</ref><ref name=\"Niemcza\">[http://www.um.niemcza.pl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=458&Itemid=123 \"Official website of the city]</ref> The oldest traces date back to the [[Bronze age]]. Between 1000 and 800 B.C. people of the [[Lusatian culture]] fortified the so-called \"city hill\" and incorporated this fortification into their Silesian defence system. This fort was probably destroyed during a battle against the [[Scythian]] around 500 BC. Members of the Germanic [[Silingi]] tribe who did not participate in the [[Migration Period]] but stayed in Silesia chose the place in the 4th century as their fortified center of a Germanic settlement area between \"mons Silencii\" ([[Mount \u015al\u0119\u017ca|\u015al\u0119\u017ca]]) and the river \"Selenca\" ([[\u015al\u0119za]]).<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.361\"/> [[Slavs]] arrived after the 6th century and called this place \"Nemci\" ( = mute, metaphorically \"those who do not speak our language\").<ref name=\"Niemcza\"/><ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\">Weczerka, p.362</ref> [[Thietmar of Merseburg]] later described \"Nemzi\" as \"eo quod a nostris olim sitcondita, dicta\" (Nemzi is called like that because it is, according to reports, founded by our people).<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\"/><ref>Petry, p.76</ref> The settlement was expanded and evolved into the center of the [[\u015al\u0119\u017canie]] district.\n[[File:Niemcza, deska na n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed.jpg|thumb|left|A monument commemorating the [[Siege of Niemcza|Polish defense of Niemcza]] in 1017 at the Market Square]]\nIn early times Niemcza became an important base in [[Bohemia]]s fight for Silesia. After 990 it was seized by [[Poland]] under first historic ruler [[Mieszko I of Poland]] and withstood both emperor [[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry II.]] in 1017 ([[Siege of Niemcza]]) and a major offensive of Bohemia in 1093.<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\">Weczerka, p.362</ref> In 1137, the Polish and Czech rulers, [[Boles\u0142aw III Wrymouth]] and [[Sob\u011bslav I, Duke of Bohemia|Sob\u011bslav I]], met in Niemcza.<ref name=UM>{{cite web|url=http://www.um.niemcza.pl/turysci/historia-2|title=Historia|website=Urz\u0105d Miasta i Gminy Niemcza|accessdate=19 October 2019|language=Polish}}</ref><ref name=MN>{{cite web|url=https://muzeumniemcza.pl/historia/kalendarium/|title=Historia / Kalendarium|website=Wirtualne Muzeum Ziemi Niemcza\u0144skiej|accessdate=19 October 2019|language=Polish}}</ref> In 1152 the overthrown Polish ruler [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw II the Exile]] stayed in Niemcza.<ref name=UM/> After 1155 it became the center of a [[Piast]] castellany district. This preurban civitas consisted of a settlement enclosed by imposing ramparts in [[Great Moravia|great-moravian]] design (the only one in Silesia), the castellany castle with St. Peter chapel, first mentioned in 1288/95, and a market place around St. Adalbert church, one of the oldest churches of Silesia, outside and to the west of the ramparts. The area was surrounded by several manors.\n\nThe German [[Ostsiedlung]] reached Niemcza and the surrounding area already in 1210.<ref name=\"Weczerka, p.362\"/> The settlement however grew only slow as the new German town was founded directly on the soil of the cramped old Polish urbs, whereas the more spacious market place around St. Adalbert was remodeled to a village. In 1282, Duke [[Henry IV Probus]] granted Niemcza [[town rights]], although it is possible that town rights were granted earlier.<ref name=UM/> Remarkable was the establishment of the parish church St. Marien, which in 1295 was assigned to both Poles and Germans for shared and separate usage. Before 1300 a new city wall was built, which is in parts preserved. At the same time the wooden castellany castle was replaced by a stone castle, and a city hall was first mentioned in 1474.\n[[File:2016 Brama Dolna w Niemczy 01.jpg|thumb|The historical fortifications and gate near the entrance to the Old Town]]\n\nWith the partition of the [[Duchy of Silesia|Duchy of Wroc\u0142aw]] in 1311 the town passed to the [[Duchy of Brzeg]]. In 1322 both the town and municipal area (Weichbild) became a pledged possession of the Duchy of \u015awidnica, whose duke [[Bolko I the Strict|Bolko I.]] used the strategic position of Niemcza in his fight against [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]]. In 1331 Niemcza was successfully defended during the Czech invasion of King [[John of Bohemia]].<ref name=UM/> After 1392 the duchy of \u015awidnica was dissolved, Niemcza came back to the duchy of Brzeg, which in 1419 was reunited with the [[Duchy of Legnica]] and remained under the rule of the [[Piast dynasty]] until 1675, although under Bohemian suzerainty. The [[Hussite]]s seized Niemcza/Nimptsch in 1430 and held the town for several years. After six unsuccessful sieges it was returned in 1434 and razed to the ground by the burghers of [[Wroc\u0142aw]]. In 1455 duchess [[Hedwig of Legnica]] confirmed the town rights of Niemcza.<ref name=MN/>\n\n[[File:Niemcza by Werner.jpg|left|thumb|220px|Nimptsch in 1752, drawing by Friedrich Bernhard Werner]]\nIn 1481 the administration of the municipal area was moved to [[Bia\u0142obrzezie]].<ref name=MN/> Nimptsch, which was equipped below average, enclosed by noble properties, on the periphery of the municipal area, in the extreme western corner of the duchy and close to the far more successful foundations of [[Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w|Reichenbach]] (Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w) and [[Z\u0105bkowice \u015al\u0105skie|Frankenstein]] (Z\u0105bkowice \u015al\u0105skie), could never overcome such backlashes. A moderate recovery, marked by the reconstruction of the town wall, the modernisation of the,never used, ducal residence, the rebuilding of St. Adalbert as the Protestant church St. George in 1612 and the awarding of several town rights, was stopped by the [[Thirty Years' War]]. During the war, in 1625 a plague epidemic broke out, and in the 1630s the town was destroyed and plundered by foreign troops.<ref name=MN/> In 1635 [[Daniel Casper von Lohenstein]] was born in the residence, the only building not destroyed during this war. Only 12 out of 103 landlords of Nimpsch survived firestorm and pest. In 1642 the town hall was rebuilt.<ref name=MN/>\n\nThe slow rebuilding, with the help of immigrated Bohemians, was again stopped by several major fires, which destroyed the town hall and parts of the residence. After the extinction of the local Piasts in 1675 the [[counter-reformation]] obtained the tension-filled reestablishment of a Catholic commune. At the same time Nimptsch became a center of sacred music thanks to Protestant cantor Johann Heinrich Quiel.\n\n{{multiple image |align=right |perrow=3 |total_width=350 |header=Historic sights of Niemcza (examples)\n| image1=2016 Niemcza, pl. Rynek 10 01.jpg\n| image2=Niemcza, kostel.jpg\n| image3=2016 Baszta Bramy G\u00f3rnej w Niemczy 02.jpg\n| image4=Niemcza kamienica Rynek 37.jpg\n| image5=2016 Niemcza, pl. Rynek 34 02.jpg\n| image6=2016 Niemcza, pl. Rynek 5 01.jpg\n| footer=Top, left to right: Town hall, Immaculate Conception church, Tower of the Upper Gate; bottom: historic townhouses at the Market Square\n}}\nIn 1742 it was annexed by [[Kingdom of Prussia]], and from 1871 to 1945 it was part of Germany. In 1832 and 1846, Protestant and Catholic schools were built.<ref name=MN/> In 1940, the Germans established a [[Forced labour under German rule during World War II|forced labour]] camp in the town,<ref name=MN/> and in 1944 also the ''AL Nimptsch'' subcamp of the [[Gro\u00df-Rosen concentration camp]], whose prisoners were mostly Poles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.gross-rosen.eu/historia-kl-gross-rosen/filie-obozu-gross-rosen/|title=Subcamps of KL Gross- Rosen|website=Gross-Rosen Museum in Rogo\u017anica|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> After the defeat of [[Nazi Germany]] Nimptsch passed to [[Poland]] and the historic Polish name ''Niemcza'' was restored. The German inhabitants were expelled<ref>''Die vollst\u00e4ndige Entfernung der deutschen Bev\u00f6lkerung aus Polen war nur auf dem Weg der organisierten Massenaussiedlung zu erreichen. Sie begann im Winter 1945/46 und brachte bis Ende 1945 \u00fcber 3 Millionen Menschen in die britische und sowjetische Besatzungszone. Ende 1947 war die Aussiedlung im Wesentlichen abgeschlossen, auch wenn 1948 bis 1950 noch einmal rund 140.000 Deutsche aus Polen ausgesiedelt wurden - vor allem jene, denen als unentbehrliche Arbeitskr\u00e4fte die Ausreise bis dahin verweigert worden war.'' Thum, p.118</ref> and the town was resettled with Poles, many of whom where themselves expelled from [[Kresy|former eastern Polish territories]], annexed by the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=UM/> Also [[Greeks in Poland|Greeks]], refugees of the [[Greek Civil War]], settled in Niemcza in the 1950s.<ref name=MN/><ref>Izabela Kubasiewicz, ''Emigranci z Grecji w Polsce Ludowej. Wybrane aspekty z \u017cycia mniejszo\u015bci'', p. 117 (in Polish)</ref> The town wasn't destroyed in [[World War II]]. Of the three preserved historical buildings at that time the [[Renaissance]] octagon of the residence and the Catholic Church are decayed and demolished. St. George is preserved, as well as the late Baroque residential buildings on the market place (''Rynek'').\n\nThe town suffered in the [[1997 Central European flood]].<ref name=MN/>\n\n==Population==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! year !! population\n|-\n| 1740 || 1150\n|-\n| 1787 || 1256\n|-\n| 1825 || 2182\n|-\n| 1905 || 2216\n|-\n| 1939 || 3523 (16,24&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n|-\n| 1961 || 3557 (19,25&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n|-\n| 1970 || 3772\n|-\n| 2006 || 3121\n|-\n| 2007 || 3085\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Friedrich von Logau]]\n* [[Daniel Casper von Lohenstein]]\n* [[Sigmar Wittig]]\n* [[Jo Brauner]]\n* [[Pawe\u0142 Sibik]]\n* [[Krzysztof Piatek]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\nSee [[Gmina Niemcza#Twin_towns_\u2013_sister_cities|twin towns of Gmina Niemcza]].\n\n==Surroundings==\n* '''[[Gola Dzier\u017coniowska Castle]]'''\n* Cistercian monastery at [[Henryk\u00f3w, Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Henryk\u00f3w]]\n\n==References==\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book\n  |title= Handbuch der historischen St\u00e4tten: Schlesien \n  |last= Weczerka \n  |first= Hugo \n  |year= 2003 \n  |publisher= Alfred Kr\u00f6ner Verlag \n  |location= Stuttgart \n  |isbn= 3-520-31602-1}}\n*{{cite book\n  |title= Geschichte Schlesiens. Band 1: Von der Urzeit bis zum Jahre 1526 \n  |last= Petry\n  |first= Ludwig\n  |author2=Josef Joachim Menzel |author3=Winfried Irgang\n   |year= 2000 \n  |publisher= Jan Thorbecke Verlag Stuttgart \n  |location= Stuttgart \n  |isbn= 3-7995-6341-5}}\n*{{cite book\n  |title= Die fremde Stadt. Breslau nach 1945 \n  |last= Thum\n  |first= Gregor\n  |year= 2006 \n  |publisher= [[Random House]] \n  |location= M\u00fcnchen\n  |isbn= 3-570-55017-6}}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{commons category|Niemcza}}\n\n{{Gmina Niemcza}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Lower Silesian Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Dzier\u017coni\u00f3w County]]\n[[Category:Cities in Silesia]]\n", "name_user": "Atsme", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix miscapitalizations (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niemcza"}
{"title_page": "John Gwynneth", "text_new": "{{short description|Welsh clergyman and musical composer}}\nDr '''John Gwynneth''' (or Guinete) ([[Floruit|fl.]] 1511-1557), was a clergyman of Welsh nationality originating from [[Gwynedd]], and was a [[composer]] of religious and liturgical vocal music.<ref>J.P.D. Cooper, 'Gwynneth [Gwynedd], John (d. 1560x63), composer and polemicist', Oxford Dictionary of National Biography (2004).</ref> He held benefices in England in [[Northamptonshire]], [[Bedfordshire]] and [[London]], and in North Wales at [[Clynnog Fawr]].<ref>C.F. Mayer and T.B. Walters, ''The Correspondence of Reginald Pole. 4: A Biographical Companion: the British Isles'', St Andrews Studies in Medieval History (Ashgate, Aldershot 2008), pp. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_daeDoWdQ0cC&pg=PA235#v=onepage&q&f=false 235], [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_daeDoWdQ0cC&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q&f=false 236] (Google).</ref> Although he was a [[polemic|polemicist]] for the Catholic faith, he maintained his ministry through the reigns of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] and [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]], and was brother-in-law and [[executor]] of [[Stephen Vaughan (merchant)|Stephen Vaughan]] (a supporter of the [[English Reformation]]). He is principally remembered, with [[Thomas Tallis]] and others, as one of the leading exponents of early [[Tudor period]] [[polyphony]].\n\n==Young life==\n;Origins and education\nJohn Gwynneth was the son of Dafydd ap Llewelyn ap Ithel of Castellmarch, [[Llanengan]], [[Ll\u0177n Peninsula|Ll\u0177n]], [[Caernarfonshire]]:<ref>According to Arthur Bulkeley, Dafydd was brother to Robert ap Llewelyn ap Ithel of Castellmarch, ancestor of [[William Jones (judge)|Sir William Jones, knight]] (1566-1640). The relationship is explained by Professor A.H. Dodd, 'Jones, Sir William (1566-1640), judge',''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig'' (1959), [https://bywgraffiadur.cymru/article/c3-JONE-WIL-1566 online].</ref> it was claimed that he was of the Welsh royal blood.<ref>Dom A. Hamilton, O.S.B. (ed.), ''The Chronicle of the English Augustinian Canonesses Regular of the Lateran, at St. Monica's in Louvain, 1548-1625'', 2 vols (Sands & Co., Edinburgh/London 1904), I, [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive).</ref> [[Anthony Wood (antiquary)|Anthony \u00e0 Wood]] remarks that he had great natural abilities but little or nothing to support him in his studies at [[Oxford University]]. He was therefore sponsored by a churchman (\"an ecclesiastical [[Gaius Maecenas|Mec\u00e6nas]]\") who hoped that he would become a useful writer against the opponents of Roman Catholicism. Wood adds that in his youth he was well versed in polite literature, and later familiarized himself with the writings and arguments for and against the doctrines of [[Martin Luther|Luther]] and [[Huldrych Zwingli|Zwingli]].<ref>A. \u00e0 Wood, ed. P. Bliss, ''Athenae Oxonienses, with the Fasti'', 3rd Edition with additions, 3 vols (F.C. & J. Rivington, etc., London/Oxford 1813-1817), I, [https://archive.org/details/athenaeoxoniense01wooduoft/page/n323 pp. 246-48] (Internet Archive).</ref> \n\nHowever there is no record that he completed a bachelor's degree. From his declaration to the University made in 1531 (below), it appears that from around 1510 he was active in the composition and theory of polyphonic music. Since he became a secular priest, this experience was perhaps gained in Oxford and then or thereafter as a secular chaplain attached to a religious house possessing a choir, though he did not enter a formal order. In 1522, a clerk, he was owed \u00a318 (an old debt) by the [[St Albans Cathedral|Abbey of St Albans]].<ref>29 September 1522, item 2583, 'St Albans', in J.S. Brewer (ed.), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 3: 1519-1523 (HMSO London, 1867), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol3/pp1084-1101 pp. 1084-1101, at p. 1098] (British History Online).</ref> When still an [[acolyte]] he was collated, apparently by the [[St Andrew's Priory, Northampton|Cluniac priory of St Andrew]], [[Northampton]],<ref>For which see 'Houses of Cluniac monks: The priory of St Andrew, Northampton', in R.M. Serjeantson and W.R.D. Adkins (eds), ''A History of the County of Northampton'', Vol. 2 (VCH/HMSO London, 1906), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/northants/vol2/pp102-109 pp. 102-09] (British History Online).</ref> to the [[benefice]] of Stuchbury or Stotesbury (near [[Sulgrave]]), Northamptonshire in December 1528, which he held until his death.<ref>G. Baker, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Northampton'' (John Bowyer Nichols, London 1822-1830), I, [https://archive.org/details/HistoryAndAntiquitiesOfTheCountyOfNorthamptonBakerVol1/page/n693 p. 691] (Internet Archive).</ref> Stuchbury was attached to the College of [[All Saints' Church, Northampton|All Hallows, Northampton]],<ref>J. Caley (ed.), ''Valor Ecclesiasticus Temp. Henry VIII'', IV (Commissioners, 1821), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7EfvuwaAb6MC&pg=PA320#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 320] (Google).</ref> which had an important medieval choir.\n\n;Musical composer\nJohn Gwynneth is particularly noteworthy as an early Tudor composer of music.<ref>W.H. Grattan Flood, ''Early Tudor Composers'' (Oxford University Press/Humphrey Milford, London 1925), pp. 108-10.</ref> By December 1531 he had achieved a remarkable output, at which time he made a formal approach to the University of Oxford: <blockquote>\"John Gwynneth a secular priest, who had spent twelve years in the praxis and theory of music, and had composed all the [[antiphon|responses]] of the whole year in division-song,<ref>I.e. [[polyphony]], \"in cantis chrispis aut fractis, ut aiunt\", S. Harper, ''Music in Welsh Culture before 1650: a Study of the Principal Sources'' (Ashgate 2007/Routledge, London and New York 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FzQrDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT304#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 283-84] (Google).</ref> and had published many masses in the said song, supplicated that these his labours might enable him to be admitted to the praxis of music. This being granted conditionally that he compose one mass against the act following, he supplicated again that whereas he had spent 20 years in the praxis and theory of music, and had published three masses of five parts, and five masses of four, as also certain symphonas, antiphonas, and divers songs for the use of the church, he might be admitted to proceed in the faculty of music; which desire of his being granted, conditionally that he pay to the university, on the day of his admission, 20 pence, he was forthwith licensed to proceed.\"<ref>A. \u00e0 Wood, ed. P. Bliss, ''Fasti Oxonienses, or Annals of the University of Oxford'', New Edition, Part I: 1500-1640, (F.C. & J. Rivington etc, London 1815), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=U1ruEakGAKwC&pg=PA1531#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 86] (Google)</ref></blockquote>\n\nThus he was awarded the degree of [[Doctor of Music]].<ref>C.W. Boase, ''Register of the University of Oxford'' Vol. I: 1449-63; 1505-71 (Oxford Historical Society/Clarendon Press, Oxford 1885), [https://archive.org/details/registerofuniver01univuoft/page/166 p. 167] (Internet Archive)</ref><ref>T. Cooper, 'Gwynneth, John, (fl. 1557), catholic divine and musician', ''Dictionary of National Biography'' (1885-1900), [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Gwynneth,_John_(DNB00) Vol. 23].</ref> He was one of the composers whose work was included in the collection printed in 1530, called the \"Book of XX Songes\",<ref>See an introduction in J. Milsom, 'Songs and Society in Early Tudor London', in I. Fenlon (ed.), ''Early Music History'', Vol. 17, Studies in Medieval and Early Modern Music (Cambridge University Press 1997), pp. 282-85.</ref> of which only the volume of bass lines (''Bassus'') survives.<ref>'My Love mourneth' (commencing 'And I mankynd') in ''Book of XX Songes'' (1530), \"Bassus\", fols 30v [https://repository.royalholloway.ac.uk/items/c6584bb2-3d90-62b2-88a2-63f62493baa0/1/treenav.jsp?tempwn.b=close to 34v] (Royal Holloway digital). Text in E. Rickert, ''Ancient English Christmas Carols, 1400 to 1700'' (Chatto & Windus, London 1910), [https://archive.org/details/ancientenglishch00rickuoft/page/140 pp. 140-42], 156 (Internet Archive).</ref> [[Thomas Morley]], in his ''Plaine and Easie Introduction to Practicall Musicke'' (1597), lists \"Io. Guinneth\" among the ''English'' practitioners whose works he has diligently perused, for finding the true use of the [[Mode (music)|Moods]].<ref>T. Morley, ''A Plaine and Easie Introduction to Practicall Musicke set downe in forme of a Dialogue'' (Peter Short, London 1597), [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A07753.0001.001/1:20?rgn=div1;view=fulltext List of Authorities] (Umich/eebo - Open).</ref>\n\n;Family connections\nJohn Gwynneth's sister Margaret was firstly the wife of Edward Awpart (Alporte<ref>No doubt a representative of the Alport family of [[Cannock]], Staffordshire.</ref>), citizen and [[Worshipful Company of Girdlers|Girdler]] of London in the parish of [[St Mary le Bow]], who originated from [[Penkridge]] in [[Staffordshire]]. In 1524 Awpart took the lease on premises called \"The Three Leggs\" in St Mary le Bow from St Bartholomew's Priory.<ref>D.J. Keene and V. Harding, 'St. Mary le Bow 104/32', in ''Historical Gazetteer of London Before the Great Fire'', Cheapside; Parishes of All Hallows Honey Lane, St Martin Pomary, St Mary Le Bow, St Mary Colechurch and St Pancras Soper Lane (Centre for Metropolitan History, London 1987), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-gazetteer-pre-fire/pp346-350 pp. 346-50], after note 6 (British History Online).</ref> The Awparts had five children, Elizabeth, Anne, Joan, Edward and Susan, who were all unmarried at the time of their father's death in 1532. By his will dated 24 June 1532 Awpart, who mentions a debt to his hostess at the \"Viniarde in [[Antwerp|Andwarpe]]\", appointed his widow and \"Sir\" John Gwynneth<ref>\"Sir\" is a usual title for a secular priest at this date, not denoting knighthood.</ref> his executors, making a gift of \u00a36.13s.4d to John, and both were sworn to probate (John in person, Margaret by attorney) on 6 July 1532. In this will Awpart refers to his wife's mother by the name Joan White.<ref>Will of Edward Awpart, \"Girdler\" (mis-written \"Gardener\" in Discovery Catalogue of TNA (UK)) of London (P.C.C. 1532, Thower quire, m/film imgs 237-38): PROB 11/24/211 and PROB 11/24/220.</ref><ref>\"White\" is the English counterpart of the Welsh name \"Gwyn\".</ref> He appointed Thomas Marbury, [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers|Haberdasher]], as Overseer, who in the same year, as executor to John Maltby, ran into difficulties with the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|Mercers' Company]].<ref>A.F. Sutton, ''The Mercery of London: Trade, Goods and People, 1130\u20131578'' (Ashgate, 2005/Routledge, Abingdon 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=epyoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT495#v=onepage&q&f=false pt. 495] (Google).</ref>\n\nMargaret Gwynneth then (by 1533) re-married to [[Stephen Vaughan (merchant)|Stephen Vaughan]], Governor of the [[Company of Merchant Adventurers of London|Merchant Adventurers]] (1534) and royal agent and secretary in Antwerp. Vaughan in 1536 assumed the lease on \"The Three Leggs\", and, following the priory's dissolution, in 1540 it was granted by the Crown to him and Margaret for life, and in remainder to their male issue.<ref>Keene and Harding, ''Historical Gazetteer'', [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-gazetteer-pre-fire/pp346-350 pp. 346-50] at notes 6-10 (British History Online).</ref><ref>'379. Grants in December 1540, no. 44', in J. Gairdner and R.H. Brodie (eds), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 16: 1540-1541 (HMSO, London 1898), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol16/pp162-178 pp. 175-76] (British History Online).</ref> Vaughan's sister Mawdlyn was the wife of the London [[Grocer]] William Pratt, after whose death in 1539<ref>Will of William Pratt, Grocer of London (P.C.C. 1539, Dyngeley quire). Not to be confused with the Draper of the same name and similar date.</ref> she married Pratt's well-travelled apprentice [[Thomas Lodge (Lord Mayor of London)|Thomas Lodge]]. Vaughan, who could call upon the help of [[Thomas Cromwell]], found a place at Court for his wife Margaret as silkwoman in service to [[Anne Boleyn]].<ref>R.M. Warnicke, ''The Rise and Fall of Anne Boleyn: Family Politics at the Court of Henry VIII'' (Cambridge University Press 1991), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_iUIzcXV4toC&pg=PA136#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 136] (Google).</ref><ref>S.M. Felch (ed.), ''The Collected Works of Anne Vaughan Lock'', Arizona Center for Medieval and Renaissance Studies in conjunction with Renaissance English Text Society (Tempe, AZ, 1999), pp. xxv\u2013xxvi.</ref> With him she had further children ([[Anne Locke|Anne]], Stephen and Jane), dying in 1544.<ref>M.K. Dale, 'Vaughan, Stephen (by 1502-49), of St. Mary-le-Bow, London', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509-1558'' (from Boydell and Brewer, 1982), [https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/vaughan-stephen-1502-49 History of Parliament online].</ref> Marbury died in 1545,<ref>Will of Thomas Merbury, haberdasher (P.C.C. 1545, Pynnyng quire).</ref> leaving John Gwynneth with sole responsibility to administer the Awpart estate.\n\n==Opportunity and controversy==\n;Stoke sub Hamdon, and Luton - writing against Frith\n[[File:StMarysLuton.jpg|thumb|right|250px|St Mary's church, Luton]]\nThe King presented Gwynneth to the collegiate church of [[Stoke sub Hamdon Priory]], [[Somerset]], in September 1534, at the Crown's disposal on the death of John Glyn.<ref>'Grants in September 1534: 3. John Gwynneth, clerk', in J. Gairdner (ed.), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 7: 1534 (London 1883), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol7/pp462-475 p. 474] (British History Online).</ref> He published his first writings against the doctrines of [[John Frith]], as ''The confutacyon of the fyrst parte of Frythes boke: with a dysputacyon before whether it be possyble for any heretike to know that hym selfe is one or not. And also an other, whether it be wors to denye directely more or lesse of the fayth.'' This was printed at [[St Albans]] in 1536,<ref>J. Ames, ed. W. Herbert, ''Typographical Antiquities, or, An Historical Account of the Origin and Progress of Printing in Great Britain and Ireland'', Volume 1 part 3 (London, 1785-1790), [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_s2C8MeKuXPwC/page/n127 pp. 1430-36] (Internet Archive).</ref> under the auspices of the last abbot,<ref>W. Wizeman (SJ), ''The Theology and Spirituality of Mary Tudor's Church'' (Ashgate, 2006/Routledge, London & New York 2017), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SmdQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 39] (Google).</ref> three years after Frith's execution as a [[heretic]]. Gwynneth was presented to the vicariate of [[Luton]], [[Bedfordshire]] (\"the best preferment in the Abbey of St Albans\") by Stephen Vaughan as assignee of Edward Awpart senior by grant of St Albans Abbey, in December 1537,<ref>Mayer and Walters, ''Correspondence of Reginald Pole, Biographical Companion'',  p. 236.</ref> where he continued his ministrations for twenty years, until around 1558.<ref>H. Cobbe, ''Luton Church - Historical and Descriptive'' (George Bell and Sons/F. Hockliffe, London/Luton 1899),  [https://archive.org/details/lutonchurchhisto00cobbuoft/page/n199 pp. 173-85] (Internet Archive) and [https://archive.org/details/lutonchurchhist00cobbgoog/page/n295 p. 259]. A Catalogue of Gwynneth's works is at Appendix BI, [https://archive.org/details/lutonchurchhisto00cobbuoft/page/n663 pp. 612-16] (Internet Archive).</ref> \n\n;Clynnog Fawr\nIn October 1537 Gwynneth was presented by [[Henry VIII of England|the King]] to the provostship or rectory ''[[Sinecure|sine cura]]'' of [[Clynnog Fawr]] (in the [[Ll\u0177n Peninsula|Ll\u0177n]] south of Caernarfon), with the chapels and church of [[Llangeinwen]] and [[Llangaffo]] ([[Anglesey]]), upon the death of Dr. William Glyn of [[Glynllifon]].<ref>'Grants, October 1537: 29. John Gwynneth, clerk', in J. Gairdner (ed.), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 12 Part 2: June-December 1537 (London, 1891), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol12/no2/pp345-355 p. 353] (British History Online). This Dr Glyn is not to be confused with the [[William Glyn (bishop)|Bishop of Bangor]] of that name, who died in 1558.</ref> [[John Capon]], [[Bishop of Bangor]] (1534\u201339), would not admit him, instituting instead Gregory Williamson, a child nephew of Thomas Cromwell's, to the living.<ref>Wood, ed. Bliss, ''Athenae Oxonienses, with the Fasti'', I (1813), [https://archive.org/details/athenaeoxoniense01wooduoft/page/n323 pp. 246-47] (Internet Archive).</ref> [[Arthur Bulkeley]], then [[Prebendary]] of Clynnog Fechan at Llangeinwen, had been displaced thereby at Cromwell's prompting.<ref>Wood, ed. Bliss, ''Athenae Oxonienses, with the Fasti'', II (1815), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MxUTbAj-58kC&pg=PA681#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 767-68] (Google).</ref> Gwynneth brought a writ of ''[[quare impedit]]'' against Bishop Capon and Williamson, but in 1539 Capon was succeeded by [[John Bird (bishop)|John Bird]] (1539\u201341), and in July 1540 Cromwell fell. In October 1540 [[Thomas Cranmer|Archbishop Cranmer]] granted a dispensation to Gwynneth to occupy the perpetual vicarage of [[Enstone]], Oxfordshire pending its transfer from the [[Diocese of Lincoln]] to that of [[Diocese of Oxford|Oxford]] in 1542.<ref>Clergy of the Church of England database, Dispensation Appointment Record ID: [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/DisplayDispensation.jsp?CDBDispenID=3925 3925]; Location: (Parish) Church: Enstone, Location Record ID: [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/locations/index.jsp?locUnitKey=1282 1189].</ref>\n\n[[File:Eglwys Beuno Sant, Clynnog Fawr, south side.jpg|thumb|right|250px|St Beuno's church, Clynnog Fawr]]\nIn July 1541 Gwynneth renewed his suit, now against Bird, who however was translated to [[Bishop of Chester|Chester]] in August 1541. In October, during the vacancy in the see of Bangor, Gwynneth (described as \"Magister\", and \"sacellanus\" or royal chaplain) had himself instituted to Clynnog Fawr by the Commissary of the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]].<ref>Church of England Clergy database, CCEd Appointment Evidence Record [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/DisplayAppointment.jsp?CDBAppRedID=288881 ID: 288881].</ref> Arthur Bulkeley became Bishop of Bangor in November 1541, but before he came into residence Gwynneth had obtained a [[Default judgement|judgement in default]]. There followed a great controversy between Gwynneth and Bulkeley<ref>'Petition of Bishop Bulkeley' (Bangor Cathedral Archives), in W. Hughes, ''Diocesan Histories: Bangor'' (S.P.C.K., London 1911), [https://archive.org/details/bangor00commgoog/page/n196 pp. 190-92] (Internet Archive).</ref> in the [[Court of Star Chamber]],<ref>'Interrogatories: John Gwyneth', The National Archives (UK), ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/record?catid=-3190770&catln=7 E 321/46/205]. See also [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C3977076 STAC 2/25/139].</ref> and in 1543 Gwynneth won judgement in his favour.<ref>T. Hearne (ed.), ''Thomae Caii (Collegii Universitatis Regnante Elizabetha Magistri) Vindiciae Antiquitatis Academiae Oxoniensis contra Joannem Caium Cantabrigiensem'', 2 vols (E theatro Sheldoniensis, Oxford 1733), II, p. 666.</ref> \n\nHaving thus asserted the King's right of patronage over that of the Bishop of Bangor, he then, on 21 January, 36 Henry VIII (1544/45) at St Mary le Bow, demised the Rectory of Clynnog Fawr to Dafydd ap Robert alias Gryffyth of Merthyr, Caernarfonshire, gent., for nine years, he paying John \u00a357.14s.6d for each year that he occupied it.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Common Pleas, CP 40/1157, m. 509 front, [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/M/CP40no1157/aCP40no1157fronts/IMG_1043.htm AALT image 1043].</ref> In the following year however, it became likely that the provostship would be subject to Crown resumption under the Act for Chantries. Vaughan appealed to [[William Paget, 1st Baron Paget|Lord Paget]] on Gwynneth's behalf, explaining that he had spent 8 years in continual suit and expense in the law over it, at his personal cost of 500 marks.<ref>'26. Vaughan to Paget, 7 January 1546', in J. Gairdner and R.H. Brodie (eds), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'' Vol. 21 Part 1: January-August 1546,  (London, 1908), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol21/no1/pp10-27 p. 13] (British History Online).</ref>\n\n==Challenge and responsibility==\n;St Peter, Westcheap\nMeanwhile, on 19 September 1543, at the presentation of [[Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden|Thomas Audley]] (died 1544), he was instituted by [[Bishop Bonner]] to the rectory of [[St Peter, Westcheap]] in the city of London (historically a St Albans benefice).<ref>R. Newcourt, ''Repertorium Ecclesiasticum Parochiale Londinense'' (Benjamin Motte, for Baker, Tooke, Parker, Bowyer and Clements, London 1708), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9bNQAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA522#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 522] (Google).</ref> The Louvain narrative states that he had formerly been curate there.<ref>Hamilton, ''Chronicle of St Monica's'', [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive).</ref> At St Peter's he followed in the footsteps of [[Thomas Goodrich]] and [[Richard Gwent]], both very advanced churchmen. He held this benefice through the reign of [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] (possibly with some interruption), and through that of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]]. During Edward's reign the old Faringdon chantry was done away with, the church fraternity was dissolved, the rood was taken down, the altars were replaced with tables and the paraphernalia of the Catholic ritual were removed from St Peter's.<ref>W. Sparrow Simpson, 'On the parish of St. Peter Cheap, in the City of London, from 1392 to 1633', ''Journal of the British Archaeological Association'' Original Series vol. XXIV (1868), [https://archive.org/details/journalofbritish24brit/page/248 pp. 248-68], at pp. 250-51 (Internet Archive).</ref> \n\nAs the [[Chantry#Abolition of Chantries Acts, 1545 and 1547|dissolution of the chantries]] proceeded, in March 1548 Sir [[Walter Mildmay]], one of the two Surveyors-general of the [[Court of Augmentations]], was appointed a Commissioner for the sale of chantry lands. Gwynneth's first cousin, John Roberts of Castellmarch, was [[Sheriff of Caernarvonshire]] in that year, whose son Griffith ap John (sometime in the service of [[John Dudley, 1st Duke of Northumberland|John Dudley, Earl Warwick]]) was appointed Constable of [[Conwy Castle]] in 1549.<ref>Dodd, 'Jones, Sir William', ''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig''.</ref> \n\n;Executor and matchmaker\nIn October 1548 Gwynneth's niece Joan Awparte, Vaughan's stepdaughter, married Edward Myldemay,<ref>J.L. Chester and G.J. Armytage, ''Allegations for Marriage Licences issued from the Faculty Office of the Archbishop of Canterbury at London 1542 to 1869'', Harleian Society XXIV (1886), [https://archive.org/details/marriagelicence00chester/page/12 p. 13] (Internet Archive).</ref> elder brother of Sir Walter. The marriage was brief, for Edward, who had become [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|citizen and Mercer]] in October 1541,<ref>H.A. St.J. Mildmay, ''A Brief Memoir of the Mildmay Family'' (John Lane, The Bodley Head/Private, London/New York 1913), [https://archive.org/details/briefmemoirofmil00mild/page/n25 p. 14] (Internet Archive).</ref> made his will on 22 March 1549, in which he gives \"to Elizabeth Awparte, sister to my late wife Johanna, \u00a320 which is owing me by my uncle the vicar of Luton.\" (Possibly this was money owing by Gwynneth upon the marriage settlement, since he, as the surviving executor of Edward Awparte senr, held the portions of the Awparte children until their age of 21 or else were married, a term now elapsing.<ref>Will of Edward Awparte, Girdler of London (P.C.C. 1532).</ref>) Myldemay makes gifts of various of his wife's effects: the will was proved by Sir Walter Mildmay on 3 April 1549.<ref>Will of Edwarde Myldemay, Gentleman of London (P.C.C. 1549, Populwell quire).</ref> \n\nStephen Vaughan made Gwynneth his executor at his death in December 1549, leaving him in charge of \"The Three Leggs\" in Westcheap with a room for his own lodgings and the management of the premises on behalf of Vaughan's daughters for the space of nine years. Vaughan's brother-in-law Thomas Lodge, husband of Mawdlyn (who died in 1548), and John Griffith were his overseers. (Lodge had of late conducted secret surveillance for Vaughan overseas.<ref>J. Gairdner and R.H. Brodie (eds), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol XX Part 1: January-July 1545 (HMSO 1905), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol20/no1/pp101-114 p. 107, item 250] (British History Online).</ref>) Gwynneth swore to probate on 26 February 1549/50.<ref>Will of Stephen Vaughan (P.C.C. 1550, Coode quire). 'Inquisition post mortem: Stephen Vaughan', in G.S. Fry (ed.), ''Abstracts of Inquisitiones Post Mortem For the City of London'', Part 1 (London 1896), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/abstract/no1/pp78-95 pp. 78\u201395] (British History Online).</ref> In that connection he had the task of delivering to Sir John Williams some \u00a3305 owing to the King from Vaughan's accounts as Under-Treasurer of the Tower Mint.<ref>J.R. Dasent (ed.), ''Acts of the Privy Council of England'', New Series III: 1550\u20131552 (HMSO 1891), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112119573936;view=1up;seq=348 p. 308] (Hathi Trust).</ref>\n \nA notice of Gwynneth's niece Jane Vaughan, written upon family authority in 1632, states that Gwynneth was \"a long time kept in prison when heresy came in\", and thereafter arranged Jane's marriage to (Thomas) Wiseman,<ref>Hamilton, ''Chronicle of St Monica's'', [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive). The source, derived from living tradition, is explicit that John Gwynneth was the uncle of Jane Wiseman the recusant. C. Walker, 'Wiseman [n\u00e9e Vaughan], Jane (d. 1610)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (2004) gives an incorrect parentage.</ref> (son of John Wiseman of [[Felsted]], Essex (died 1559/60)<ref>Wizeman, ''The Theology and Spirituality of Mary Tudor's Church'', p. 36. Parentage confused in S.M. Thorpe/R.J.W. Swales, 'Wiseman, John (by 1515-58), of Great Canfield, Essex', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509-1558'' (from Boydell and Brewer, 1982), [https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/wiseman-john-1515-58 History of Parliament Online].</ref>): if so this imprisonment may have been in the Edwardian period, as he barely survived into the time of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]], and the Wisemans' elder children were born during the 1550s.<ref>These connections and affiliations are fully demonstrated by G. Ford, ''Genealogical Findings from the Diary of Thomas Cartwright, Bishop of Chester (1634-1689)'', 2 vols (Queensland, 2013), I ({{ISBN|148255142X}}). See Will of John Wiseman of Felsted, Essex (P.C.C. 1560, Mellershe quire), PROB 11/43/74.</ref> Vaughan had entrusted to Gwynneth a dower of gold for the use of his children, for which, in 1551-52, they in their own names were obliged to sue the stepmother (now the wife of [[George Rolle]] of [[Stevenstone]] (d. 1552)<ref>A.D.K. Hawkyard, 'Rolle, George (by 1486-1552), of Stevenstone, Devon and London', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509-1558'' (from Boydell and Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/rolle-george-1486-1552 History of Parliament Online]. His will was made 11 November 1552 and first proved on 9 February 1552/53: Will of George Rolle of Stevenstone, (P.C.C. 1553, Tashe quire), PROB 11/36/44 and PROB 11/36/183.</ref>) in the years immediately after their father's death:<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery: ''Vaughan v Rolles'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7500615 C 1/1319/9-11].</ref> the suit was then continued with Gwynneth's support.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery: ''Guyneth v Rolles'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7500616 C 1/1319/12-14]. ?See also ''John ?Guwill v. George Rolle and Margery'' [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C9250536 C 4/120/88].</ref> At this stage Jane Vaughan was unmarried, but her sister [[Anne Locke|Anne]] was already married to Henry Locke, son of Sir [[William Lok]].\n\n==Vindication==\n;Marian apologist\nThe accession of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]] and the aftermath of [[Wyatt's rebellion]] restored Gwynneth's doctrine. Gwynneth was at Luton on 23 July 1553 to deliver his sermon celebrating the return of a Catholic monarch, in which he did not fail to find a parallel in Mary's name with the cult of [[Mary, mother of Jesus]] so favoured in Tudor Catholicism (and so repudiated by the Edwardian Reformists).<ref>Wizeman, ''The Theology and Spirituality of Mary Tudor's Church'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SmdQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA233#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 233] (Google).</ref> It was soon published by [[John Cawood (printer)|John Cawood]] and found a ready circulation.<ref>J.N. King, 'The Account Book of a Marian Bookseller, 1553-4', ''British Library Journal'' (1987), [https://www.bl.uk/eblj/1987articles/pdf/article3.pdf pp. 33-57] (British Library pdf), at pp. 39, 42 (nos. 20 and 22).</ref> In April 1554 outside his church door in London, at the [[Eleanor cross|Cheapside Cross]], the popular mood was expressed by the spectacle of a cat hanged on a scaffold, robed like a priest with its head shaved, its bound paws holding up a morsel representing the [[Sacramental bread|Sacrament]].<ref>J. Foxe, ''The Actes and Monuments'', 1563 edition, [https://www.johnfoxe.org/index.php?realm=text&gototype=&edition=1563&pageid=1069&anchor=cat#kw Book 5, p. 1069] ('John Foxe's ''Acts and Monuments'' online'): from City Records, Journal 16, fol. 285 b.</ref> \n\nFrom the London press of [[Thomas Berthelet]] Gwynneth renewed his writings against Frith in enlarged editions, with ''{{Proper name|A manifeste detection of the notable falshed of that part of Iohn Frithes boke whiche he calleth his foundacion}}'',<ref>Full text at [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A02424.0001.001?view=toc Umich/eebo] (Open).</ref> and ''{{Proper name|A Declaration of the State wherein all Heretickes dooe leade their lives; and also of their continuall indever and propre fruictes}}'',<ref>Full text at [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo2/A02423.0001.001?view=toc Umich/eebo] (Reserved: Login only).</ref> in 1554. The title page of the latter bore the text: \"{{lang|en-emodeng|There is a waie, which semeth to a man streight, and yet the endes therof leaden to perdicion}}\" ([[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]], 16:25). The lease of nine years having expired, he brought action for a debt of \u00a367.14s.6d against Dafydd Gryffyth owing for Clynnog Fawr,<ref>The National Archives (UK), Common Pleas CP 40/1157, m. 385 dorse, AALT image [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/M/CP40no1157/bCP40no1157dorses/IMG_0662.htm 662] (2nd entry), and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/M/CP40no1157/aCP40no1157fronts/IMG_1043.htm m. 509 front] as above.</ref> and against various persons for tithes in Caernarfon and Anglesey.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery, ''Guyneth v Vaghan'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7501647 C 1/1352/77-82].</ref> Its chantry lands had passed into Crown hands.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery: ''Cobham v ap Madocke'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7496874 C 1/1210/21-23].</ref>\n\n;Restitutions\nIn 1555 there was a concerted effort to restore the fittings of St Peter's in Westcheap. Brick and stone altars were instated and re-dedicated, a new rood with St Mary and [[John the Apostle|St John]] forming a [[Stabat Mater (art)|Stabat Mater]] was acquired, and Father Howe was brought in to repair the organs with new springs and new tongues for the [[Flue pipe|principals]] in the bass [[Regal (instrument)|regals]]. The [[Easter Sepulchre]] was repaired, and a vigil was kept.<ref>Simpson, 'Parish of St Peter Cheap', [https://archive.org/details/journalofbritish24brit/page/256 at pp. 256-58], 264, 268. (Internet Archive).</ref> In his writings Gwynneth deplored the reformists' removal of the altar tables out of the chancel into the body of the church:<ref>Cooper, 'Gwynneth, John', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''.</ref> masonry altars made this more difficult. The charges for the hallowing of the altars are itemized in the St Peter's accounts, including the small sum of 4d for a pound of [[frankincense]].<ref>Simpson, ''Parish of St Peter Cheap'', [https://archive.org/details/journalofbritish24brit/page/262 262] (Internet Archive).</ref> The 1556 accounts show the acquisition of a book of [[homily|homilies]], three large [[Roman Ritual|Processionals]], three \"greylls\", an [[Antiphonary]], and a [[Legendary material in Christian hagiography|Legendary]], all very useful and necessary for the performance of the Roman ritual.<ref>Simpson, 'Parish of St Peter Cheap', p. 267.</ref>\n\nIn Luton in 1545 Gwynneth had acted as overseer in the will of Edward Crawley, one of his churchwardens. Crawley, with the consent of the parish, had sold off a silver [[pax (liturgical object)|pax]], a silver-gilt [[pyx]], and two double-gilt [[chalice]]s belonging to the church for \u00a315, which was to be \"{{lang|en-emodeng|ymployed about the new makynge of an ile of the churche}}\". This came to light in the Edwardian inventory of church goods, whereupon Crawley's brother took responsibility. In March 1556 the commissioners made a discretionary allowance of \u00a38.6s.8d towards the repairs, on condition that Crawley spend the remainder on church ornaments by Midsummer, for which Gwynneth gave an undertaking to the [[Bishop of Ely]]. On 10 June he was able to report to the commissioners ([[William Barnes (died 1558)|William Berners]], [[Thomas Mildmay (by 1515 \u2013 1566)|Thomas Mildmay]] and John Wiseman) that Crawley (at his own expense) had spent \u00a35 on a cope and vestment of blue velvet and more than 20 nobles on a chalice.<ref>W. Austin, ''History of a Bedfordshire Family; being a History of the Crawleys of Nether Crawley (etc.)'' (Alston Rivers, Ltd., London 1911), [https://archive.org/details/historyofbedford00aust/page/n157 pp. 67-72] (Internet Archive), citing F.C. Eeles and J.E. Brown (eds), ''The Edwardian Inventories for Bedfordshire'' (Longmans, Green, London 1905), pp. 22, 27.</ref>\n\n==Last stand==\nVaughan's widow, having made a further marriage to [[Sir Leonard Chamberlain|Sir Leonard Chamberlayne]] of [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire|Woodstock]], with him brought suit against Gwynneth claiming that he had withheld her share of Vaughan's estate. The parties agreed to [[arbitration]], which found that Gwynneth, as executor, owed a further \u00a3500 over and above \u00a3500 which Dame Margery had already received. This was then reduced to \u00a3400 by taking into account \u00a3100 which she and George Rolle had taken upon a bond from the children's portions deposited for them by Gwynneth in the Chamber of London, and which had not been repaid. Gwynneth made a payment and was granted his release or acquittance by the arbitrators. \n\nChamberlayne, however, pressed his bill, and Gwynneth then brought the matter to a perfect issue. He objected that Rolle's bond was nothing to do with Chamberlayne's suit, had not been mentioned in arbitration, and was never a subject of dispute. He revealed and proved that he had paid the full \u00a3500 before receiving his acquittance. He thereby exonerated himself from any possible imputation that he had used the children's money to discharge what he owed to Dame Margery. Her obligation, on the other hand, still remained. By a final and definitive sentence in Chancery on 4 November 1556 he was completely discharged and awarded costs, and Chamberlayne's bill was dismissed.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery, Pleadings: ''Chamberlayn v Guyneth'', [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7501237 C 1/1339/16-20], and C 18/10/26; Final decree: ''Chamberlayne v Gwnyneth'' [''[[sic]]'', recte Gwyneth], ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C14514974 C 78/10/26], View original at AALT, images [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/C78/C78no10/IMG_0025.htm 0025] and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/C78/C78no10/IMG_0026.htm 0026].</ref>\n\nGwynneth resigned from St Peter's, Westcheap before 19 November 1556, when his successor, Richard Smith, was presented by George Keynsham and George Wiseman under a concessionary advowson remaining from St Alban's Abbey, and instituted by Bonner.<ref>R. Newcourt, ''Repertorium Ecclesiasticum Parochiale Londinense'' (Benjamin Motte, for Baker, Tooke, Parker, Bowyer and Clements, London 1708), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9bNQAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA522#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 522] (Google).</ref> His last publication ''A playne demonstration of Iohn Frithes lacke of witte and learnynge in his vnderstandynge of holie scripture and of the olde holy doctours, in the blessed sacrament of the aulter'', printed by Thomas Powell in London, appeared in 1557.<ref>Full text at [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A02426.0001.001?view=toc Umich/eebo] (Open).</ref> His theological dialogues have been described as \"excruciatingly pedantic\".<ref>V. Westbrook and E. Evenden, ''Catholic Renewal and Protestant Resistance in Marian England'' (Routledge, Abingdon 2016),  [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w2CrCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 160] (Google).</ref>\n\n;Death\nGwynneth appears to have died around the end of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]]'s reign: the death is placed before 1 December 1558 in Episcopal Registers.<ref>Mayer and Walters, ''Correspondence of Reginald Pole, Biographical Companion'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_daeDoWdQ0cC&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 236], citing Lincoln Record Office, Episcopal Register 28, fol. 147 recto; ''LI2'', no. 653.</ref> He is described as deceased (\"defunctus\"<ref>\"...Johnis Gwinneth Clerici nuper vicarii de Luton diocesse Lincolnie provicieque Cantuarie defuncti\", i.e., \"...of John Gwynneth, clerk, late vicar of Luton in the diocese of Lincoln and the province of Canterbury, deceased\".</ref>) in [[Hilary term]] 1558/59, when his [[administrator (law)|administrators]] and next of kin (\"proximi consanguinei\"), his nephew Edward Awpart (jr) and his niece Elizabeth Awpart, wife of George Keynsham of [[Tempsford]], Bedfordshire,<ref>[[High Sheriff of Bedfordshire]], 1577\u201378. See Will of George Keynsham (P.C.C. 1592, Harrington quire), making Stephen Vaughan jnr his overseer.</ref> pressed a claim for debt of \u00a340 against Sir Thomas Rotherham of [[Someries Castle|Someries]], Luton.<ref>L. Jack, 'Revd. John Gwinneth, c. 1510 - c. 1563', [http://www.gwinnett.me.uk/characters/revd-john-gwinneth-c-1510-to-c-1559 Gwinnett Family History website], reciting The National Archives, Common Pleas Ref: CP 40/1178 m.902 dorse, with transcript and translation by David Bethell. (Verified at [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/Eliz/CP40no1178/bCP40no1178dorses/IMG_0738.htm AALT]).</ref> At Stuchbury his successor Laurence Washington entered the living (vacant by his death) in May 1559.<ref>Baker, ''History and Antiquities of Northampton'', I, 691.</ref> \n\nTwo factors have been taken to suggest that he survived into the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]].<ref>J.J. Jones, 'Gwynneth, John, (?1490-?1562), offeiriad Pabyddol a cherddor', ''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig'' [https://bywgraffiadur.cymru/article/c-GWYN-JOH-1490? Online]. J.P.D. Cooper, 'Gwynneth [Gwynedd], John (d. 1560x63), composer and polemicist', Oxford Dictionary of National Biography (2004).</ref> One is the story of his imprisonment: the other is the late record of a suit brought in his name before the Star Chamber for the recovery of the possessions of \"the late Dr Glyn\" at Clynnog Fawr in [[Llanwnda, Gwynedd|Llanwnda]] and [[Llanfaglan]].<ref>J.J. Jones, 'A Welsh Catholic controversialist', in ''Journal of the Welsh Bibliographical Society'' Vol. V part 2 (1938) [https://cylchgronau.llyfrgell.cymru/view/1226390/1227945/30#?xywh=-391%2C243%2C2943%2C2150 pp. 90-93] (Llyfrgell Genedlaethol Cymru), citing I. ab O. Edwards, ''A Catalogue of Star Chamber Proceedings relating to Wales'' (1929), p. 31.</ref> If this refers to Dr William Glyn of Glynllifon, Gwynneth's predecessor at Clynnog Fawr (who died in 1537), the grounds of the suit need not post-date the death (in 1558) of the more famous Dr William Glyn, Bishop of Bangor.\n\n==Nephews and nieces==\nAs executor, Gwynneth had responsibility for the estates of the children of the two marriages of his sister Margaret Gwynneth (also called Margery), who died in 1544. By her first marriage, to Edward Awpart, Girdler of London (died 1532), her children were:\n\n* Elizabeth Awpart, married (by Easter term 1557<ref>'Yorkshire Fines: 1557', in F. Collins (ed.), ''Feet of Fines of the Tudor Period [Yorks]: Part 1, 1486-1571'' (Leeds, 1887), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/feet-of-fines-yorks/vol1/pp199-210 pp. 199-210] (British History Online).</ref>) George Keynsham of [[Bygrave]], Hertfordshire and Tempsford, Bedfordshire (died 1593).<ref>Will of George Keynsham (P.C.C. 1592, Harrington quire). See Bedfordshire Records, ref. WY 1-444, [http://bedsarchivescat.bedford.gov.uk/Details/archive/110245966 \"Admin/biog history\"], (Bedfordshire Archives Service Catalogue).</ref><ref>It is unclear if she is the same wife Elizabeth who survived George and married Francis Gill of London: 'Parishes: Tempsford', in W. Page (ed.), ''A History of the County of Bedford'', Vol. 2 (VCH/HMSO, London 1908), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/beds/vol2/pp251-255 pp. 251-55] (British History Online).</ref>\n* Ann Awpart, living 1532.\n* Joan Awpart, married Edward Mildmay (elder brother of Sir Walter Mildmay) in 1548. Both died in 1548-1549.\n* Edward Awpart, one of the signatories to the testimonial provided by the [[English College, Rome#History|English Hospice in Rome]] for [[Thomas Sackville, 1st Earl of Dorset|Thomas Sackville]] at the time of his visit to Rome in 1564.<ref>H.D.G., 'Four Papers Relative to the Visit of Thomas Sackville', ''Miscellanea II: Publications of the Catholic Record Society'' vol. 2 (Society/Arden Press, London 1906 [https://archive.org/details/miscellanea02cath/page/n17 pp. 1-4] and [https://archive.org/details/miscellanea02cath/page/n11 Frontispiece] (Internet Archive).</ref> In 1572 Sir Thomas Ragland raised a mortgage on lands in Glamorganshire from George Keynsham and Edward Alporte, which led to a suit in Chancery between Ragland and Keynsham in 1578.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Exchequer: refs. [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C5922265 E 133/10/1565]; [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C5922262 E 133/10/1562]; [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C5921137 E 133/3/444] (Discovery Catalogue).</ref>\n* Susan Awpart, living 1532.\n\nBy her second marriage, 1532-33, to Stephen Vaughan (died 1549), her children were:\n\n* [[Anne Locke|Anne Vaughan]] (1534 - c. 1590), poet, married (1: c. 1549) Henry Lock (a younger son of Sir [[William Lok]]), who died in 1571;<ref>Will of Henry Lok (P.C.C. 1571, Holney quire).</ref> (2: 1572) [[Edward Dering (priest)|Edward Dering]] (died 1576); (3: 1576) Richard Prowse of Exeter. She was the author of ''A Meditation of a Penitent Sinner'' (1560).<ref>S.M. Felch, 'The Exemplary Anne Vaughan Lock,' in J. Harris and E. Scott-Baumann, ''The Intellectual Culture of Puritan Women, 1558\u20131680'' (Palgrave Macmillan, New York 2010), pp. 15-27.</ref>\n* Stephen Vaughan (b. 1537 - will proved 1605), entered [[Gonville Hall, Cambridge]], 1554; [[Inner Temple]], 1564.<ref>J. and J.A. Venn, ''Alumni Cantabrigienses'', Part 1 vol. 4 (Cambridge University Press, 1927), [https://archive.org/details/p1alumnicantabri04univuoft/page/294 p. 295] (Internet Archive)</ref> He married Jane, daughter of Richard Stroud (Strode), of [[Newnham (Old)|(Old) Newnham]], Devon.<ref>'Vaughan', in J.J. Howard (ed.), ''The Visitation of London, A.D. 1633, 1634, 1635'', 2 Vols, Harleian Society XV, XVII (1880/1883), II, [https://archive.org/details/publicationshar08socigoog/page/n322 p. 309] (Internet Archive).</ref> Stephen was an overseer in the will of George Keynsham, 1593. They had three daughters and three sons, of whom the eldest, Stephen, was considered insane, having been \"corrupted in religion\".<ref>Lambeth Palace Library, MS 3470 (Fairhurst Papers), [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/f7a3f182-0e5e-4baa-97c5-40568372f133 fol. 113] (Discovery Catalogue).</ref> The youngest son, Rowland Vaughan, inherited.<ref>Will of Stephen Vaughan of St Mary without Bishopsgate (P.C.C. 1605, Hayes quire).</ref>\n* Jane Vaughan (died c. 1610), recusant, married (by c. 1555) Thomas Wiseman, son of John Wiseman of Felsted.<ref>W.C. Metcalfe (ed.), ''The Visitations of Essex'', 2 Vols, Harleian Society XIII-XIV (1878/1879), 'Wiseman (1) (1612)' at [https://archive.org/details/visitationsofess13metc/page/324 pp. 324-25]; 'Wiseman (1) (1634)' at [https://archive.org/details/visitationsofess13metc/page/526 pp. 526-28].</ref> They had several children, including four sons (the heir being Sir William Wiseman), and four daughters of whom two became Abbess and Prioress of the [[Syon Abbey#Peregrination|Bridgettine house at Lisbon]], and two were nuns at St Ursula's of Louvain. Jane was imprisoned and condemned for recusancy, but the sentence against her was remitted.<ref>See Hamilton, ''Chronicle of St Monica's'', [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive); Ford, ''Genealogical Findings from the Diary of Thomas Cartwright'', I.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n[[File:John Herford, St Albans, printer's mark 1536.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Printer's mark from Gwynneth's \"Confutacyon\" of 1536.]]\nHis works are:\n* 'My Love mourneth,' music and words in a book, ''Bassus,'' beginning \"In this boke are conteynyd xx songes\", 1530, obl. 4to.<ref>''Book of XX Songes'' (1530), \"Bassus\", fols 30v [https://repository.royalholloway.ac.uk/items/c6584bb2-3d90-62b2-88a2-63f62493baa0/1/treenav.jsp?tempwn.b=close to 34v] (Royal Holloway digital). Text in E. Rickert, ''Ancient English Christmas Carols, 1400 to 1700'' (Chatto & Windus, London 1910), [https://archive.org/details/ancientenglishch00rickuoft/page/140 pp. 140-42], 156 (Internet Archive).</ref>\n* ''The confutacyon of the fyrst parte of Frythes boke, with a disputacyon before, whether it be possyble for any heretike to know that hymselfe is one or not, And also another, whether it be wors to denye directely more or lesse of the fayth,'' St. Albans, 1536, 16mo.\n* ''A brief Declaration of the notable Victory given of God to oure soueraygne lady, quene Marye, made in the church of Luton, the 23 July, in the first yere of her gracious reign,'' London [1554], 16mo.\n* ''A Declaration of the State wherein all Heretickes dooe leade their lives; and also of their continuall indever and propre fruictes, which beginneth in the 38 Chapiter, and so to thende of the Woorke,'' London, 1554, 4to.\n* ''A Manifeste Detection of the notable falshed of that Part of Frythes boke which he termeth his Foundation, and bosteth it to be invincible,'' 2nd edition, London, 1554, 8vo.\n* ''A Playne Demonstration of John Frithes lacke of witte and learnynge in his understandynge of holie Scripture, and of the olde holy doctours, in the Blessed Sacrament of the Aulter, newly set foorthe,'' London, 1557, 4to, written in the form of a dialogue.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{nobots|deny=InternetArchiveBot}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gwynneth, John}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Welsh religious writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh musicians]]\n[[Category:Welsh Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century Welsh people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:16th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Welsh clergyman and musical composer}}\nDr '''John Gwynneth''' (or Guinete) ([[Floruit|fl.]] 1511-1557), was a clergyman of Welsh nationality originating from [[Gwynedd]], and was a [[composer]] of religious and liturgical vocal music.<ref>J.P.D. Cooper, 'Gwynneth [Gwynedd], John (d. 1560x63), composer and polemicist', Oxford Dictionary of National Biography (2004).</ref> He held benefices in England in [[Northamptonshire]], [[Bedfordshire]] and [[London]], and in North Wales at [[Clynnog Fawr]].<ref>C.F. Mayer and T.B. Walters, ''The Correspondence of Reginald Pole. 4: A Biographical Companion: the British Isles'', St Andrews Studies in Medieval History (Ashgate, Aldershot 2008), pp. [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_daeDoWdQ0cC&pg=PA235#v=onepage&q&f=false 235], [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_daeDoWdQ0cC&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q&f=false 236] (Google).</ref> Although he was a [[polemic|polemicist]] for the Catholic faith, he maintained his ministry through the reigns of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] and [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]], and was brother-in-law and [[executor]] of [[Stephen Vaughan (merchant)|Stephen Vaughan]] (a supporter of the [[English Reformation]]). He is principally remembered, with [[Thomas Tallis]] and others, as one of the leading exponents of early [[Tudor period]] [[polyphony]].\n\n==Young life==\n;Origins and education\nJohn Gwynneth was the son of Dafydd ap Llewelyn ap Ithel of Castellmarch, [[Llanengan]], [[Ll\u0177n Peninsula|Ll\u0177n]], [[Caernarfonshire]]:<ref>According to Arthur Bulkeley, Dafydd was brother to Robert ap Llewelyn ap Ithel of Castellmarch, ancestor of [[William Jones (judge)|Sir William Jones, knight]] (1566-1640). The relationship is explained by Professor A.H. Dodd, 'Jones, Sir William (1566-1640), judge',''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig'' (1959), [https://bywgraffiadur.cymru/article/c3-JONE-WIL-1566 online].</ref> it was claimed that he was of the Welsh royal blood.<ref>Dom A. Hamilton, O.S.B. (ed.), ''The Chronicle of the English Augustinian Canonesses Regular of the Lateran, at St. Monica's in Louvain, 1548-1625'', 2 vols (Sands & Co., Edinburgh/London 1904), I, [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive).</ref> [[Anthony Wood (antiquary)|Anthony \u00e0 Wood]] remarks that he had great natural abilities but little or nothing to support him in his studies at [[Oxford University]]. He was therefore sponsored by a churchman (\"an ecclesiastical [[Gaius Maecenas|Mec\u00e6nas]]\") who hoped that he would become a useful writer against the opponents of Roman Catholicism. Wood adds that in his youth he was well versed in polite literature, and later familiarized himself with the writings and arguments for and against the doctrines of [[Martin Luther|Luther]] and [[Huldrych Zwingli|Zwingli]].<ref>A. \u00e0 Wood, ed. P. Bliss, ''Athenae Oxonienses, with the Fasti'', 3rd Edition with additions, 3 vols (F.C. & J. Rivington, etc., London/Oxford 1813-1817), I, [https://archive.org/details/athenaeoxoniense01wooduoft/page/n323 pp. 246-48] (Internet Archive).</ref> \n\nHowever there is no record that he completed a bachelor's degree. From his declaration to the University made in 1531 (below), it appears that from around 1510 he was active in the composition and theory of polyphonic music. Since he became a secular priest, this experience was perhaps gained in Oxford and then or thereafter as a secular chaplain attached to a religious house possessing a choir, though he did not enter a formal order. In 1522, a clerk, he was owed \u00a318 (an old debt) by the [[St Albans Cathedral|Abbey of St Albans]].<ref>29 September 1522, item 2583, 'St Albans', in J.S. Brewer (ed.), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 3: 1519-1523 (HMSO London, 1867), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol3/pp1084-1101 pp. 1084-1101, at p. 1098] (British History Online).</ref> When still an [[acolyte]] he was collated, apparently by the [[St Andrew's Priory, Northampton|Cluniac priory of St Andrew]], [[Northampton]],<ref>For which see 'Houses of Cluniac monks: The priory of St Andrew, Northampton', in R.M. Serjeantson and W.R.D. Adkins (eds), ''A History of the County of Northampton'', Vol. 2 (VCH/HMSO London, 1906), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/northants/vol2/pp102-109 pp. 102-09] (British History Online).</ref> to the [[benefice]] of Stuchbury or Stotesbury (near [[Sulgrave]]), Northamptonshire in December 1528, which he held until his death.<ref>G. Baker, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Northampton'' (John Bowyer Nichols, London 1822-1830), I, [https://archive.org/details/HistoryAndAntiquitiesOfTheCountyOfNorthamptonBakerVol1/page/n693 p. 691] (Internet Archive).</ref> Stuchbury was attached to the College of [[All Saints' Church, Northampton|All Hallows, Northampton]],<ref>J. Caley (ed.), ''Valor Ecclesiasticus Temp. Henry VIII'', IV (Commissioners, 1821), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7EfvuwaAb6MC&pg=PA320#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 320] (Google).</ref> which had an important medieval choir.\n\n;Musical composer\nJohn Gwynneth is particularly noteworthy as an early Tudor composer of music.<ref>W.H. Grattan Flood, ''Early Tudor Composers'' (Oxford University Press/Humphrey Milford, London 1925), pp. 108-10.</ref> By December 1531 he had achieved a remarkable output, at which time he made a formal approach to the University of Oxford: <blockquote>\"John Gwynneth a secular priest, who had spent twelve years in the praxis and theory of music, and had composed all the [[antiphon|responses]] of the whole year in division-song,<ref>I.e. [[polyphony]], \"in cantis chrispis aut fractis, ut aiunt\", S. Harper, ''Music in Welsh Culture before 1650: a Study of the Principal Sources'' (Ashgate 2007/Routledge, London and New York 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FzQrDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT304#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 283-84] (Google).</ref> and had published many masses in the said song, supplicated that these his labours might enable him to be admitted to the praxis of music. This being granted conditionally that he compose one mass against the act following, he supplicated again that whereas he had spent 20 years in the praxis and theory of music, and had published three masses of five parts, and five masses of four, as also certain symphonas, antiphonas, and divers songs for the use of the church, he might be admitted to proceed in the faculty of music; which desire of his being granted, conditionally that he pay to the university, on the day of his admission, 20 pence, he was forthwith licensed to proceed.\"<ref>A. \u00e0 Wood, ed. P. Bliss, ''Fasti Oxonienses, or Annals of the University of Oxford'', New Edition, Part I: 1500-1640, (F.C. & J. Rivington etc, London 1815), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=U1ruEakGAKwC&pg=PA1531#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 86] (Google)</ref></blockquote>\n\nThus he was awarded the degree of [[Doctor of Music]].<ref>C.W. Boase, ''Register of the University of Oxford'' Vol. I: 1449-63; 1505-71 (Oxford Historical Society/Clarendon Press, Oxford 1885), [https://archive.org/details/registerofuniver01univuoft/page/166 p. 167] (Internet Archive)</ref><ref>T. Cooper, 'Gwynneth, John, (fl. 1557), catholic divine and musician', ''Dictionary of National Biography'' (1885-1900), [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Gwynneth,_John_(DNB00) Vol. 23].</ref> He was one of the composers whose work was included in the collection printed in 1530, called the \"Book of XX Songes\",<ref>See an introduction in J. Milsom, 'Songs and Society in Early Tudor London', in I. Fenlon (ed.), ''Early Music History'', Vol. 17, Studies in Medieval and Early Modern Music (Cambridge University Press 1997), pp. 282-85.</ref> of which only the volume of bass lines (''Bassus'') survives.<ref>'My Love mourneth' (commencing 'And I mankynd') in ''Book of XX Songes'' (1530), \"Bassus\", fols 30v [https://repository.royalholloway.ac.uk/items/c6584bb2-3d90-62b2-88a2-63f62493baa0/1/treenav.jsp?tempwn.b=close to 34v] (Royal Holloway digital). Text in E. Rickert, ''Ancient English Christmas Carols, 1400 to 1700'' (Chatto & Windus, London 1910), [https://archive.org/details/ancientenglishch00rickuoft/page/140 pp. 140-42], 156 (Internet Archive).</ref> [[Thomas Morley]], in his ''Plaine and Easie Introduction to Practicall Musicke'' (1597), lists \"Io. Guinneth\" among the ''English'' practitioners whose works he has diligently perused, for finding the true use of the [[Mode (music)|Moods]].<ref>T. Morley, ''A Plaine and Easie Introduction to Practicall Musicke set downe in forme of a Dialogue'' (Peter Short, London 1597), [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A07753.0001.001/1:20?rgn=div1;view=fulltext List of Authorities] (Umich/eebo - Open).</ref>\n\n;Family connections\nJohn Gwynneth's sister Margaret was firstly the wife of Edward Awpart (Alporte<ref>No doubt a representative of the Alport family of [[Cannock]], Staffordshire.</ref>), citizen and [[Worshipful Company of Girdlers|Girdler]] of London in the parish of [[St Mary le Bow]], who originated from [[Penkridge]] in [[Staffordshire]]. In 1524 Awpart took the lease on premises called \"The Three Leggs\" in St Mary le Bow from St Bartholomew's Priory.<ref>D.J. Keene and V. Harding, 'St. Mary le Bow 104/32', in ''Historical Gazetteer of London Before the Great Fire'', Cheapside; Parishes of All Hallows Honey Lane, St Martin Pomary, St Mary Le Bow, St Mary Colechurch and St Pancras Soper Lane (Centre for Metropolitan History, London 1987), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-gazetteer-pre-fire/pp346-350 pp. 346-50], after note 6 (British History Online).</ref> The Awparts had five children, Elizabeth, Anne, Joan, Edward and Susan, who were all unmarried at the time of their father's death in 1532. By his will dated 24 June 1532 Awpart, who mentions a debt to his hostess at the \"Viniarde in [[Antwerp|Andwarpe]]\", appointed his widow and \"Sir\" John Gwynneth<ref>\"Sir\" is a usual title for a secular priest at this date, not denoting knighthood.</ref> his executors, making a gift of \u00a36.13s.4d to John, and both were sworn to probate (John in person, Margaret by attorney) on 6 July 1532. In this will Awpart refers to his wife's mother by the name Joan White.<ref>Will of Edward Awpart, \"Girdler\" (mis-written \"Gardener\" in Discovery Catalogue of TNA (UK)) of London (P.C.C. 1532, Thower quire, m/film imgs 237-38): PROB 11/24/211 and PROB 11/24/220.</ref><ref>\"White\" is the English counterpart of the Welsh name \"Gwyn\".</ref> He appointed Thomas Marbury, [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers|Haberdasher]], as Overseer, who in the same year, as executor to John Maltby, ran into difficulties with the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|Mercers' Company]].<ref>A.F. Sutton, ''The Mercery of London: Trade, Goods and People, 1130\u20131578'' (Ashgate, 2005/Routledge, Abingdon 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=epyoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT495#v=onepage&q&f=false pt. 495] (Google).</ref>\n\nMargaret Gwynneth then (by 1533) re-married to [[Stephen Vaughan (merchant)|Stephen Vaughan]], Governor of the [[Company of Merchant Adventurers of London|Merchant Adventurers]] (1534) and royal agent and secretary in Antwerp. Vaughan in 1536 assumed the lease on \"The Three Leggs\", and, following the priory's dissolution, in 1540 it was granted by the Crown to him and Margaret for life, and in remainder to their male issue.<ref>Keene and Harding, ''Historical Gazetteer'', [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-gazetteer-pre-fire/pp346-350 pp. 346-50] at notes 6-10 (British History Online).</ref><ref>'379. Grants in December 1540, no. 44', in J. Gairdner and R.H. Brodie (eds), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 16: 1540-1541 (HMSO, London 1898), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol16/pp162-178 pp. 175-76] (British History Online).</ref> Vaughan's sister Mawdlyn was the wife of the London [[Grocer]] William Pratt, after whose death in 1539<ref>Will of William Pratt, Grocer of London (P.C.C. 1539, Dyngeley quire). Not to be confused with the Draper of the same name and similar date.</ref> she married Pratt's well-travelled apprentice [[Thomas Lodge (Lord Mayor of London)|Thomas Lodge]]. Vaughan, who could call upon the help of [[Thomas Cromwell]], found a place at Court for his wife Margaret as silkwoman in service to [[Anne Boleyn]].<ref>R.M. Warnicke, ''The Rise and Fall of Anne Boleyn: Family Politics at the Court of Henry VIII'' (Cambridge University Press 1991), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_iUIzcXV4toC&pg=PA136#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 136] (Google).</ref><ref>S.M. Felch (ed.), ''The Collected Works of Anne Vaughan Lock'', Arizona Center for Medieval and Renaissance Studies in conjunction with Renaissance English Text Society (Tempe, AZ, 1999), pp. xxv\u2013xxvi.</ref> With him she had further children ([[Anne Locke|Anne]], Stephen and Jane), dying in 1544.<ref>M.K. Dale, 'Vaughan, Stephen (by 1502-49), of St. Mary-le-Bow, London', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509-1558'' (from Boydell and Brewer, 1982), [https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/vaughan-stephen-1502-49 History of Parliament online].</ref> Marbury died in 1545,<ref>Will of Thomas Merbury, haberdasher (P.C.C. 1545, Pynnyng quire).</ref> leaving John Gwynneth with sole responsibility to administer the Awpart estate.\n\n==Opportunity and controversy==\n;Stoke sub Hamdon, and Luton - writing against Frith\n[[File:StMarysLuton.jpg|thumb|right|250px|St Mary's church, Luton]]\nThe King presented Gwynneth to the collegiate church of [[Stoke sub Hamdon Priory]], [[Somerset]], in September 1534, at the Crown's disposal on the death of John Glyn.<ref>'Grants in September 1534: 3. John Gwynneth, clerk', in J. Gairdner (ed.), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 7: 1534 (London 1883), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol7/pp462-475 p. 474] (British History Online).</ref> He published his first writings against the doctrines of [[John Frith]], as ''The confutacyon of the fyrst parte of Frythes boke: with a dysputacyon before whether it be possyble for any heretike to know that hym selfe is one or not. And also an other, whether it be wors to denye directely more or lesse of the fayth.'' This was printed at [[St Albans]] in 1536,<ref>J. Ames, ed. W. Herbert, ''Typographical Antiquities, or, An Historical Account of the Origin and Progress of Printing in Great Britain and Ireland'', Volume 1 part 3 (London, 1785-1790), [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_s2C8MeKuXPwC/page/n127 pp. 1430-36] (Internet Archive).</ref> under the auspices of the last abbot,<ref>W. Wizeman (SJ), ''The Theology and Spirituality of Mary Tudor's Church'' (Ashgate, 2006/Routledge, London & New York 2017), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SmdQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 39] (Google).</ref> three years after Frith's execution as a [[heretic]]. Gwynneth was presented to the vicariate of [[Luton]], [[Bedfordshire]] (\"the best preferment in the Abbey of St Albans\") by Stephen Vaughan as assignee of Edward Awpart senior by grant of St Albans Abbey, in December 1537,<ref>Mayer and Walters, ''Correspondence of Reginald Pole, Biographical Companion'',  p. 236.</ref> where he continued his ministrations for twenty years, until around 1558.<ref>H. Cobbe, ''Luton Church - Historical and Descriptive'' (George Bell and Sons/F. Hockliffe, London/Luton 1899),  [https://archive.org/details/lutonchurchhisto00cobbuoft/page/n199 pp. 173-85] (Internet Archive) and [https://archive.org/details/lutonchurchhist00cobbgoog/page/n295 p. 259]. A Catalogue of Gwynneth's works is at Appendix BI, [https://archive.org/details/lutonchurchhisto00cobbuoft/page/n663 pp. 612-16] (Internet Archive).</ref> \n\n;Clynnog Fawr\nIn October 1537 Gwynneth was presented by [[Henry VIII of England|the King]] to the provostship or rectory ''[[Sinecure|sine cura]]'' of [[Clynnog Fawr]] (in the [[Ll\u0177n Peninsula|Ll\u0177n]] south of Caernarfon), with the chapels and church of [[Llangeinwen]] and [[Llangaffo]] ([[Anglesey]]), upon the death of Dr. William Glyn of [[Glynllifon]].<ref>'Grants, October 1537: 29. John Gwynneth, clerk', in J. Gairdner (ed.), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol. 12 Part 2: June-December 1537 (London, 1891), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol12/no2/pp345-355 p. 353] (British History Online). This Dr Glyn is not to be confused with the [[William Glyn (bishop)|Bishop of Bangor]] of that name, who died in 1558.</ref> [[John Capon]], [[Bishop of Bangor]] (1534\u201339), would not admit him, instituting instead Gregory Williamson, a child nephew of Thomas Cromwell's, to the living.<ref>Wood, ed. Bliss, ''Athenae Oxonienses, with the Fasti'', I (1813), [https://archive.org/details/athenaeoxoniense01wooduoft/page/n323 pp. 246-47] (Internet Archive).</ref> [[Arthur Bulkeley]], then [[Prebendary]] of Clynnog Fechan at Llangeinwen, had been displaced thereby at Cromwell's prompting.<ref>Wood, ed. Bliss, ''Athenae Oxonienses, with the Fasti'', II (1815), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MxUTbAj-58kC&pg=PA681#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 767-68] (Google).</ref> Gwynneth brought a writ of ''[[quare impedit]]'' against Bishop Capon and Williamson, but in 1539 Capon was succeeded by [[John Bird (bishop)|John Bird]] (1539\u201341), and in July 1540 Cromwell fell. In October 1540 [[Thomas Cranmer|Archbishop Cranmer]] granted a dispensation to Gwynneth to occupy the perpetual vicarage of [[Enstone]], Oxfordshire pending its transfer from the [[Diocese of Lincoln]] to that of [[Diocese of Oxford|Oxford]] in 1542.<ref>Clergy of the Church of England database, Dispensation Appointment Record ID: [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/DisplayDispensation.jsp?CDBDispenID=3925 3925]; Location: (Parish) Church: Enstone, Location Record ID: [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/locations/index.jsp?locUnitKey=1282 1189].</ref>\n\n[[File:Eglwys Beuno Sant, Clynnog Fawr, south side.jpg|thumb|right|250px|St Beuno's church, Clynnog Fawr]]\nIn July 1541 Gwynneth renewed his suit, now against Bird, who however was translated to [[Bishop of Chester|Chester]] in August 1541. In October, during the vacancy in the see of Bangor, Gwynneth (described as \"Magister\", and \"sacellanus\" or royal chaplain) had himself instituted to Clynnog Fawr by the Commissary of the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]].<ref>Church of England Clergy database, CCEd Appointment Evidence Record [http://db.theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/DisplayAppointment.jsp?CDBAppRedID=288881 ID: 288881].</ref> Arthur Bulkeley became Bishop of Bangor in November 1541, but before he came into residence Gwynneth had obtained a [[Default judgement|judgement in default]]. There followed a great controversy between Gwynneth and Bulkeley<ref>'Petition of Bishop Bulkeley' (Bangor Cathedral Archives), in W. Hughes, ''Diocesan Histories: Bangor'' (S.P.C.K., London 1911), [https://archive.org/details/bangor00commgoog/page/n196 pp. 190-92] (Internet Archive).</ref> in the [[Court of Star Chamber]],<ref>'Interrogatories: John Gwyneth', The National Archives (UK), ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/record?catid=-3190770&catln=7 E 321/46/205]. See also [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C3977076 STAC 2/25/139].</ref> and in 1543 Gwynneth won judgement in his favour.<ref>T. Hearne (ed.), ''Thomae Caii (Collegii Universitatis Regnante Elizabetha Magistri) Vindiciae Antiquitatis Academiae Oxoniensis contra Joannem Caium Cantabrigiensem'', 2 vols (E theatro Sheldoniensis, Oxford 1733), II, p. 666.</ref> \n\nHaving thus asserted the King's right of patronage over that of the Bishop of Bangor, he then, on 21 January, 36 Henry VIII (1544/45) at St Mary le Bow, demised the Rectory of Clynnog Fawr to Dafydd ap Robert alias Gryffyth of Merthyr, Caernarfonshire, gent., for nine years, he paying John \u00a357.14s.6d for each year that he occupied it.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Common Pleas, CP 40/1157, m. 509 front, [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/M/CP40no1157/aCP40no1157fronts/IMG_1043.htm AALT image 1043].</ref> In the following year however, it became likely that the provostship would be subject to Crown resumption under the Act for Chantries. Vaughan appealed to [[William Paget, 1st Baron Paget|Lord Paget]] on Gwynneth's behalf, explaining that he had spent 8 years in continual suit and expense in the law over it, at his personal cost of 500 marks.<ref>'26. Vaughan to Paget, 7 January 1546', in J. Gairdner and R.H. Brodie (eds), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'' Vol. 21 Part 1: January-August 1546,  (London, 1908), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol21/no1/pp10-27 p. 13] (British History Online).</ref>\n\n==Challenge and responsibility==\n;St Peter, Westcheap\nMeanwhile, on 19 September 1543, at the presentation of [[Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden|Thomas Audley]] (died 1544), he was instituted by [[Bishop Bonner]] to the rectory of [[St Peter, Westcheap]] in the city of London (historically a St Albans benefice).<ref>R. Newcourt, ''Repertorium Ecclesiasticum Parochiale Londinense'' (Benjamin Motte, for Baker, Tooke, Parker, Bowyer and Clements, London 1708), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9bNQAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA522#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 522] (Google).</ref> The Louvain narrative states that he had formerly been curate there.<ref>Hamilton, ''Chronicle of St Monica's'', [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive).</ref> At St Peter's he followed in the footsteps of [[Thomas Goodrich]] and [[Richard Gwent]], both very advanced churchmen. He held this benefice through the reign of [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] (possibly with some interruption), and through that of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]]. During Edward's reign the old Faringdon chantry was done away with, the church fraternity was dissolved, the rood was taken down, the altars were replaced with tables and the paraphernalia of the Catholic ritual were removed from St Peter's.<ref>W. Sparrow Simpson, 'On the parish of St. Peter Cheap, in the City of London, from 1392 to 1633', ''Journal of the British Archaeological Association'' Original Series vol. XXIV (1868), [https://archive.org/details/journalofbritish24brit/page/248 pp. 248-68], at pp. 250-51 (Internet Archive).</ref> \n\nAs the [[Chantry#Abolition of Chantries Acts, 1545 and 1547|dissolution of the chantries]] proceeded, in March 1548 Sir [[Walter Mildmay]], one of the two Surveyors-general of the [[Court of Augmentations]], was appointed a Commissioner for the sale of chantry lands. Gwynneth's first cousin, John Roberts of Castellmarch, was [[Sheriff of Caernarvonshire]] in that year, whose son Griffith ap John (sometime in the service of [[John Dudley, 1st Duke of Northumberland|John Dudley, Earl Warwick]]) was appointed Constable of [[Conwy Castle]] in 1549.<ref>Dodd, 'Jones, Sir William', ''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig''.</ref> \n\n;Executor and matchmaker\nIn October 1548 Gwynneth's niece Joan Awparte, Vaughan's stepdaughter, married Edward Myldemay,<ref>J.L. Chester and G.J. Armytage, ''Allegations for Marriage Licences issued from the Faculty Office of the Archbishop of Canterbury at London 1542 to 1869'', Harleian Society XXIV (1886), [https://archive.org/details/marriagelicence00chester/page/12 p. 13] (Internet Archive).</ref> elder brother of Sir Walter. The marriage was brief, for Edward, who had become [[Worshipful Company of Mercers|citizen and Mercer]] in October 1541,<ref>H.A. St.J. Mildmay, ''A Brief Memoir of the Mildmay Family'' (John Lane, The Bodley Head/Private, London/New York 1913), [https://archive.org/details/briefmemoirofmil00mild/page/n25 p. 14] (Internet Archive).</ref> made his will on 22 March 1549, in which he gives \"to Elizabeth Awparte, sister to my late wife Johanna, \u00a320 which is owing me by my uncle the vicar of Luton.\" (Possibly this was money owing by Gwynneth upon the marriage settlement, since he, as the surviving executor of Edward Awparte senr, held the portions of the Awparte children until their age of 21 or else were married, a term now elapsing.<ref>Will of Edward Awparte, Girdler of London (P.C.C. 1532).</ref>) Myldemay makes gifts of various of his wife's effects: the will was proved by Sir Walter Mildmay on 3 April 1549.<ref>Will of Edwarde Myldemay, Gentleman of London (P.C.C. 1549, Populwell quire).</ref> \n\nStephen Vaughan made Gwynneth his executor at his death in December 1549, leaving him in charge of \"The Three Leggs\" in Westcheap with a room for his own lodgings and the management of the premises on behalf of Vaughan's daughters for the space of nine years. Vaughan's brother-in-law Thomas Lodge, husband of Mawdlyn (who died in 1548), and John Griffith were his overseers. (Lodge had of late conducted secret surveillance for Vaughan overseas.<ref>J. Gairdner and R.H. Brodie (eds), ''Letters and Papers, Foreign and Domestic, Henry VIII'', Vol XX Part 1: January-July 1545 (HMSO 1905), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/letters-papers-hen8/vol20/no1/pp101-114 p. 107, item 250] (British History Online).</ref>) Gwynneth swore to probate on 26 February 1549/50.<ref>Will of Stephen Vaughan (P.C.C. 1550, Coode quire). 'Inquisition post mortem: Stephen Vaughan', in G.S. Fry (ed.), ''Abstracts of Inquisitiones Post Mortem For the City of London'', Part 1 (London 1896), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/abstract/no1/pp78-95 pp. 78\u201395] (British History Online).</ref> In that connection he had the task of delivering to Sir John Williams some \u00a3305 owing to the King from Vaughan's accounts as Under-Treasurer of the Tower Mint.<ref>J.R. Dasent (ed.), ''Acts of the Privy Council of England'', New Series III: 1550\u20131552 (HMSO 1891), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112119573936;view=1up;seq=348 p. 308] (Hathi Trust).</ref>\n \nA notice of Gwynneth's niece Jane Vaughan, written upon family authority in 1632, states that Gwynneth was \"a long time kept in prison when heresy came in\", and thereafter arranged Jane's marriage to (Thomas) Wiseman,<ref>Hamilton, ''Chronicle of St Monica's'', [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive). The source, derived from living tradition, is explicit that John Gwynneth was the uncle of Jane Wiseman the recusant. C. Walker, 'Wiseman [n\u00e9e Vaughan], Jane (d. 1610)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (2004) gives an incorrect parentage.</ref> (son of John Wiseman of [[Felsted]], Essex (died 1559/60)<ref>Wizeman, ''The Theology and Spirituality of Mary Tudor's Church'', p. 36. Parentage confused in S.M. Thorpe/R.J.W. Swales, 'Wiseman, John (by 1515-58), of Great Canfield, Essex', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509-1558'' (from Boydell and Brewer, 1982), [https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/wiseman-john-1515-58 History of Parliament Online].</ref>): if so this imprisonment may have been in the Edwardian period, as he barely survived into the time of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]], and the Wisemans' elder children were born during the 1550s.<ref>These connections and affiliations are fully demonstrated by G. Ford, ''Genealogical Findings from the Diary of Thomas Cartwright, Bishop of Chester (1634-1689)'', 2 vols (Queensland, 2013), I ({{ISBN|148255142X}}). See Will of John Wiseman of Felsted, Essex (P.C.C. 1560, Mellershe quire), PROB 11/43/74.</ref> Vaughan had entrusted to Gwynneth a dower of gold for the use of his children, for which, in 1551-52, they in their own names were obliged to sue the stepmother (now the wife of [[George Rolle]] of [[Stevenstone]] (d. 1552)<ref>A.D.K. Hawkyard, 'Rolle, George (by 1486-1552), of Stevenstone, Devon and London', in S.T. Bindoff (ed.), ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1509-1558'' (from Boydell and Brewer 1982), [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/rolle-george-1486-1552 History of Parliament Online]. His will was made 11 November 1552 and first proved on 9 February 1552/53: Will of George Rolle of Stevenstone, (P.C.C. 1553, Tashe quire), PROB 11/36/44 and PROB 11/36/183.</ref>) in the years immediately after their father's death:<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery: ''Vaughan v Rolles'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7500615 C 1/1319/9-11].</ref> the suit was then continued with Gwynneth's support.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery: ''Guyneth v Rolles'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7500616 C 1/1319/12-14]. ?See also ''John ?Guwill v. George Rolle and Margery'' [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C9250536 C 4/120/88].</ref> At this stage Jane Vaughan was unmarried, but her sister [[Anne Locke|Anne]] was already married to Henry Locke, son of Sir [[William Lok]].\n\n==Vindication==\n;Marian apologist\nThe accession of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]] and the aftermath of [[Wyatt's rebellion]] restored Gwynneth's doctrine. Gwynneth was at Luton on 23 July 1553 to deliver his sermon celebrating the return of a Catholic monarch, in which he did not fail to find a parallel in Mary's name with the cult of [[Mary, mother of Jesus]] so favoured in Tudor Catholicism (and so repudiated by the Edwardian Reformists).<ref>Wizeman, ''The Theology and Spirituality of Mary Tudor's Church'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SmdQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA233#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 233] (Google).</ref> It was soon published by [[John Cawood (printer)|John Cawood]] and found a ready circulation.<ref>J.N. King, 'The Account Book of a Marian Bookseller, 1553-4', ''British Library Journal'' (1987), [https://www.bl.uk/eblj/1987articles/pdf/article3.pdf pp. 33-57] (British Library pdf), at pp. 39, 42 (nos. 20 and 22).</ref> In April 1554 outside his church door in London, at the [[Eleanor cross|Cheapside Cross]], the popular mood was expressed by the spectacle of a cat hanged on a scaffold, robed like a priest with its head shaved, its bound paws holding up a morsel representing the [[Sacramental bread|Sacrament]].<ref>J. Foxe, ''The Actes and Monuments'', 1563 edition, [https://www.johnfoxe.org/index.php?realm=text&gototype=&edition=1563&pageid=1069&anchor=cat#kw Book 5, p. 1069] ('John Foxe's ''Acts and Monuments'' online'): from City Records, Journal 16, fol. 285 b.</ref> \n\nFrom the London press of [[Thomas Berthelet]] Gwynneth renewed his writings against Frith in enlarged editions, with ''{{Proper name|A manifeste detection of the notable falshed of that part of Iohn Frithes boke whiche he calleth his foundacion}}'',<ref>Full text at [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A02424.0001.001?view=toc Umich/eebo] (Open).</ref> and ''{{Proper name|A Declaration of the State wherein all Heretickes dooe leade their lives; and also of their continuall indever and propre fruictes}}'',<ref>Full text at [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo2/A02423.0001.001?view=toc Umich/eebo] (Reserved: Login only).</ref> in 1554. The title page of the latter bore the text: \"{{lang|en-emodeng|There is a waie, which semeth to a man streight, and yet the endes therof leaden to perdicion}}\" ([[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]], 16:25). The lease of nine years having expired, he brought action for a debt of \u00a367.14s.6d against Dafydd Gryffyth owing for Clynnog Fawr,<ref>The National Archives (UK), Common Pleas CP 40/1157, m. 385 dorse, AALT image [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/M/CP40no1157/bCP40no1157dorses/IMG_0662.htm 662] (2nd entry), and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/M/CP40no1157/aCP40no1157fronts/IMG_1043.htm m. 509 front] as above.</ref> and against various persons for tithes in Caernarfon and Anglesey.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery, ''Guyneth v Vaghan'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7501647 C 1/1352/77-82].</ref> Its chantry lands had passed into Crown hands.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery: ''Cobham v ap Madocke'', ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7496874 C 1/1210/21-23].</ref>\n\n;Restitutions\nIn 1555 there was a concerted effort to restore the fittings of St Peter's in Westcheap. Brick and stone altars were instated and re-dedicated, a new rood with St Mary and [[John the Apostle|St John]] forming a [[Stabat Mater (art)|Stabat Mater]] was acquired, and Father Howe was brought in to repair the organs with new springs and new tongues for the [[Flue pipe|principals]] in the bass [[Regal (instrument)|regals]]. The [[Easter Sepulchre]] was repaired, and a vigil was kept.<ref>Simpson, 'Parish of St Peter Cheap', [https://archive.org/details/journalofbritish24brit/page/256 at pp. 256-58], 264, 268. (Internet Archive).</ref> In his writings Gwynneth deplored the reformists' removal of the altar tables out of the chancel into the body of the church:<ref>Cooper, 'Gwynneth, John', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''.</ref> masonry altars made this more difficult. The charges for the hallowing of the altars are itemized in the St Peter's accounts, including the small sum of 4d for a pound of [[frankincense]].<ref>Simpson, ''Parish of St Peter Cheap'', [https://archive.org/details/journalofbritish24brit/page/262 262] (Internet Archive).</ref> The 1556 accounts show the acquisition of a book of [[homily|homilies]], three large [[Roman Ritual|Processionals]], three \"greylls\", an [[Antiphonary]], and a [[Legendary material in Christian hagiography|Legendary]], all very useful and necessary for the performance of the Roman ritual.<ref>Simpson, 'Parish of St Peter Cheap', p. 267.</ref>\n\nIn Luton in 1545 Gwynneth had acted as overseer in the will of Edward Crawley, one of his churchwardens. Crawley, with the consent of the parish, had sold off a silver [[pax (liturgical object)|pax]], a silver-gilt [[pyx]], and two double-gilt [[chalice]]s belonging to the church for \u00a315, which was to be \"{{lang|en-emodeng|ymployed about the new makynge of an ile of the churche}}\". This came to light in the Edwardian inventory of church goods, whereupon Crawley's brother took responsibility. In March 1556 the commissioners made a discretionary allowance of \u00a38.6s.8d towards the repairs, on condition that Crawley spend the remainder on church ornaments by Midsummer, for which Gwynneth gave an undertaking to the [[Bishop of Ely]]. On 10 June he was able to report to the commissioners ([[William Barnes (died 1558)|William Berners]], [[Thomas Mildmay (by 1515 \u2013 1566)|Thomas Mildmay]] and John Wiseman) that Crawley (at his own expense) had spent \u00a35 on a cope and vestment of blue velvet and more than 20 nobles on a chalice.<ref>W. Austin, ''History of a Bedfordshire Family; being a History of the Crawleys of Nether Crawley (etc.)'' (Alston Rivers, Ltd., London 1911), [https://archive.org/details/historyofbedford00aust/page/n157 pp. 67-72] (Internet Archive), citing F.C. Eeles and J.E. Brown (eds), ''The Edwardian Inventories for Bedfordshire'' (Longmans, Green, London 1905), pp. 22, 27.</ref>\n\n==Last stand==\nVaughan's widow, having made a further marriage to [[Sir Leonard Chamberlain|Sir Leonard Chamberlayne]] of [[Woodstock, Oxfordshire|Woodstock]], with him brought suit against Gwynneth claiming that he had withheld her share of Vaughan's estate. The parties agreed to [[arbitration]], which found that Gwynneth, as executor, owed a further \u00a3500 over and above \u00a3500 which Dame Margery had already received. This was then reduced to \u00a3400 by taking into account \u00a3100 which she and George Rolle had taken upon a bond from the children's portions deposited for them by Gwynneth in the Chamber of London, and which had not been repaid. Gwynneth made a payment and was granted his release or acquittance by the arbitrators. \n\nChamberlayne, however, pressed his bill, and Gwynneth then brought the matter to a perfect issue. He objected that Rolle's bond was nothing to do with Chamberlayne's suit, had not been mentioned in arbitration, and was never a subject of dispute. He revealed and proved that he had paid the full \u00a3500 before receiving his acquittance. He thereby exonerated himself from any possible imputation that he had used the children's money to discharge what he owed to Dame Margery. Her obligation, on the other hand, still remained. By a final and definitive sentence in Chancery on 4 November 1556 he was completely discharged and awarded costs, and Chamberlayne's bill was dismissed.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Chancery, Pleadings: ''Chamberlayn v Guyneth'', [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C7501237 C 1/1339/16-20], and C 18/10/26; Final decree: ''Chamberlayne v Gwnyneth'' [''[[sic]]'', recte Gwyneth], ref. [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C14514974 C 78/10/26], View original at AALT, images [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/C78/C78no10/IMG_0025.htm 0025] and [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/C78/C78no10/IMG_0026.htm 0026].</ref>\n\nGwynneth resigned from St Peter's, Westcheap before 19 November 1556, when his successor, Richard Smith, was presented by George Keynsham and George Wiseman under a concessionary advowson remaining from St Alban's Abbey, and instituted by Bonner.<ref>R. Newcourt, ''Repertorium Ecclesiasticum Parochiale Londinense'' (Benjamin Motte, for Baker, Tooke, Parker, Bowyer and Clements, London 1708), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9bNQAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA522#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 522] (Google).</ref> His last publication ''A playne demonstration of Iohn Frithes lacke of witte and learnynge in his vnderstandynge of holie scripture and of the olde holy doctours, in the blessed sacrament of the aulter'', printed by Thomas Powell in London, appeared in 1557.<ref>Full text at [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A02426.0001.001?view=toc Umich/eebo] (Open).</ref> His theological dialogues have been described as \"excruciatingly pedantic\".<ref>V. Westbrook and E. Evenden, ''Catholic Renewal and Protestant Resistance in Marian England'' (Routledge, Abingdon 2016),  [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=w2CrCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 160] (Google).</ref>\n\n;Death\nGwynneth appears to have died around the end of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]]'s reign: the death is placed before 1 December 1558 in Episcopal Registers.<ref>Mayer and Walters, ''Correspondence of Reginald Pole, Biographical Companion'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=_daeDoWdQ0cC&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 236], citing Lincoln Record Office, Episcopal Register 28, fol. 147 recto; ''LI2'', no. 653.</ref> He is described as deceased (\"defunctus\"<ref>\"...Johnis Gwinneth Clerici nuper vicarii de Luton diocesse Lincolnie provicieque Cantuarie defuncti\", i.e., \"...of John Gwynneth, clerk, late vicar of Luton in the diocese of Lincoln and the province of Canterbury, deceased\".</ref>) in [[Hilary term]] 1558/59, when his [[administrator (law)|administrators]] and next of kin (\"proximi consanguinei\"), his nephew Edward Awpart (jr) and his niece Elizabeth Awpart, wife of George Keynsham of [[Tempsford]], Bedfordshire,<ref>[[High Sheriff of Bedfordshire]], 1577\u201378. See Will of George Keynsham (P.C.C. 1592, Harrington quire), making Stephen Vaughan jnr his overseer.</ref> pressed a claim for debt of \u00a340 against Sir Thomas Rotherham of [[Someries Castle|Someries]], Luton.<ref>L. Jack, 'Revd. John Gwinneth, c. 1510 - c. 1563', [http://www.gwinnett.me.uk/characters/revd-john-gwinneth-c-1510-to-c-1559 Gwinnett Family History website], reciting The National Archives, Common Pleas Ref: CP 40/1178 m.902 dorse, with transcript and translation by David Bethell. (Verified at [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT3/Eliz/CP40no1178/bCP40no1178dorses/IMG_0738.htm AALT]).</ref> At Stuchbury his successor Laurence Washington entered the living (vacant by his death) in May 1559.<ref>Baker, ''History and Antiquities of Northampton'', I, 691.</ref> \n\nTwo factors have been taken to suggest that he survived into the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]].<ref>J.J. Jones, 'Gwynneth, John, (?1490-?1562), offeiriad Pabyddol a cherddor', ''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig'' [https://bywgraffiadur.cymru/article/c-GWYN-JOH-1490? Online]. J.P.D. Cooper, 'Gwynneth [Gwynedd], John (d. 1560x63), composer and polemicist', Oxford Dictionary of National Biography (2004).</ref> One is the story of his imprisonment: the other is the late record of a suit brought in his name before the Star Chamber for the recovery of the possessions of \"the late Dr Glyn\" at Clynnog Fawr in [[Llanwnda, Gwynedd|Llanwnda]] and [[Llanfaglan]].<ref>J.J. Jones, 'A Welsh Catholic controversialist', in ''Journal of the Welsh Bibliographical Society'' Vol. V part 2 (1938) [https://cylchgronau.llyfrgell.cymru/view/1226390/1227945/30#?xywh=-391%2C243%2C2943%2C2150 pp. 90-93] (Llyfrgell Genedlaethol Cymru), citing I. ab O. Edwards, ''A Catalogue of Star Chamber Proceedings relating to Wales'' (1929), p. 31.</ref> If this refers to Dr William Glyn of Glynllifon, Gwynneth's predecessor at Clynnog Fawr (who died in 1537), the grounds of the suit need not post-date the death (in 1558) of the more famous Dr William Glyn, Bishop of Bangor.\n\n==Nephews and nieces==\nAs executor, Gwynneth had responsibility for the estates of the children of the two marriages of his sister Margaret Gwynneth (also called Margery), who died in 1544. By her first marriage, to Edward Awpart, Girdler of London (died 1532), her children were:\n\n* Elizabeth Awpart, married (by Easter term 1557<ref>'Yorkshire Fines: 1557', in F. Collins (ed.), ''Feet of Fines of the Tudor Period [Yorks]: Part 1, 1486-1571'' (Leeds, 1887), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/feet-of-fines-yorks/vol1/pp199-210 pp. 199-210] (British History Online).</ref>) George Keynsham of [[Bygrave]], Hertfordshire and Tempsford, Bedfordshire (died 1593).<ref>Will of George Keynsham (P.C.C. 1592, Harrington quire). See Bedfordshire Records, ref. WY 1-444, [http://bedsarchivescat.bedford.gov.uk/Details/archive/110245966 \"Admin/biog history\"], (Bedfordshire Archives Service Catalogue).</ref><ref>It is unclear if she is the same wife Elizabeth who survived George and married Francis Gill of London: 'Parishes: Tempsford', in W. Page (ed.), ''A History of the County of Bedford'', Vol. 2 (VCH/HMSO, London 1908), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/beds/vol2/pp251-255 pp. 251-55] (British History Online).</ref>\n* Ann Awpart, living 1532.\n* Joan Awpart, married Edward Mildmay (elder brother of Sir Walter Mildmay) in 1548. Both died in 1548-1549.\n* Edward Awpart, one of the signatories to the testimonial provided by the [[English College, Rome#History|English Hospice in Rome]] for [[Thomas Sackville, 1st Earl of Dorset|Thomas Sackville]] at the time of his visit to Rome in 1564.<ref>H.D.G., 'Four Papers Relative to the Visit of Thomas Sackville', ''Miscellanea II: Publications of the Catholic Record Society'' vol. 2 (Society/Arden Press, London 1906 [https://archive.org/details/miscellanea02cath/page/n17 pp. 1-4] and [https://archive.org/details/miscellanea02cath/page/n11 Frontispiece] (Internet Archive).</ref> In 1572 Sir Thomas Ragland raised a mortgage on lands in Glamorganshire from George Keynsham and Edward Alporte, which led to a suit in Chancery between Ragland and Keynsham in 1578.<ref>The National Archives (UK), Exchequer: refs. [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C5922265 E 133/10/1565]; [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C5922262 E 133/10/1562]; [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C5921137 E 133/3/444] (Discovery Catalogue).</ref>\n* Susan Awpart, living 1532.\n\nBy her second marriage, 1532-33, to Stephen Vaughan (died 1549), her children were:\n\n* [[Anne Locke|Anne Vaughan]] (1534 - c. 1590), poet, married (1: c. 1549) Henry Lock (a younger son of Sir [[William Lok]]), who died in 1571;<ref>Will of Henry Lok (P.C.C. 1571, Holney quire).</ref> (2: 1572) [[Edward Dering (priest)|Edward Dering]] (died 1576); (3: 1576) Richard Prowse of Exeter. She was the author of ''A Meditation of a Penitent Sinner'' (1560).<ref>S.M. Felch, 'The Exemplary Anne Vaughan Lock,' in J. Harris and E. Scott-Baumann, ''The Intellectual Culture of Puritan Women, 1558\u20131680'' (Palgrave Macmillan, New York 2010), pp. 15-27.</ref>\n* Stephen Vaughan (b. 1537 - will proved 1605), entered [[Gonville Hall, Cambridge]], 1554; [[Inner Temple]], 1564.<ref>J. and J.A. Venn, ''Alumni Cantabrigienses'', Part 1 vol. 4 (Cambridge University Press, 1927), [https://archive.org/details/p1alumnicantabri04univuoft/page/294 p. 295] (Internet Archive)</ref> He married Jane, daughter of Richard Stroud (Strode), of [[Newnham (Old)|(Old) Newnham]], Devon.<ref>'Vaughan', in J.J. Howard (ed.), ''The Visitation of London, A.D. 1633, 1634, 1635'', 2 Vols, Harleian Society XV, XVII (1880/1883), II, [https://archive.org/details/publicationshar08socigoog/page/n322 p. 309] (Internet Archive).</ref> Stephen was an overseer in the will of George Keynsham, 1593. They had three daughters and three sons, of whom the eldest, Stephen, was considered insane, having been \"corrupted in religion\".<ref>Lambeth Palace Library, MS 3470 (Fairhurst Papers), [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/f7a3f182-0e5e-4baa-97c5-40568372f133 fol. 113] (Discovery Catalogue).</ref> The youngest son, Rowland Vaughan, inherited.<ref>Will of Stephen Vaughan of St Mary without Bishopsgate (P.C.C. 1605, Hayes quire).</ref>\n* Jane Vaughan (died c. 1610), recusant, married (by c. 1555) Thomas Wiseman, son of John Wiseman of Felsted.<ref>W.C. Metcalfe (ed.), ''The Visitations of Essex'', 2 Vols, Harleian Society XIII-XIV (1878/1879), 'Wiseman (1) (1612)' at [https://archive.org/details/visitationsofess13metc/page/324 pp. 324-25]; 'Wiseman (1) (1634)' at [https://archive.org/details/visitationsofess13metc/page/526 pp. 526-28].</ref> They had several children, including four sons (the heir being Sir William Wiseman), and four daughters of whom two became Abbess and Prioress of the [[Syon Abbey#Peregrination|Bridgettine house at Lisbon]], and two were nuns at St Ursula's of Louvain. Jane was imprisoned and condemned for recusancy, but the sentence against her was remitted.<ref>See Hamilton, ''Chronicle of St Monica's'', [https://archive.org/details/TheChronicleOfTheEnglishAugustinianV1/page/n131 p. 81] (Internet Archive); Ford, ''Genealogical Findings from the Diary of Thomas Cartwright'', I.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n[[File:John Herford, St Albans, printer's mark 1536.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Printer's mark from Gwynneth's \"Confutacyon\" of 1536.]]\nHis works are:\n* 'My Love mourneth,' music and words in a book, ''Bassus,'' beginning \"In this boke are conteynyd xx songes\", 1530, obl. 4to.<ref>''Book of XX Songes'' (1530), \"Bassus\", fols 30v [https://repository.royalholloway.ac.uk/items/c6584bb2-3d90-62b2-88a2-63f62493baa0/1/treenav.jsp?tempwn.b=close to 34v] (Royal Holloway digital). Text in E. Rickert, ''Ancient English Christmas Carols, 1400 to 1700'' (Chatto & Windus, London 1910), [https://archive.org/details/ancientenglishch00rickuoft/page/140 pp. 140-42], 156 (Internet Archive).</ref>\n* ''The confutacyon of the fyrst parte of Frythes boke, with a disputacyon before, whether it be possyble for any heretike to know that hymselfe is one or not, And also another, whether it be wors to denye directely more or lesse of the fayth,'' St. Albans, 1536, 16mo.\n* ''A brief Declaration of the notable Victory given of God to oure soueraygne lady, quene Marye, made in the church of Luton, the 23 July, in the first yere of her gracious reign,'' London [1554], 16mo.\n* ''A Declaration of the State wherein all Heretickes dooe leade their lives; and also of their continuall indever and propre fruictes, which beginneth in the 38 Chapiter, and so to thende of the Woorke,'' London, 1554, 4to.\n* ''A Manifeste Detection of the notable falshed of that Part of Frythes boke which he termeth his Foundation, and bosteth it to be invincible,'' 2nd edition, London, 1554, 8vo.\n* ''A Playne Demonstration of John Frithes lacke of witte and learnynge in his understandynge of holie Scripture, and of the olde holy doctours, in the Blessed Sacrament of the Aulter, newly set foorthe,'' London, 1557, 4to, written in the form of a dialogue.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gwynneth, John}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Welsh religious writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh musicians]]\n[[Category:Welsh Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century Welsh people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:16th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n", "name_user": "Eebahgum", "label": "safe", "comment": "twk", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Gwynneth"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chile", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Chile}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chile\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Chile (Density).svg\n| legend1         = Map of regions with confirmed coronavirus cases ('''as of 5 April'''): {{legend|#FCEED3|1\u20139 confirmed}}{{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|500\u2013999 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|1000\u20139999 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Chile]]\n| first_case      = [[Talca]]\n| arrival_date    = 3 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=03|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| first_outbreak  = \n| recovery_cases  = 528\n| deaths          = 34<ref name=\"Deaths\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.emol.com/noticias/Nacional/2020/03/31/981612/Minsal-nuevo-balance-covid19.html|title=Minsal reporta cuatro nuevos fallecidos por covid-19 y v\u00edctimas llegan a 12: Hay 2.738 casos registrados |website=emol.com |date=31 March 2020 }}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 4,471<ref name=\"Govt_Report\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/ minsal.cl: Nuevo Coronavirus COVID-19]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Chile]] on March 2020.<ref name=\"First_Case\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-chile/chile-records-first-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-health-ministry-idUSKBN20Q2UU |title=Chile records first confirmed case of coronavirus: health ministry |access-date=3 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305082641/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-chile/chile-records-first-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-health-ministry-idUSKBN20Q2UU |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of |2020|3}} there is a considerable [[COVID-19]] outbreak in Chile. While initial cases had been imported from [[South East Asia]] and [[Europe]], they expanded into a sizeable quantity of untraceable infections, placing the country within phase 4 of the pandemic as defined by the [[WHO]], and surpassing a thousand confirmed cases in 25 March 2020. The potential for an increase of Coronavirus cases in Chile is vast, especially given the [[2019\u201320 Chilean protests|continuing mass protests]].\n\n== Timeline ==\n*'''3 March 2020''': The Minister of Public Health confirmed the first case of the [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus in Chile, thus making the country the third in [[Latin America]] to report such an instance after [[Brazil]] and [[Argentina]],<ref name=\"First_Case\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24horas.cl/nacional/confirman-primer-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile-paciente-esta-en-talca-3990369|title=Confirman primer caso de coronavirus en Chile: paciente est\u00e1 en Talca|date=3 March 2020|website=24Horas.cl|language=es|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> the latter reporting its first case a few hours prior. Patient zero is a 33-year-old man in the city of [[Talca]].<ref name=\"usnews\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-03-03/chile-records-first-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-health-ministry |title=Chile Records First Confirmed Case of Coronavirus: Health Ministry |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*'''4 March 2020'''; The regional secretary (Seremi), Marlenne Dur\u00e1n, confirmed the second case of COVID-19 in the country. The new patient being the wife of the 33-year-old doctor who was diagnosed positive the previous day.<ref name=\"2nd_Case\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.chvnoticias.cl/trending/esposa-segundo-caso-coronavirus-chile_20200304/ |title=Esposa de m\u00e9dico con coronavirus tambi\u00e9n est\u00e1 contagiada |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, the Ministry of Health confirmed a third case in [[Santiago de Chile|Santiago]]; a 56-year-old woman, who returned to Chile after traveling to Europe, where she visited several countries, including Italy.<ref name=\"Case_3\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.cnnchile.com/pais/tercer-caso-coronavirus-chile-region-metropolitana_20200304/ |title=Ministerio de Salud confirma el tercer caso de coronavirus en Chile: Paciente reside en la Regi\u00f3n Metropolitana|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*'''5 March 2020''': The Public Health Institute (ISP) confirmed a fourth case in [[Santiago de Chile|Santiago]]; a 40-year-old woman who entered Chile on 29 February from Italy.<ref name=\"Case_4\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.cnnchile.com/pais/confirman-cuarto-caso-coronavirus-chile_20200305/ |title=Confirman cuarto caso de coronavirus en Chile|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*'''6 March 2020''': The Ministry of Health confirmed a fifth case in Santiago; a 58-year-old man who travelled to Europe alongside patient n\u00b03.<ref name=\"Case_5\">{{cite news |title=Confirman quinto caso de Coronavirus Covid-19 en Chile: es la pareja de una de las contagiadas|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-metropolitana/2020/03/06/confirman-quinto-caso-de-coronavirus-covid-19-en-chile-es-la-pareja-de-una-de-las-contagiadas.shtml |accessdate=6 March 2020 |work=BioBio Chile |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Radio BioBio |date=6 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''7 March 2020''': The Ministry of Health confirmed a sixth case; a 17-year-old male related to patients n\u00b03 and 5 who travelled to Europe alongside them.<ref name=\"Case_6\">{{cite news |title=Ministerio de Salud confirma sexto caso de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.24horas.cl/nacional/ministerio-de-salud-confirma-sexto-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile-4002978 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=24 Horas Chile |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=24 horas |date=7 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Later that same day, a 20-year-old woman from [[Puerto Montt]] was confirmed as the 7th case in the country.<ref name=\"Case_7\">{{cite news |title=Minsal confirma s\u00e9ptimo caso de coronavirus en Chile: es el primero en la regi\u00f3n de Los Lagos|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/07/minsal-confirma-septimo-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile-se-trata-de-joven-de-20-anos.shtml |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Radio BioBio |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=BioBio Chile |date=7 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''8 March 2020''': 3 more cases were confirmed; an 83-year-old woman who contracted the virus from a family member that visited her from [[New York (state)|New York]], who in turn, later presented symptoms and was diagnosed with COVID-19 upon arrival to the United States<ref name=\"Case_8\">{{cite news |title=Confirman octavo caso de Coronavirus COVID-19 en Chile: es una persona de 83 a\u00f1os|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/08/confirman-octavo-caso-de-coronavirus-covid-19-en-chile-es-una-persona-de-83-anos.shtml |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=Radio BioBio |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=BioBio Chile |date=8 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> (Possibly making this the first infection to occur entirely within Chilean soil); a 39-year-old man from Talca related to the 1st and 2nd cases who had contracted the virus via contact with them,<ref name=\"Case_9\">{{cite news |title=Confirman octavo caso de Coronavirus COVID-19 en Chile: es una persona de 83 a\u00f1os|url=https://www.latercera.com/nacional/noticia/minsal-confirma-noveno-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chile/LJXNH57SYVH4HFLIXI3SQAIONE/ |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=La Tercera |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=La Tercera |date=8 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> and a 14-year-old male who travelled to Europe with patients n\u00b03, 5 and 6.\n\n*'''9 March 2020''': The Ministry of health reported 3 new cases; a 42-year-old man from Santiago, a 2-year-old infant belonging to the Maule cluster and a 38-year-old man from [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], marking the first case within the [[Biob\u00edo Region]]. Along with the news, the Ministry of Health announced that it will start reporting new cases on a daily basis instead of one-by-one as they get confirmed.<ref name=\"Cases_11-13\">{{cite news |title=Confirman 13 casos de coronavirus en Chile: Minsal establece colaboraci\u00f3n con las FF.AA.|url=https://www.chvnoticias.cl/trending/13-casos-coronavirus-minsal-colaboracion-ff-aa_20200309/ |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Chilevisi\u00f3n noticias |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Chilevisi\u00f3n |date=9 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref name=\"COVID-19 MINSAL data\">{{cite news |title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/ |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Ministerio de Salud |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Minsal |date=9 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''10 March 2020''': 4 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 17; 5 of which belong to a small cluster from San Benito school in [[Vitacura]] that can be traced to a family who had travelled to Europe, as well as a man who had contact with a person who had recently been to [[Spain]]. The infected students have been quarantined and the Ministry of Health has placed the school under observation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cinco de los 17 casos de coronavirus est\u00e1n ligados a un colegio de Vitacura|url=https://www.latercera.com/nacional/noticia/cinco-de-los-17-casos-de-coronavirus-estan-ligados-a-un-colegio-de-vitacura/3UA6ZKHTYFA2NJUAGLBQ5RD4EI/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |work=La Tercera |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=La Tercera|date=10 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''11 March 2020''': 6 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 23. Among the infected, 14 reside in the [[Santiago Metropolitan Region]], becoming the first region in Chile to surpass ten confirmed cases.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n*'''12 March 2020''': 11 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 34. These new cases were reported in the [[Santiago Metropolitan Region]], specifically concentrated in the communes of [[Las Condes]], [[Vitacura]] and [[Lo Barnechea]]. <ref name=\"Cases_33\">{{cite news |title=Casos de coronavirus en Chile aumentan a 33 personas|url=https://www.df.cl/noticias/empresas/salud/casos-de-coronavirus-en-chile-aumentan-a-33-personas/2020-03-12/111740.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Chilevisi\u00f3n noticias |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=df.cl|date=12 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn_Case_33\">{{cite news |title=10 nuevos casos: Minsal reporta que hay 33 infectados de Covid-19 en Chile|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/pais/coronavirus-minsal-33-infectados-covid19-chile_20200312/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=cnnchile |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile|date=12 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> An additional case was also reported in [[Talca]]. <ref name=\"Cases_34\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Chile: Confirman nuevo caso en Talca y cifra de contagiados aumenta a 34|url=https://www.latercera.com/que-pasa/noticia/coronavirus-en-chile-confirman-nuevo-caso-en-talca-y-cifra-de-contagiados-aumenta-a-34/TGQOT7SG4FFNRGSU4DAD2JERHI/ |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=La Tercera |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=latercera.com|date=12 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''13 March 2020''': 9 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 43.<ref name=\"Cases_43\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Confirman primeros 2 casos en Concepci\u00f3n y total nacional de contagios llega a 43|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/13/covid-19-confirman-primeros-2-casos-en-concepcion-y-total-nacional-de-contagios-llega-a-4.shtml |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Radio BioBi\u00edo |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=biobiochile.cl|date=13 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> [[Saint George's College, Santiago|Saint George's College]] began a 15-day quarantine period after a teacher tested positive to the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Colegio de Vitacura entra en cuarentena por coronavirus|url=https://www.radioagricultura.cl/nacional/2020/03/13/colegio-de-vitacura-entra-en-cuarentena-por-coronavirus.html|accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Radio Agricultura |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=radioagricultura.cl|date=13 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''14 March 2020''': 18 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 61.<ref name=\"Cases_61a\">{{cite news |title=Chile entra en fase 3: Aumentan a 61 los casos coronavirus y aparecen los primeros en el norte|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/61-casos-coronavirus-chile_20200314/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=cnnchile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile.com|date=14 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> The Ministry of health detailed that there are four new cases in three regions, which are [[Antofagasta]] (2 cases), [[Atacama]] (1) and [[Ays\u00e9n Region|Ays\u00e9n]] (1), the latter being an 83-year-old British tourist aboard a cruise ship that landed in [[Coyhaique]] after showing symptoms of COVID-19, having previously disembarked in [[Caleta Tortel]]. The rest of the 14 new cases of COVID-19 infection are located in the [[Santiago Metropolitan Region]] (11), Maule (1) and \u00d1uble (2).<ref name=\"Cases_61\">{{cite news |title=Se sumaron tres regiones: Minsal aumenta a 61 los casos confirmados de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/294876-ministerio-de-salud-coronavirus-casos-confirmados-contagiados-chile-balance.html |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=meganoticias |issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=14 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''15 March 2020''': 14 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 75.<ref name=\"Cases_75\">{{cite news |title=Nuevo reporte eleva a 75 los casos de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/nuevo-reporte-75-casos-coronavirus-chile_20200315/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=cnnchile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile.com|date=15 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''16 March 2020''': 81 new cases were confirmed in a single day, bringing the total up to 156. According to the definition of the Health Organization (WHO), the start of stage 4 of the pandemic has been initiated.<ref name=\"Cases_155\">{{cite news |title=Chile entra en Fase 4: 155 casos de coronavirus y Gobierno anuncia cierre de fronteras\n|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/chile/2020/03/16/chile-entra-en-fase-4-155-casos-de-coronavirus-y-gobierno-anuncia-cierre-de-fronteras.shtml |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=cnnchile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile.com|date=16 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''17 March 2020''': 45 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 201.<ref name=\"Cases_201\">{{cite news |title=Ministro de Salud confirma 201 casos de personas contagiadas de coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295181-ministro-de-salud-jaime-manalich-201-casos-contagios-coronavirus-chile.html |accessdate=17 March 2020 |work=meganoticias|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=17 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> It was also determined that the virus spread through the +20 cases cluster in Chill\u00e1n via direct and indirect interpersonal contact within a gym, which was later closed and sanitized. Its users have been placed in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gimnasio fue foco de varios contagios de coronavirus en Chill\u00e1n|url=https://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/pais/region-de-nuble/gimnasio-fue-foco-de-varios-contagios-de-coronavirus-en-chillan/2020-03-17/145451.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Radio Cooperativa|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cooperativa.cl|date=17 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''18 March 2020''': 37 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 238.<ref name=\"Cases_238\">{{cite news |title=Sube a 238 la cifra de contagiados por coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295317-coronavirus-ministro-salud-jaime-manalich-238-casos-contagios-chile.html |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=meganoticias|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=18 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> The Maule region became the third to surpass 10 cases.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n*'''19 March 2020''': 103 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 342.<ref name=\"Cases_342\">{{cite news |title=Chile suma 103 nuevos casos de coronavirus y cifra de contagios llega a 342|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295456-balance-casos-coronavirus-chile-342-jaime-manalich.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=meganoticias|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=19 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref> The same day, patients zero and 1 (The 33-year-old man from Talca and his wife, both who had travelled to Southeast Asia) were ruled as healthy and sent back home to begin a post-recovery quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title='Caso cero' del COVID-19 en Chile fue dado de alta|url=https://rpp.pe/mundo/chile/coronavirus-caso-cero-del-covid-19-en-chile-fue-dado-de-alta-noticia-1252636?ref=rpp |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=RPP|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=rpp.pe|date=19 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''20 March 2020''': 92 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 434.<ref name=\"Cases_434\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Chile: nuevos casos y \u00faltimas noticias de hoy en vivo|url=https://chile.as.com/chile/2020/03/20/tikitakas/1584701975_596888.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=chile.as.com|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=chile.as.com|date=20 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''21 March 2020''': 103 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 537 nationwide. Health Minister Jaime Ma\u00f1alich confirmed the first death derived from coronavirus infection in Chile; an 83-year-old woman from Santiago.<ref name=\"Cases_537\">{{cite news |title=Ministro Ma\u00f1alich confirm\u00f3 muerte de la primera persona contagiada por coronavirus en Chile|url=https://www.meganoticias.cl/nacional/295726-manalich-coronavirus-primera-muerte-en-chile-mujer-83-anos-postrada-manejo-compasivo.html|accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=meganoticias.cl|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=meganoticias.cl|date=21 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''22 March 2020''': 95 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 632. Nationwide wide night time curfew was imposed.<ref name=\"Cases_632\"/>\n\n*'''24 March 2020''': The first case in [[Easter Island|Easter Island (Rapa Nui)]] is reported, despite the lockdown established on 19 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/de-origen-autoctono-rapa-nui-confirma-primer-contagio-de-coronavirus-en-la-isla_20200324/|title=De origen aut\u00f3ctono: Rapa Nui confirma primer contagio de coronavirus en la isla|publisher=CNN Chile|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref> 176 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total up to 922. <ref name=\"Cases_922\">{{cite news |title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|publisher=Minsal|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n*'''25 March 2020''': 220 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,142 and 3, respecitvely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.futuro.cl/2020/03/minsal-informo-de-1142-casos-de-coronavirus-en-chile-con-tercer-fallecido/|title=Minsal inform\u00f3 de 1142 casos de coronavirus en Chile con tercer fallecido|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n*'''26 March 2020''': 164 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,306 and 4, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://chile.as.com/chile/2020/03/26/tikitakas/1585219333_248806.html/|title=Coronavirus en Chile: 1306 casos, 4 muertes y noticias 26 de marzo|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>Total curfew to 7 communes of the Metropolitan Region was imposed. <ref name=\"Cases_1306\">{{cite news |title=Plan de Acci\u00f3n por Coronavirus|url=https://www.gob.cl/coronavirus/plandeaccion/|publisher=Chilean Government|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n*'''27 March 2020''': 304 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,610 and 5, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|date=28 March 2020|work=|accessdate=27 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es-CL}}</ref>Total curfew to Araucania Region was imposed due to high increase on new     cases.<ref name=\"Cases_1610\">{{cite news |title=Plan de Acci\u00f3n por Coronavirus|url=https://www.gob.cl/coronavirus/plandeaccion/|publisher=Chilean Government|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n*'''28 March 2020''': 299 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 1,909 and 6, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|date=28 March 2020|work=|accessdate=29 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n*'''29 March 2020''': 230 new cases and one death were confirmed, bringing the total up to 2,139 and 7, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/|title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|date=29 March 2020|work=|accessdate=29 March 2020|url-status=live|language=es-CL}}</ref>\n\n==Case summary==\n\n=== Region-wise details ===\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Chile medical cases}}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Region-wise summary ===\n* ''Updated as of 5 April 2020''.<ref name=\"Govt_Report\">{{cite news |title=Casos confirmados en Chile COVID-19|url=https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Ministerio de Salud|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=Gobierno de Chile|date=13 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Regions\n!Confirmed cases\n!Confirmed deaths\n|-\n|{{Flag|Arica y Parinacota}}\n|28\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Tarapac\u00e1}}\n|20\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Antofagasta}}\n|60\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Atacama}}\n|5\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Coquimbo}}\n|50\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Valpara\u00edso}}\n|191\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Santiago Metropolitan Region}}\n|2102\n|10\n|-\n|{{Flag|O'Higgins}}\n|41\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Maule Region}}\n|103\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|\u00d1uble Region}}\n|425\n|3\n|-\n|{{Flag|Biob\u00edo Region}}\n|365\n|2\n|-\n|[[Image:Flag of La Araucania, Chile.svg|23px|border]] [[Araucan\u00eda Region]]\n|509\n|13\n|-\n|[[Image:Flag of Los R\u00edos, Chile.svg|23px|border]] [[Los R\u00edos Region]]\n|99\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Los Lagos Region}}\n|276\n|1\n|-\n|{{Flag|Ays\u00e9n}}\n|7\n|0\n|-\n|{{Flag|Magallanes}}\n|190\n|2\n|-\n! Total: 16 regions\n! 4471 confirmed cases\n! 34 confirmed deaths\n|}\n\n== Statistics ==\n* ''{{As of|2020|4|5|df=}} there are 4471 confirmed cases in Chile''.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Chile medical cases chart}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Day !! New cases !! Cumulative cases || Cumulative recovered || Cumulative death\n|-\n| {{dts|3 March 2020}} || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|4 March 2020}} || 2 || 3 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|5 March 2020}} || 1 || 4 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|6 March 2020}} || 1 || 5 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|7 March 2020}} || 2 || 7 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|8 March 2020}} || 3 || 10 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|9 March 2020}} || 3 || 13 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|10 March 2020}} || 4 || 17 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| {{dts|11 March 2020}} 