legend=Legend\n | showValues=offset:2\n | y1Title = Active cases\n | xAxisTitle= Date\n | yAxisTitle= No. of active cases\n}}\n\n==Government response==\n*'''13 March 2020''': President [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]] announced a ban on public events with more than 500 people, as the government tries to control the spread of coronavirus even as massive social demonstrations are planned in March and April months.<ref name=\"Response_1\">{{cite news |title=Chile bans large public events over coronavirus fears, ahead of planned protests|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-chile/chile-bans-large-public-events-over-coronavirus-fears-ahead-of-planned-protests-idUSKBN21102N |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=reuters|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=reuters.com|date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*'''14 March 2020''': Nearly 1,300 passengers on two cruises in Chile have been quarantined after an 83-year-old British national tested positive for coronavirus.<ref name=\"Response_2\">{{cite news |title=Chile quarantines 1,300 cruise passengers after Brit, 83, catches coronavirus|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/chile-quarantines-1300-cruise-passengers-brit-83-catches-coronavirus-12399822/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=metro.co.uk|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=metro.co.uk}}</ref> [[Caleta Tortel]], a small coastal village that had been visited by the aforementioned tourist was subsequently placed under a 14-day quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Caleta Tortel inicia cuarentena y suspenden servicios de transporte en la comuna |url=https://radio.uchile.cl/2020/03/15/caleta-tortel-inicia-cuarentena-y-suspenden-servicios-de-transporte-en-la-comuna/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Radio UChile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=radio.uchile.cl|date=15 March 2020 |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''15 March 2020''': President Pi\u00f1era announced below points regarding student in a press conference\n# 14-day isolation for any member of an educational community who has a direct relative with confirmed contagion.\n# Suspension of classes for 14 days of the complete course when a student has confirmed contagion.\n# Suspension of classes for 14 days from the complete educational establishment in the case of two or more cases of students with confirmed contagion. These measures may be modified or extended to specific territories, such as communes and regions, as necessary.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n*'''16 March 2020''': President Pi\u00f1era announced the closure of the borders for 14 days. He said \u201cWe have decided to close all land, sea and area borders of our country for the transit of foreign people. This will not affect the entry and exit of cargo or carriers, to continue guaranteeing a normal supply of our country. This measure will take effect from 18 March 2020. Chilean nationals and permanent residents in Chile, who come from high-risk places, may enter our country undergoing Sanitary Customs and a mandatory 14-day quarantine.<ref name=\"Cases_155\"/>\n\n*'''18 March 2020''': President Pi\u00f1era issued a 90-day state of catastrophe ''(a [[state of exception]] subtype regulated in the [[Constitution of Chile]])'' in order to control the spread of the virus, effective at midnight.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus en Chile: Pi\u00f1era decreta estado de cat\u00e1strofe por 90 d\u00edas |url=https://oasisfm.cl/oasis-hoy/coronavirus-en-chile-pinera-decreta-estado-de-catastrofe-por-90-dias |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Oasis FM|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=oasisfm.cl|language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n*'''20 March 2020''': The mayors of Las Condes, La Reina and Vitacura declared a preventive quarantine for these sectors of the capital, where a large number of confirmed cases of coronavirus were recorded. <ref>{{cite news |title=Alcaldes de Vitacura, La Reina y Las Condes anuncian cuarentena preventiva en sus comunas |url=https://www.cnnchile.com/coronavirus/cuarentena-preventiva-la-reina-vitacura-las-condes_20200320/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=cnnchile|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=cnnchile|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*'''22 March 2020''': Chile announced a nationwide, night-time curfew between 22:00 Hrs to 5:00 Hrs to keep people off the streets and away from one another as the number of cases of coronavirus continued to creep upwards in the South American nation.<ref name=\"Cases_632\">{{cite news |title=Chile announces nationwide nightly curfew, coronavirus cases hit 632 |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/chile-announces-nationwide-nightly-curfew-coronavirus-cases-hit-632 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=nationalpost|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=nationalpost|language=En}}</ref>\n\n*'''22 March 2020''': The curfew was extended from 10pm-5am to 2pm-5am in Easter Island. <ref>{{cite news |title=Ampl\u00edan toque de queda en Isla de Pascua por primer caso de COVID-19: desde las 14 horas hasta las 5 de la ma\u00f1ana |url=http://lanacion.cl/2020/03/24/amplian-toque-de-queda-en-isla-de-pascua-por-primer-caso-de-covid-19-desde-las-14-horas-hasta-las-5-de-la-manana/|accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=La Naci\u00f3n|issue=Mar2020 |publisher=lanacion.cl|language=Es}}</ref>\n\n*'''26 March 2020''': At 10pm, a complete lockdown is established in 7 communes of [[Santiago, Chile|Greater Santiago]] ([[Santiago (commune)|Santiago]], [[Independencia, Chile|Independencia]], [[Providencia, Chile|Providencia]], [[\u00d1u\u00f1oa]], [[Las Condes]], [[Vitacura]] and [[Lo Barnechea]]), covering 1.3 million inhabitants.\n\n*'''28 March 2020''': At 10pm, a complete lockdown is established in [[Temuco]] and [[Padre Las Casas, Chile|Padre las Casas]].\n\n*'''1 April 2020''': At 10pm, a complete lockdown is established in [[Punta Arenas, Chile]].\n\n== Reactions ==\nOn 2 March 2020, The CRU World Copper Conference in [[Santiago]] the largest annual gathering of copper miners in the world was canceled which was scheduled between 23 and 27 March 2020, due to concerns over travel risks associated with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Reaction1\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/chile-copper/update-1-world-copper-conference-in-chile-canceled-over-coronavirus-concerns-cesco-idUSL1N2AV0P7 |title=UPDATE 1-World Copper Conference in Chile canceled over coronavirus concerns - Cesco |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMassive events such as [[Lollapalooza Chile]] (scheduled between 27 and 29 March 2020) and the [[FIDAE|XXI International Air and Space Fair]] (scheduled to take place between 31 March and 5 April), have been preventively suspended.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latercera.com/la-tercera-pm/noticia/lollapalooza-para-noviembre-metallica-y-kiss-en-suspenso-teleton-casi-sin-pubico-el-dificil-semestre-que-espera-a-los-eventos-en-chile/4VNVHUMCZ5CUHADRJ5QBNLG5DA/|title=Lollapalooza para noviembre, Metallica y Kiss en suspenso, Telet\u00f3n casi sin p\u00fablico: el Coronavirus contagia a los eventos en Chile|accessdate=13 March 2020|date=12 March 2020|website=La Tercera|lang=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latercera.com/nacional/noticia/presidente-pinera-anuncia-que-se-suspendera-la-fidae-por-el-coronavirus/I6A5JH4KFBCILNHJOSU645O2EI/|title=Presidente Pi\u00f1era anuncia que se suspender\u00e1 la Fidae por el coronavirus|accessdate=13 March 2020|date=13 March 2020|website=La Tercera|lang=es}}</ref> However, the Chilean government has assured that the [[2020 Chilean national plebiscite|26 April National Plebiscite]] will be held under sanitary safeguard measures.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latercera.com/nacional/noticia/manalich-asegura-que-gobierno-no-tiene-previsto-cancelar-plebiscito-por-coronavirus-no-anticipo-que-haya-una-discusion-respecto-a-la-pertinencia-de-hacerlo/RLNT27PYF5CEFALFZLUSLIDRE4/|title=Ma\u00f1alich asegura que gobierno no tiene previsto cancelar plebiscito por coronavirus: \"No anticipo que haya una discusi\u00f3n respecto a la pertinencia de hacerlo\"|accessdate=13 March 2020|date=13 March 2020|website=La Tercera|lang=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2020, Chilean lawmakers had reached agreement to postpone the referendum on a new constitution until late October as safety concerns around the coronavirus pandemic take precedence over politics. The referendum, originally slated for 26 April 2020 will be rescheduled for 25 October 2020, However the deal still requires formal approval by a two-thirds vote of congress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-chile/chile-to-postpone-referendum-on-new-constitution-as-coronavirus-concerns-grow-idUSKBN2163TL|title=Chile to postpone referendum on new constitution as coronavirus concerns grow\n|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=19 March 2020|website=reuters|lang=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.minsal.cl/nuevo-coronavirus-2019-ncov/casos-confirmados-en-chile-covid-19/ Official Chile's government confirmed cases in Chile COVID-19 Report]\n* [https://datastudio.google.com/u/0/reporting/f97733c1-17e1-4bd6-8841-9dd2d45ac9b4/page/W3OJB/ COVID-19 Chile Dashboard]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Chile]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America|Chile]]\n[[Category:2020 in Chile|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Chile]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:added commas", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Chile"}
{"title_page": "Prehistory of Brittany", "text_new": "[[File:Carnac Kermario 07.jpg|thumb|350px|The [[Carnac stones|alignments of Carnac]], the largest collection of megaliths in the world, demonstrate the organisation of Neolithic culture in Brittany]]\nThis page concerns the [[prehistory]] of [[Brittany]].\n\n==Palaeolithic==\nBrittany was never [[glaciation|glaciated]] during the [[Quaternary]], owing to its latitude, proximity to the coast and absence of significant mountain ranges. However, even though free of glaciers, Palaeolithic Brittany was extremely cold compared to its present climate, with annual mean temperatures at the last glacial maximum estimated at -3&nbsp;\u00b0C (27&nbsp;\u00b0F). [[Permafrost]] was present with only a very shallow active layer estimated at only 1 foot (30&nbsp;cm) thawing each summer, so that only a very light (less than 5 percent) cover of [[tundra]] could grow. This vegetation could only support very low densities of grazing mammals like [[reindeer]], which (in Europe) are found today only in areas then uninhabitable due to the presence of thick [[ice sheet]]s.\n\nConsequently, few if any people could survive in Brittany prior to the end of the last glaciation, and only a few Palaeolithic sites are known from Brittany, like the rock shelter of [[Perros-Guirec]] near [[Rochworn]]. The only cave site known so far is Roc'h Toul  in a sandstone promontory near Guiclan ([[Finist\u00e8re]]). The cave contained about 200 artifacts and was dated to the late [[Magdalenian]] by [[Gabriel de Mortillet|de Mortillet]]. Because of the presence of points with curved backs, it is now connected with the [[epipalaeolithic]] [[Azilian]]. Other Azilian sites include Parc-an-Plenen and Enez Guennoc.\n\n==Mesolithic==\nThe best-known [[mesolithic]] sites from Brittany are the cemeteries on the islands of [[Ho\u00ebdic]] (10 graves) and [[T\u00e9viec]] (9 graves) in [[Morbihan]]. The collective graves are placed in [[shell midden]]s without any particular order. Some graves show evidence of postmortal manipulations of the bones. There are single burials and empty graves ([[cenotaph]]s) as well. The graves are covered with stones, a [[hearth]] or [[antler]]s forming a sort of dome. Rich funeral gifts, [[flint tools]], engraved bones, shell ornaments and [[ochre]] demonstrate the affluence of these [[hunter-gatherers]], or rather fisher-gatherers. Certain shells are sex-specific.\n\nIn Teviec there are stone [[cist]] graves. The bones of an infant have been postmortally ornamented with striations.\n\nThe corresponding settlements consist of shell middens. A [[radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon date]] of 4625 (uncal.) for Ho\u00ebdic places it in the 6th Millennium BC cal, rather late in the Mesolithic sequence, and indeed there are some indications of contact with agricultural societies to the East. Their economy was based on marine resources. Recently, a number of [[accelerator (chemistry)|accelerator]] dates have been published for Ho\u00ebdic.\n\nIn [[Beg an Dorchenn]] in Plomeur (Finist\u00e8re), domestic dog and cattle were already present, in [[Dissignac]], [[microlith]]s were associated with [[pollen]] evidence for [[forest clearance|clearance]]s.\n\nSome scholars speculate that megalithic graves might go back to the Mesolithic, but this contention is difficult to prove, as most structures have been reused. Large numbers of microliths have been found under the [[chambered tomb]] of Dissignac [[:fr:Tumulus de Dissignac]].\n\n==Neolithic==\n[[File:Kerloas menhir.JPG|thumb|The Kerloas Menhir, near Plouarzel. With a height of 9.5 metres this menhir is the tallest standing menhir in Brittany. A few centuries ago the top was knocked off in a thunder storm: originally it must have been over 10 metres high.]]\nThe westernmost extensions of the [[Villeneuve-Saint-Germain culture]], based on a [[linearbandkeramic]] tradition are found in eastern Brittany at Le Haut Me\u00e9. The use of [[schist]] from the eastern edge of the Breton Massif for bracelets in settlements in the Paris Bassin attests to widespread trade. A bracelet of polished stone found in a grave in the VSG-settlement of [[Jablines]] Les-Longues-Raies was made of [[amphibolite]] from the island of [[Groix]] in southern Morbihan, proves  trade with local [[Mesolithic]] communities.\n\nThe earliest long mounds date to the mid-5th millennium ([[Barnenez]]). The early [[passage grave]]s generally date to between 4000 and 3000 bc, followed by evolved passage graves between 3000-2500 bc. In the later part of the Neolithic, [[all\u00e9e couverte|all\u00e9es couvertes]] and simple [[dolmen]]s became the predominant type of burial monument.\nSome passage graves are decorated with incised lines, of which [[Gavrinis]] is probably the best known example.\n\nSome scholars see an influence of the central European [[Linear band ceramic]] culture in the finds from the longbarrows of [[Man\u00e9 Ty Ec]] and [[Man\u00e9 Pochat er Ieu]] ([[Morbihan]]), but this should rather be connected to the [[la Hoguette]] tradition, ultimately of [[Cardial Ware|Cardial]] extraction.\n\nCarn-pottery, thin walled round based deep bowls, often with applied crescents (croissants) is typical for early [[chambered tomb]]s. It is found in Finist\u00e8re, Morbihan and [[Loire-Atlantique]].\n\nMiddle Neolithic settlements include La Motte, La Butte-aux-Pierres and Lannic. They mainly concentrate on the Coast. The pottery shows [[Chass\u00e9en]] influences. Bowls are still round-bottomed, but with s-shaped profiles and vertically perforated [[Lug (knob)|lug]]s. Some geometric decoration occurs, but is rather rare. Vase-supports of Chassey-type are found as well, the Breton variety has been named the Er Lannic type and is characterised by triangular perforations, while the examples found in the [[Channel Islands]] show circular perforations. Other local pottery types include Castellic grooved ware, [[Souc'h-ware]], and Colpo-type ware.\n\n[[Stone circle]]s like [[Er Lannic]] (a double oval of standing stones and a ditch) sometimes contain settlement material and pottery of Chass\u00e9en-type.\n\nBy the middle of the 3rd century, the Kerugou, upper and lower Conguel and Rosmeur/Croh Coll\u00e9 types became preponderant.\n\n[[Seine-Oise-Marne culture]]-influenced pottery in central Brittany includes the Quessoy and Crec'h Quille/Le Melus types. Collared bottles can be related to the Kragenflaschenhorizont of the late TBK.\n\nFrom the late 3rd millennium, Grand-Pressigny [[flint]] was imported in some quantity. Some type of Breton axes were exported. For example, [[dolerite]] axes made at Plussulien have been found in Britain. The dolmen Man\u00e9-Lud at [[Locmariaquer]] is thought to show a picture of a boat.\n\n[[Beaker people|Beaker]] material is known from some settlement sites, for example Kastel Koz, other beakers were found in rivers. Marine beakers predominate, AOC-decoration is found in Southern Brittany. Small [[gold]] plaques are known from beaker graves, in Kerouaren a diadem has been found.\n\nThere is no indication that the beaker people already exploited the Armorican metal deposits.\n\n==Bronze Age==\nThe early [[Bronze Age]] culture is commonly believed to have grown out of Beaker roots, with some [[Wessex culture|Wessex]] and [[Unetice culture|Unetice]] influence. In the early Bronze Age, rich individual graves are found under [[tumulus|barrows]], which indicates a complete change of the social structure. The Breton barrows have been divided into two series by Cogn\u00e9 and Guiot, the first dating from 1900-1600 bc, the second to 1600-1400 bc. The barrows of the first series can be up to 50 m in diameter and 6 m high. They are found in Western Brittany, along the coast, the [[Blavet]] river and at the southern border of the [[Monts d'Arr\u00e9e]]. A few examples have been recorded from Normandy. The barrows contain a small cairn over a stone cist, wooden coffin or dry stone structure containing the burial. Often the chambers are covered by large stone slabs. Sometimes roofed mortuary houses are found, for example at St. Jude en Bourbriac. The stone [[cist]]s can be quite large, up to 4 m long, but always only contain a single body. Grave gifts include [[amber]] beads, [[silver]] cups, gold-hilted daggers (Saint Adrien), tanged flint [[arrowhead]]s and stone [[axe]]s. Because of these rich [[grave goods]], J. Briard sees them as burials of warrior-priests. Certainly not everybody was buried in this way, but nothing is known of \"commoner-burials\", especially as bones are not normally preserved in the acidic soils of Brittany. The gold-pin decoration of the dagger hilts and the amber-beads show close connection to the Wessex-culture, but there are technical differences.\n\nThe barrow of Kernonen en Plouvorn, Finist\u00e8re, provides a good example of a rich burial of the first series.\n\nThe barrows of the second series are a bit smaller and show a more inland-distribution. They do not normally contain metal, but numerous pottery vessels, high biconical vessels, sometimes with a geometric decoration under the rim, or single four-handled undecorated pots. There seems to be no division of the grave goods by gender.\n\nGlass-beads are found in some graves, for example at Mez-Nabat, Plouhinec (Finist\u00e8re).\n\nA number of [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon-dates]] are known from the barrows:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! name of site\n! dept.\n! Lab number\n! date\n! standard deviation\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-805\n| 1960\n| 120\n|-\n| Melrand, Saint-Fiacre\n| Morbihan\n| Gif-863\n| 1950\n| 135\n|-\n| Goarem Goasven\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1313\n| 1850\n| 130\n|-\n| Saint Evarzec, Kerhuel\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-482\n| 1630\n| 200\n|-\n| Kervigny\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-2481\n| 1560\n| 100\n|-\n| Ligollenec, Berrien\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1866\n| 1550\n| 120\n|-\n| Kerno en Ploudariel\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-2421\n| 1500\n| 100\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1149\n| 1480\n| 120\n|-\n| Cleger, Kervelerin\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gsy-86\n| 1345\n| 150\n|-\n| Guidel, Tuchenn Cruguel\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-235\n| 1320\n| 200\n|-\n| Cleder, Le Helen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-748\n| 1300\n| 115\n|-\n| Plouz\u00e9v\u00e9d\u00e9, Ar R\u00e9unic\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1113\n| 1250\n| 120\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-806\n| 1250\n| 120\n|-\n| Plouz\u00e9v\u00e9d\u00e9, Ar R\u00e9unic\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1115\n| 1210\n| 120\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-807\n| 1200\n| 120\n|-\n| Goarem Goasven\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1314\n| 1050\n| 130\n|-\n| Courcoury\n| Charente Maritime\n| Gif-2347\n| 850\n| 70\n|-\n| Plouhinec, Lescongar\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-2347\n| 850\n| 70\n|-\n| Cr\u00e9e de Carat\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| GrN-1973\n| 700\n| 60\n|}\n\nThe later part of the early Bronze Age saw the beginning of the exploitation of the Armorican [[tin]] deposits. Numerous hoards contain tools and weapons, but metalwork is rarely found in burials or settlements, which makes the synchronisation of hoards and settlements difficult. The Tr\u00e9boul-group of hoards is thought to be contemporaneous with the second series barrows. Decorated spear-heads, flanged axes, [[palstaves]] and long daggers are typical. The hoard from Bignan (Morbihan) contained only bronze jewellery.\n\nCoastal [[saltern]]s are known from the late Bronze Age onwards as well, for example at Curnic, Guiss\u00e9ny.\n\nPollen analysis shows that widespread clearance of the beech forests took place in the early Bronze Age. Cereal pollen have been found at Porsguen, Plouescat, for example. Domestic animals included sheep, goats and cattle, but hunting may have still provided a lot of meat. La Roche, Videlles, has still 60% wild animals among the animal bones, but it is not clear if this is typical. Carbonised remains of naked wheat and barley have been found at Ploun\u00e9our-Trez, hazelnuts and acorns were eaten as well. Flint still formed an important part of the tool inventory.\n\n[[File:Bretagne Morbihan Locmariaquer 14017.jpg|thumb|The ''Grand Menhir Bris\u00e9'' and ''Table des Marchand'' at Locmariaquer]]\n\nSome standing stones (Menhirs) and stone alignments date to the early Bronze Age, for example the Grand Menhir Bris\u00e9 at Locmariaquer.\n\nThe later Bronze Age sees only a slight [[Urnfield]] influence. Hoards are numerous. The Saint-Brieuc-des-Iffs phase marks the beginnings of the Atlantic bronze industries. It is succeeded by the [[carp's-tongue complex]], found in Britain and Portugal as well.\n\nThe square-socketed armorican axes turn up in [[hoard]]s in great numbers. At Maure-de-Bretagne, over 4000 axes have been found, ca. 800 at Tr\u00e9hou and Loud\u00e9ac.\n\nThe axes are mainly unused and may have been a form of ingot of primitive [[currency]]. They contain a high amount of lead or consist of pure lead and are distributed from the Iberian Peninsula to eastern Germany, Ireland and Southern Britain, with some pieces from Scotland, Poland and Switzerland. Different regional types are known: Brandivy in Morbihan, Dahouet and Plurien on the North coast, Tr\u00e9hou in Finist\u00e8re. The miniature types of Maure-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine and Couville are typical of [[Upper Brittany]].\n\n[[Copper]] was imported from Spain as plano-convex [[ingot]]s, as  found in the [[hoard]] of Penfoul, [[Landelau]].\n\nSettlements have rarely been excavated, [[Ploubazlanec]] at the mouth of the [[Trieux]] is an example of a fortified village.\n\nThe Museum of PreHistory in Carnac has large quantities of Late Bronze Age bronze and copper artifacts from the [[Atlantic Bronze Age]] culture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museedecarnac.com/protohistoire.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604211819/http://www.museedecarnac.com/protohistoire.htm |archivedate=2010-06-04 }}</ref>\nThis culture was a maritime trading-networked culture that included Brittany and most of the rest of France, the other [[Celtic nations]], England, Spain and Portugal. According to [[John T. Koch]], [[Barry Cunliffe]], Karl, and Wodtko, [[Celtic languages]] developed in the intense interactions of this culture with the [[Tartessian language]] the first written language so far discovered from this era,<ref>http://www.aber.ac.uk/aberonline/en/archive/2008/05/au7608/</ref><ref name=Koch>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.ac.uk/Resources/Documents/Research/ODonnell.pdf|title=O'Donnell Lecture 2008 Appendix}}</ref><ref name=Koch2009>{{cite book | last = Koch | first = John | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Tartessian: Celtic from the Southwest at the Dawn of History in Acta Palaeohispanica X Palaeohispanica 9 (2009)| publisher = Palaeohispanica | year = 2009 | location = | pages = 339\u2013351 | url = http://ifc.dpz.es/recursos/publicaciones/29/54/26koch.pdf | doi = | id = | issn = 1578-5386 | accessdate = 2010-05-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=2146413465|title=New research suggests Welsh Celtic roots lie in Spain and Portugal|last=Koch|first=John|accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cunliffe, Karl, Guerra, McEvoy, Bradley; Oppenheimer, Rrvik, Isaac, Parsons, Koch, Freeman and Wodtko|title=Celtic from the West: Alternative Perspectives from Archaeology, Genetics, Language and Literature|year=2010|publisher=Oxbow Books and Celtic Studies Publications|isbn=978-1-84217-410-4|pages=384|url=http://www.oxbowbooks.com/bookinfo.cfm/ID/88298//Location/DBBC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612212219/http://www.oxbowbooks.com/bookinfo.cfm/ID/88298/Location/DBBC|archivedate=2010-06-12}}</ref> but this view stands in contrast to the more generally accepted view of Celticists that their origin lies with the Central European [[Hallstatt culture]] and that [[Tartessian language|Tartessian]] cannot be classified as Celtic at all.\n\n==Iron Age==\nA variety of tribes are mentioned in Roman sources, like the [[Veneti (Gaul)|Veneti]], [[Armoricani]], [[Osismii]], [[Namnetes]] and [[Coriosolites]]. [[Strabo]] and [[Poseidonius]] describe the Armoricani as belonging to the [[Belgae]].\n\nArmorican gold coins have been widely exported and are even found in the Rhineland.\n\n[[Salterns]] are widespread in Northern Armorica, for example at Tr\u00e9gor, Ebihens and Enez Vihan near Pleumeur-Bodou (C\u00f4tes-d'Armor) and the island of Yoc'h near Landuvez (Finist\u00e8re) of late [[La T\u00e8ne culture|La T\u00e8ne]] date.\n\nAn estimated  40\u201355&nbsp;kg  of salt per oven were produced at [[Ebihens]]. Each oven was  about 2 m long. The site dates to the end of the early [[La T\u00e8ne culture|La T\u00e8ne]] or the middle La T\u00e8ne period. Numerous [[briquetage]]-remains  have been found. At Tregor, boudins de Calage (hand-bricks) were the typical form of briquetage, between 2,5 and 15&nbsp;cm long and with a diameter between 4\u20137&nbsp;cm.\nAt the salterns at Landrellec and Enez Vihan at Pleumeur-Bodou the remains of rectangular ovens have been excavated that are 2,5\u20133 m long and ca. 1 m wide and constructed of stones and clay.\nOn the  [[Gulf of Morbihan]] about 50 salterns have been found so far. mainly dating to the final La T\u00e9ne period.\n\n:''For subsequent periods of Brittany's past, see [[Armorica]] and [[history of Brittany]].''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Bowen, E. G. (1977) ''Saints, Seaways and Settlements in the Celtic Lands''. Cardiff: University of Wales Press {{ISBN|0-900768-30-4}}\n* Monnier, Jean-Jacques & Cassard, Jean-Christophe, with a team of scholars of the Breton Universities of Brest, Nantes, and Rennes (1996) ''\"Toute l\u2019histoire de Bretagne\"  in Britain and in Brittany''; 800 pages. Morlaix: Editions Skol-Vreizh {{ISBN|2-903313-95-4}}\n* Tonnerre, No\u00ebl-Yves  (1994) ''Naissance de la Bretagne''; 621 pp. Angers: Presse de l'Universit\u00e9 d' Angers\n* Fleuriot, L\u00e9on (1980) ''Les origines de la Bretagne''. Paris: \u00c9d. Payot {{ISBN|2-228-12710-8}}\n* Dillon, Myles, Chadwick, Nora & Guyonvarc'h, Christian-J. ''Les royaumes celtiques'', Librairie Arth\u00e8me Fayard, 1974.{{ISBN|2-213-00077-8}}\n* Dillon, Myles & Chadwick, Nora (1967) ''The Celtic Realms''. London: Weidenfeld and Nicolson\n*''L'Histoire de la Bretagne et des pays celtiques'', Morlaix, Skol Vreizh, 1966\n* Le Moyne de la Borderie, Arthur (1905) ''Histoire de la Bretagne''; 6 vol. 4to, Plihon Editeur, Imprimerie Vatar, Rennes 1905-1914.\n* Lobineau, ''Dom'' (1707) ''Histoire de Bretagne''; 2 vol. folio  Paris: veuve Muguet\n* Morice, ''Dom'' & Taillandier, ''Dom'' (1750) ''Histoire de Bretagne''; 2 vol. folio. Paris:, veuve elaguette, 1750-1756.\n* Morice, ''Dom'' & Taillandier, ''Dom'' (1742) ''M\u00e9moires pour servir de preuves \u00e0 l'Histoire de Bretagne''; 3 vol. folio. Paris: Ch. Osmont, 1742-1746.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Prehistoric France]]\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric France]]\n[[Category:History of Brittany]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of France]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Brittany]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Carnac Kermario 07.jpg|thumb|350px|The [[Carnac stones|alignments of Carnac]], the largest collection of megaliths in the world, demonstrate the organisation of Neolithic culture in Brittany]]\nThis page concerns the [[prehistory]] of [[Brittany]].\n\n==Palaeolithic==\nBrittany was never [[glaciation|glaciated]] during the [[Quaternary]], owing to its latitude, proximity to the coast and absence of significant mountain ranges. However, even though free of glaciers, Palaeolithic Brittany was extremely cold compared to its present climate, with annual mean temperatures at the last glacial maximum estimated at -3&nbsp;\u00b0C (27&nbsp;\u00b0F). [[Permafrost]] was present with only a very shallow active layer estimated at only 1 foot (30&nbsp;cm) thawing each summer, so that only a very light (less than 5 percent) cover of [[tundra]] could grow. This vegetation could only support very low densities of grazing mammals like [[reindeer]], which (in Europe) are found today only in areas then uninhabitable due to the presence of thick [[ice sheet]]s.\n\nConsequently, few if any people could survive in Brittany prior to the end of the last glaciation, and only a few Palaeolithic sites are known from Brittany, like the rock shelter of [[Perros-Guirec]] near [[Rochworn]]. The only cave site known so far is Roc'h Toul  in a sandstone promontory near Guiclan ([[Finist\u00e8re]]). The cave contained about 200 artifacts and was dated to the late [[Magdalenian]] by [[Gabriel de Mortillet|de Mortillet]]. Because of the presence of points with curved backs, it is now connected with the [[epipalaeolithic]] [[Azilian]]. Other Azilian sites include Parc-an-Plenen and Enez Guennoc.\n\n==Mesolithic==\nThe best-known [[mesolithic]] sites from Brittany are the cemeteries on the islands of [[Ho\u00ebdic]] (10 graves) and [[T\u00e9viec]] (9 graves) in [[Morbihan]]. The collective graves are placed in [[shell midden]]s without any particular order. Some graves show evidence of postmortal manipulations of the bones. There are single burials and empty graves ([[cenotaph]]s) as well. The graves are covered with stones, a [[hearth]] or [[antler]]s forming a sort of dome. Rich funeral gifts, [[flint tools]], engraved bones, shell ornaments and [[ochre]] demonstrate the affluence of these [[hunter-gatherers]], or rather fisher-gatherers. Certain shells are sex-specific.\n\nIn Teviec there are stone [[cist]] graves. The bones of an infant have been postmortally ornamented with striations.\n\nThe corresponding settlements consist of shell middens. A [[radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon date]] of 4625 (uncal.) for Ho\u00ebdic places it in the 6th Millennium BC cal, rather late in the Mesolithic sequence, and indeed there are some indications of contact with agricultural societies to the East. Their economy was based on marine resources. Recently, a number of [[accelerator (chemistry)|accelerator]] dates have been published for Ho\u00ebdic.\n\nIn [[Beg an Dorchenn]] in Plomeur (Finist\u00e8re), domestic dog and cattle were already present, in [[Dissignac]], [[microlith]]s were associated with [[pollen]] evidence for [[forest clearance|clearance]]s.\n\nSome scholars speculate that megalithic graves might go back to the Mesolithic, but this contention is difficult to prove, as most structures have been reused. Large numbers of microliths have been found under the [[chambered tomb]] of Dissignac [[:fr:Tumulus de Dissignac]].\n\n==Neolithic==\n[[File:Kerloas menhir.JPG|thumb|The Kerloas Menhir, near Plouarzel. With a height of 9.5 metres this menhir is the tallest standing menhir in Brittany. A few centuries ago the top was knocked off in a thunder storm: originally it must have been over 10 metres high.]]\nThe westernmost extensions of the [[Villeneuve-Saint-Germain culture]], based on a [[linearbandkeramic]] tradition are found in eastern Brittany at Le Haut Me\u00e9. The use of [[schist]] from the eastern edge of the Breton Massif for bracelets in settlements in the Paris Bassin attests to widespread trade. A bracelet of polished stone found in a grave in the VSG-settlement of [[Jablines]] Les-Longues-Raies was made of [[amphibolite]] from the island of [[Groix]] in southern Morbihan, proves  trade with local [[Mesolithic]] communities.\n\nThe earliest long mounds date to the mid-5th millennium ([[Barnenez]]). The early [[passage grave]]s generally date to between 4000 and 3000 bc, followed by evolved passage graves between 3000-2500 bc. In the later part of the Neolithic, [[all\u00e9e couverte|all\u00e9es couvertes]] and simple [[dolmen]]s became the predominant type of burial monument.\nSome passage graves are decorated with incised lines, of which [[Gavrinis]] is probably the best known example.\n\nSome scholars see an influence of the central European [[Linear band ceramic]] culture in the finds from the longbarrows of [[Man\u00e9 Ty Ec]] and [[Man\u00e9 Pochat er Ieu]] ([[Morbihan]]), but this should rather be connected to the [[la Hoguette]] tradition, ultimately of [[Cardial Ware|Cardial]] extraction.\n\nCarn-pottery, thin walled round based deep bowls, often with applied crescents (croissants) is typical for early [[chambered tomb]]s. It is found in Finist\u00e8re, Morbihan and [[Loire-Atlantique]].\n\nMiddle Neolithic settlements include La Motte, La Butte-aux-Pierres and Lannic. They mainly concentrate on the Coast. The pottery shows [[Chass\u00e9en]] influences. Bowls are still round-bottomed, but with s-shaped profiles and vertically perforated [[Lug (knob)|lug]]s. Some geometric decoration occurs, but is rather rare. Vase-supports of Chassey-type are found as well, the Breton variety has been named the Er Lannic type and is characterised by triangular perforations, while the examples found in the [[Channel Islands]] show circular perforations. Other local pottery types include Castellic grooved ware, [[Souc'h-ware]], and Colpo-type ware.\n\n[[Stone circle]]s like [[Er Lannic]] (a double oval of standing stones and a ditch) sometimes contain settlement material and pottery of Chass\u00e9en-type.\n\nBy the middle of the 3rd century, the Kerugou, upper and lower Conguel and Rosmeur/Croh Coll\u00e9 types became preponderant.\n\n[[Seine-Oise-Marne culture]]-influenced pottery in central Brittany includes the Quessoy and Crec'h Quille/Le Melus types. Collared bottles can be related to the Kragenflaschenhorizont of the late TBK.\n\nFrom the late 3rd millennium, Grand-Pressigny [[flint]] was imported in some quantity. Some type of Breton axes were exported. For example, [[dolerite]] axes made at Plussulien have been found in Britain. The dolmen Man\u00e9-Lud at [[Locmariaquer]] is thought to show a picture of a boat.\n\n[[Beaker people|Beaker]] material is known from some settlement sites, for example Kastel Koz, other beakers were found in rivers. Marine beakers predominate, AOC-decoration is found in Southern Brittany. Small [[gold]] plaques are known from beaker graves, in Kerouaren a diadem has been found.\n\nThere is no indication that the beaker people already exploited the Armorican metal deposits.\n\n==Bronze age==\nThe early [[Bronze age]] culture is commonly believed to have grown out of Beaker roots, with some [[Wessex culture|Wessex]] and [[Unetice culture|Unetice]] influence. In the early Bronze Age, rich individual graves are found under [[tumulus|barrows]], which indicates a complete change of the social structure. The Breton barrows have been divided into two series by Cogn\u00e9 and Guiot, the first dating from 1900-1600 bc, the second to 1600-1400 bc. The barrows of the first series can be up to 50 m in diameter and 6 m high. They are found in Western Brittany, along the coast, the [[Blavet]] river and at the southern border of the [[Monts d'Arr\u00e9e]]. A few examples have been recorded from Normandy. The barrows contain a small cairn over a stone cist, wooden coffin or dry stone structure containing the burial. Often the chambers are covered by large stone slabs. Sometimes roofed mortuary houses are found, for example at St. Jude en Bourbriac. The stone [[cist]]s can be quite large, up to 4 m long, but always only contain a single body. Grave gifts include [[amber]] beads, [[silver]] cups, gold-hilted daggers (Saint Adrien), tanged flint [[arrowhead]]s and stone [[axe]]s. Because of these rich [[grave goods]], J. Briard sees them as burials of warrior-priests. Certainly not everybody was buried in this way, but nothing is known of \"commoner-burials\", especially as bones are not normally preserved in the acidic soils of Brittany. The gold-pin decoration of the dagger hilts and the amber-beads show close connection to the Wessex-culture, but there are technical differences.\n\nThe barrow of Kernonen en Plouvorn, Finist\u00e8re, provides a good example of a rich burial of the first series.\n\nThe barrows of the second series are a bit smaller and show a more inland-distribution. They do not normally contain metal, but numerous pottery vessels, high biconical vessels, sometimes with a geometric decoration under the rim, or single four-handled undecorated pots. There seems to be no division of the grave goods by gender.\n\nGlass-beads are found in some graves, for example at Mez-Nabat, Plouhinec (Finist\u00e8re).\n\nA number of [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon-dates]] are known from the barrows:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! name of site\n! dept.\n! Lab number\n! date\n! standard deviation\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-805\n| 1960\n| 120\n|-\n| Melrand, Saint-Fiacre\n| Morbihan\n| Gif-863\n| 1950\n| 135\n|-\n| Goarem Goasven\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1313\n| 1850\n| 130\n|-\n| Saint Evarzec, Kerhuel\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-482\n| 1630\n| 200\n|-\n| Kervigny\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-2481\n| 1560\n| 100\n|-\n| Ligollenec, Berrien\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1866\n| 1550\n| 120\n|-\n| Kerno en Ploudariel\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-2421\n| 1500\n| 100\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1149\n| 1480\n| 120\n|-\n| Cleger, Kervelerin\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gsy-86\n| 1345\n| 150\n|-\n| Guidel, Tuchenn Cruguel\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-235\n| 1320\n| 200\n|-\n| Cleder, Le Helen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-748\n| 1300\n| 115\n|-\n| Plouz\u00e9v\u00e9d\u00e9, Ar R\u00e9unic\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1113\n| 1250\n| 120\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-806\n| 1250\n| 120\n|-\n| Plouz\u00e9v\u00e9d\u00e9, Ar R\u00e9unic\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1115\n| 1210\n| 120\n|-\n| Plouvorn, Kernonen\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-807\n| 1200\n| 120\n|-\n| Goarem Goasven\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-1314\n| 1050\n| 130\n|-\n| Courcoury\n| Charente Maritime\n| Gif-2347\n| 850\n| 70\n|-\n| Plouhinec, Lescongar\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| Gif-2347\n| 850\n| 70\n|-\n| Cr\u00e9e de Carat\n| Finist\u00e8re\n| GrN-1973\n| 700\n| 60\n|}\n\nThe later part of the early Bronze Age saw the beginning of the exploitation of the Armorican [[tin]] deposits. Numerous hoards contain tools and weapons, but metalwork is rarely found in burials or settlements, which makes the synchronisation of hoards and settlements difficult. The Tr\u00e9boul-group of hoards is thought to be contemporaneous with the second series barrows. Decorated spear-heads, flanged axes, [[palstaves]] and long daggers are typical. The hoard from Bignan (Morbihan) contained only bronze jewellery.\n\nCoastal [[saltern]]s are known from the late Bronze Age onwards as well, for example at Curnic, Guiss\u00e9ny.\n\nPollen analysis shows that widespread clearance of the beech forests took place in the early Bronze Age. Cereal pollen have been found at Porsguen, Plouescat, for example. Domestic animals included sheep, goats and cattle, but hunting may have still provided a lot of meat. La Roche, Videlles, has still 60% wild animals among the animal bones, but it is not clear if this is typical. Carbonised remains of naked wheat and barley have been found at Ploun\u00e9our-Trez, hazelnuts and acorns were eaten as well. Flint still formed an important part of the tool inventory.\n\n[[File:Bretagne Morbihan Locmariaquer 14017.jpg|thumb|The ''Grand Menhir Bris\u00e9'' and ''Table des Marchand'' at Locmariaquer]]\n\nSome standing stones (Menhirs) and stone alignments date to the early Bronze Age, for example the Grand Menhir Bris\u00e9 at Locmariaquer.\n\nThe later Bronze Age sees only a slight [[Urnfield]] influence. Hoards are numerous. The Saint-Brieuc-des-Iffs phase marks the beginnings of the Atlantic bronze industries. It is succeeded by the [[carp's-tongue complex]], found in Britain and Portugal as well.\n\nThe square-socketed armorican axes turn up in [[hoard]]s in great numbers. At Maure-de-Bretagne, over 4000 axes have been found, ca. 800 at Tr\u00e9hou and Loud\u00e9ac.\n\nThe axes are mainly unused and may have been a form of ingot of primitive [[currency]]. They contain a high amount of lead or consist of pure lead and are distributed from the Iberian Peninsula to eastern Germany, Ireland and Southern Britain, with some pieces from Scotland, Poland and Switzerland. Different regional types are known: Brandivy in Morbihan, Dahouet and Plurien on the North coast, Tr\u00e9hou in Finist\u00e8re. The miniature types of Maure-de-Bretagne, Ille-et-Vilaine and Couville are typical of [[Upper Brittany]].\n\n[[Copper]] was imported from Spain as plano-convex [[ingot]]s, as  found in the [[hoard]] of Penfoul, [[Landelau]].\n\nSettlements have rarely been excavated, [[Ploubazlanec]] at the mouth of the [[Trieux]] is an example of a fortified village.\n\nThe Museum of PreHistory in Carnac has large quantities of Late Bronze Age bronze and copper artifacts from the [[Atlantic Bronze Age]] culture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museedecarnac.com/protohistoire.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604211819/http://www.museedecarnac.com/protohistoire.htm |archivedate=2010-06-04 }}</ref>\nThis culture was a maritime trading-networked culture that included Brittany and most of the rest of France, the other [[Celtic nations]], England, Spain and Portugal. According to [[John T. Koch]], [[Barry Cunliffe]], Karl, and Wodtko, [[Celtic languages]] developed in the intense interactions of this culture with the [[Tartessian language]] the first written language so far discovered from this era,<ref>http://www.aber.ac.uk/aberonline/en/archive/2008/05/au7608/</ref><ref name=Koch>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.ac.uk/Resources/Documents/Research/ODonnell.pdf|title=O'Donnell Lecture 2008 Appendix}}</ref><ref name=Koch2009>{{cite book | last = Koch | first = John | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Tartessian: Celtic from the Southwest at the Dawn of History in Acta Palaeohispanica X Palaeohispanica 9 (2009)| publisher = Palaeohispanica | year = 2009 | location = | pages = 339\u2013351 | url = http://ifc.dpz.es/recursos/publicaciones/29/54/26koch.pdf | doi = | id = | issn = 1578-5386 | accessdate = 2010-05-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=2146413465|title=New research suggests Welsh Celtic roots lie in Spain and Portugal|last=Koch|first=John|accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cunliffe, Karl, Guerra, McEvoy, Bradley; Oppenheimer, Rrvik, Isaac, Parsons, Koch, Freeman and Wodtko|title=Celtic from the West: Alternative Perspectives from Archaeology, Genetics, Language and Literature|year=2010|publisher=Oxbow Books and Celtic Studies Publications|isbn=978-1-84217-410-4|pages=384|url=http://www.oxbowbooks.com/bookinfo.cfm/ID/88298//Location/DBBC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612212219/http://www.oxbowbooks.com/bookinfo.cfm/ID/88298/Location/DBBC|archivedate=2010-06-12}}</ref> but this view stands in contrast to the more generally accepted view of Celticists that their origin lies with the Central European [[Hallstatt culture]] and that [[Tartessian language|Tartessian]] cannot be classified as Celtic at all.\n\n==Iron Age==\nA variety of tribes are mentioned in Roman sources, like the [[Veneti (Gaul)|Veneti]], [[Armoricani]], [[Osismii]], [[Namnetes]] and [[Coriosolites]]. [[Strabo]] and [[Poseidonius]] describe the Armoricani as belonging to the [[Belgae]].\n\nArmorican gold coins have been widely exported and are even found in the Rhineland.\n\n[[Salterns]] are widespread in Northern Armorica, for example at Tr\u00e9gor, Ebihens and Enez Vihan near Pleumeur-Bodou (C\u00f4tes-d'Armor) and the island of Yoc'h near Landuvez (Finist\u00e8re) of late [[La T\u00e8ne culture|La T\u00e8ne]] date.\n\nAn estimated  40\u201355&nbsp;kg  of salt per oven were produced at [[Ebihens]]. Each oven was  about 2 m long. The site dates to the end of the early [[La T\u00e8ne culture|La T\u00e8ne]] or the middle La T\u00e8ne period. Numerous [[briquetage]]-remains  have been found. At Tregor, boudins de Calage (hand-bricks) were the typical form of briquetage, between 2,5 and 15&nbsp;cm long and with a diameter between 4\u20137&nbsp;cm.\nAt the salterns at Landrellec and Enez Vihan at Pleumeur-Bodou the remains of rectangular ovens have been excavated that are 2,5\u20133 m long and ca. 1 m wide and constructed of stones and clay.\nOn the  [[Gulf of Morbihan]] about 50 salterns have been found so far. mainly dating to the final La T\u00e9ne period.\n\n:''For subsequent periods of Brittany's past, see [[Armorica]] and [[history of Brittany]].''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Bowen, E. G. (1977) ''Saints, Seaways and Settlements in the Celtic Lands''. Cardiff: University of Wales Press {{ISBN|0-900768-30-4}}\n* Monnier, Jean-Jacques & Cassard, Jean-Christophe, with a team of scholars of the Breton Universities of Brest, Nantes, and Rennes (1996) ''\"Toute l\u2019histoire de Bretagne\"  in Britain and in Brittany''; 800 pages. Morlaix: Editions Skol-Vreizh {{ISBN|2-903313-95-4}}\n* Tonnerre, No\u00ebl-Yves  (1994) ''Naissance de la Bretagne''; 621 pp. Angers: Presse de l'Universit\u00e9 d' Angers\n* Fleuriot, L\u00e9on (1980) ''Les origines de la Bretagne''. Paris: \u00c9d. Payot {{ISBN|2-228-12710-8}}\n* Dillon, Myles, Chadwick, Nora & Guyonvarc'h, Christian-J. ''Les royaumes celtiques'', Librairie Arth\u00e8me Fayard, 1974.{{ISBN|2-213-00077-8}}\n* Dillon, Myles & Chadwick, Nora (1967) ''The Celtic Realms''. London: Weidenfeld and Nicolson\n*''L'Histoire de la Bretagne et des pays celtiques'', Morlaix, Skol Vreizh, 1966\n* Le Moyne de la Borderie, Arthur (1905) ''Histoire de la Bretagne''; 6 vol. 4to, Plihon Editeur, Imprimerie Vatar, Rennes 1905-1914.\n* Lobineau, ''Dom'' (1707) ''Histoire de Bretagne''; 2 vol. folio  Paris: veuve Muguet\n* Morice, ''Dom'' & Taillandier, ''Dom'' (1750) ''Histoire de Bretagne''; 2 vol. folio. Paris:, veuve elaguette, 1750-1756.\n* Morice, ''Dom'' & Taillandier, ''Dom'' (1742) ''M\u00e9moires pour servir de preuves \u00e0 l'Histoire de Bretagne''; 3 vol. folio. Paris: Ch. Osmont, 1742-1746.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Prehistoric France]]\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric France]]\n[[Category:History of Brittany]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of France]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Brittany]]\n", "name_user": "Atsme", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix miscapitalizations (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prehistory_of_Brittany"}
{"title_page": "McClain (band)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist|<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = McClain\n| image            = McCLAIN band 2011 cropped.jpg\n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = McClain in 2011\n| origin           = [[Atlanta, Georgia]], United States\n| Background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = {{flat list|\n* 3McClainGirls\n* McClain Sisters}}\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]}}\n| years_active     = 2005\u20132016 (on hiatus)\n| label            = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood Records]] {{small|(2011\u201313)}}\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| current_members  = * [[China Anne McClain]]\n* Sierra McClain\n* Lauryn McClain\n}}\n'''McClain''' (formerly '''3McClainGirls''' and '''McClain Sisters''') is an American [[girl group]] that was formed in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], in 2004. The group consists of sisters [[China Anne McClain]], Sierra McClain, and Lauryn McClain. They signed with [[Hollywood Records]] in 2011 and released their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\" in 2012. In 2013, the group left the record label and are now on hiatus and pursuing their acting careers. Their most recent single was \"Feelin' Like\" which was released in 2016.\n\n<br />\n\n== Early life ==\nSierra Aylina McClain was born on March 16, 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2057826/|title=Sierra Aylina McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, Lauryn Alisa McClain was born on January 9, 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2055160/|title=Lauryn Alisa McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, and China Anne McClain was born on August 25, 1998<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1942207/|title=China Anne McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. All three sisters were born and raised in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Their father, Michael McClain, is a music producer who produce [[Solange Knowles]]' debut album. Their mother, Shontell McClain, is a songwriter and former screenwriter. The sisters also have a little brother, Gabriel McClain, who was born on April 17, 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2532716/|title=Gabriel McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\nSierra Aylina, Lauryn Alisa and [[China Anne McClain]] grew up watching [[Disney]] films such as [[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]] and musical classics such as [[The Wiz]], [[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]] and [[Annie (1982 film)|Annie]].<ref name=\"filmb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmbug.com/db/346128|title=Sierra, Lauryn & China Anne McClain|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=Filmbug.com}}</ref> In 2004, the sisters became interested in music when they watched their father write and produce songs. Soon after, the girls began to write songs, choreograph and dance.<ref name=\"lions\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|title=McClain notes on Lionsgate|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=lionsgatepublicity.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206114300/http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|archivedate=February 6, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 2005\u20132009: 3McClainGirls and ''Daddy's Little Girls'' ===\nIn 2005, the sisters were discovered as actresses by a music executive who heard them sing and encouraged director [[Rob Hardy]] to audition China for his 2005 feature film ''[[The Gospel (film)|The Gospel]].'' China was cast as the character Alexis and her sisters were in the supporting cast.<ref name=\"dc\">{{cite web |url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |title=Disney Channel Bio \u2013 China Anne McClain |publisher=Disney Channel Medianet |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The sisters became more serious about a musical career and formed the girl group the 3McClainGirls. \n\nThey recorded their first song, \"Silly Games\". The song was produced by their father, Michael McClain, and written by their mother, Shontell McClain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ovguide.com/3mcclaingirls-9202a8c04000641f8000000006afa58b# |title=3McClainGirls Music |publisher=OV Guide |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2006 China joined the main cast of ''[[Tyler Perry's House of Payne]]'' (2006-2012)  as Jazmine Payne and Sierra made guest appearances. In 2007 the group starred in the comedy-drama film ''[[Daddy's Little Girls]]'' as the James sisters.<ref name=\"lions\" /> In 2008 the group recorded the song \"Daddy's Girls\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/daddys-girl-mw0001655815 |title=3mcclaingirls! Daddy's Girl |publisher=Allmusic |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> inspired by the movie, and released it exclusively on Myspace.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.myspace.com/mcclainsisters |title=3mcclaingirls Official Myspace |publisher=Myspace |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2008 the group began posting videos on Youtube of the sisters singing covers of songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCksYLtnxiIW0UTegpdbseMQ|title=3mcclaingirls|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== 2009\u20132013: McClain Sisters, ''A.N.T. Farm'' and Hollywood Records ===\nThe group continued posting covers on their Youtube channel while the sisters also made various acting appearances in films and on television. The group originally planned to use the name III as their group name, the number representing the three McClain girls in the group, but that was scrapped.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2011 the group changed their name to the McClain Sisters and signed with [[Hollywood Records]] on June 14, 2011.<ref name=\"hollywoodrecords\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|title=MCCLAIN SISTERS SIGN WITH HOLLYWOOD RECORDS|publisher=Black Celeb Kids|date=June 14, 2011|access-date=February 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126042852/http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> That same year China landed her own show on the [[Disney Channel]] called [[A.N.T. Farm]]. On October 11, 2011, the [[A.N.T. Farm (soundtrack)]] was released on which the group had two songs: \"Perfect Mistake\" and \"Electronic Apology\". The group had plans to release their debut album with the record label<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/11/arts/television/tween-stars-wanted-must-be-primed-for-pressure.html|title=Tween Stars Wanted: Must Be Primed for Pressure|date=2011-05-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but never did. In December the group performed their version of [[Jingle Bell Rock]] at the 2011 [[Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Christmas Parade 2011 McClain Sisters - Celebrity Take with Jake|url=https://video.disney.com/watch/christmas-parade-2011-mcclain-sisters-4bb39f0d70be4a8833003b15|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tigerbeat.com/2011/11/exclusive-bop-and-tiger-beats-photo-shoot-with-china/onerepublic-and-china-anne-mcclain-and-the-mcclain-sisters-perform-for-the-2011-disney-parks-christmas-day-parade/|title=OneRepublic and China Anne McClain and The McClain Sisters Perform for The 2011 Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade {{!}} TigerBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 11, 2012 they performed a new song called \"Rise\" at the [[Mall of America]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mallofamerica.com/upload/event/pdf/ChinaGuidelinesUPDATE.pdf|title=China Anne McClain & the McClain Sisters Performance and Signing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The song was written by the McClain Sisters and produced by father Michael McClain, and was the lead promotional single for the [[Disneynature]] film [[Chimpanzee (film)|''Chimpanzee'']]. The song was released on March 23, 2012. The music video premiered on March 25, 2012 during an episode of ''[[Austin & Ally]]''. It was also a featured song for [[Disney's Friends for Change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mallofamerica.com/events/view/126|title=China Anne McClain and McClain Sisters Performance and Singing|publisher=Mall of America|date=March 22, 2012}}</ref> The music video later premiered online on March 26, 2012. \n\nOn November 2, 2012, the McClain Sisters premiered their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/go-single/id573043137|title=Music \u2013 Go - iTunes United States|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> Lauryn and Sierra guest starred and performed the song, alongside China, on November 23, 2012 during the episode \"[[List of A.N.T. Farm episodes#ep41|chANTs of a lifetime]]\" for ''[[A.N.T. Farm]].'' \n\n=== 2013\u2013present: Leaving Hollywood Records, McClain, and hiatus ===\nIn December of 2013, China announced on Twitter that [[A.N.T. Farm]] would be ending after its third season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/chinamcclain/status/416460834571694080|title=It was GREAT filming ANT Farm but after 3 seasons it's come to an end. I'm excited about my secret projects and keeping you guys happy!|last=China\u2077|date=2013-12-26|website=@chinamcclain|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Shortly after this announcement, the McClain Sisters parted ways with [[Hollywood Records]]. After leaving the record label the group changed their name from the McClain Sisters to simply McClain. The group released an official lyric video for their single \"He Loves Me\" on their YouTube on December 14, 2013.<ref>{{Citation|last=mcclainsisters|title=He Loves Me- Lyric Video|date=2013-12-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z21wV7XRaqs|accessdate=2016-06-13}}</ref> The song then became available on iTunes on February 20, 2014. Later that year, McClain released a Christmas song called \"The Holiday Song\". \n\nThe last single the sisters released was \"Feelin' Like\" in 2016 and the group now seems to be on hiatus. All three sisters are pursuing their acting careers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nThe sisters are known for their family-friendly image.<ref name=\"China\">{{cite web|title=China Anne McClain Bio|url=http://www.kidzworld.com/article/25662-china-anne-mcclain-bio|work=kidzworld.com|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> They reside in Los Angeles, California with their family.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of China |url=http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |work=chinaanne.net |accessdate=September 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121125013234/http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |archivedate=November 25, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Disney's Friends for Change#Rise|Rise]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rise-feat.-mcclain-sisters/id509693456|title=Rise \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"He Loves Me\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/he-loves-me-single/id827805733|title=He Loves Me \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Feelin' Like\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/officialmcclain/feelin-like-ode-to-aaliyah|title=Feelin' Like \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=Soundcloud|accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n===Promotional singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Silly Games\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngblackstarz.org/2012/04/03/memory-lane-these-girls-had-no-time-for-silly-games/|title=MEMORY LANE: THESE GIRLS HAD NO TIME FOR \"SILLY GAMES\"|work=Young Black Stars|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref><br><span style=\"font-size:85%; <!--font-weight:normal;-->\">(featuring Tiff Mic)</span>\n| 2005\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Daddy's Girl\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/daddys-girl/id275361079|title=3mcclaingirls! \u2013 Daddy's Girl|work=iTunes|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref>\n| 2008\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust And Pixie Dust#The Great Divide|The Great Divide]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/great-divide-from-secret-wings/id556729644|title=The Great Divide \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2012\n| ''[[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust and Pixie Dust]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"The Holiday Song\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-holiday-song-single/id952382814|title=The Holiday Song - Single|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Perfect Mistake\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2011\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[A.N.T. Farm (soundtrack)|A.N.T. Farm]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Electronic Apology\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Jingle Bell Rock]]\"\n| 2012\n| ''[[Disney Channel Holiday Playlist]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Sharp As a Razor\"\n| 2013\n| ''[[Shake It Up: I Love Dance|Shake It Up: I <3 Dance]]''\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! cindy=\"sharp\"| Director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Rise (McClain Sisters song)|Rise]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| Mark Albert\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Great Divide\"\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Concert tours==\n;Opening act:\n* 2012: [[Better with U Tour#Opening act|Better with U Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/06/the-mcclain-sisters-take-to-the-stage/|title=THE MCCLAIN SISTERS TAKE TO THE STAGE|work=blackcelebkids.com|date=May 13, 2010|accessdate=May 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308123351/http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/06/the-mcclain-sisters-take-to-the-stage/|archive-date=March 8, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> {{small|([[Big Time Rush (band)|Big Time Rush]])}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mcclainsistersmusic.com/ Official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical trios]]\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:African-American girl groups]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B musical groups]]\n[[Category:American girl groups]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist|<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = McClain\n| image            = McCLAIN band 2011 cropped.jpg\n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = McClain in 2011\n| origin           = [[Atlanta, Georgia]], United States\n| Background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = {{flat list|\n* 3McClainGirls\n* McClain Sisters}}\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]}}\n| years_active     = 2005\u20132016 (on hiatus)\n| label            = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood Records]] {{small|(2011\u201313)}}\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| current_members  = * [[China Anne McClain]]\n* Sierra McClain\n* Lauryn McClain\n}}\n'''McClain''' (formerly '''3McClainGirls''' and '''McClain Sisters''') is an American [[girl group]] that was formed in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], in 2004. The group consists of sisters [[China Anne McClain]], Sierra McClain, and Lauryn McClain. They signed with [[Hollywood Records]] in 2011 and released their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\" in 2012. In 2013, the group left the record label and are now on hiatus and pursuing their acting careers. Their most recent single was \"Feelin' Like\" which was released in 2016.\n\n<br />\n\n== Early life ==\nSierra Aylina McClain was born on March 16, 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2057826/|title=Sierra Aylina McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, Lauryn Alisa McClain was born on January 9, 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2055160/|title=Lauryn Alisa McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, and China Anne McClain was born on August 25, 1998<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1942207/|title=China Anne McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. All three sisters were born and raised in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Their father, Michael McClain, is a music producer who produce [[Solange Knowles]]' debut album. Their mother, Shontell McClain, is a songwriter and former screenwriter. The sisters also have a little brother, Gabriel McClain, who was born on April 17, 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2532716/|title=Gabriel McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\nSierra Aylina, Lauryn Alisa and [[China Anne McClain]] grew up watching [[Disney]] films such as [[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]] and musical classics such as [[The Wiz]], [[Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory]] and [[Annie (1982 film)|Annie]].<ref name=\"filmb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmbug.com/db/346128|title=Sierra, Lauryn & China Anne McClain|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=Filmbug.com}}</ref> In 2004, the sisters became interested in music when they watched their father write and produce songs. Soon after, the girls began to write songs, choreograph and dance.<ref name=\"lions\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|title=McClain notes on Lionsgate|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=lionsgatepublicity.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206114300/http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|archivedate=February 6, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 2005\u20132009: 3McClainGirls and ''Daddy's Little Girls'' ===\nIn 2005, the sisters were discovered as actresses by a music executive who heard them sing and encouraged director [[Rob Hardy]] to audition China for his 2005 feature film ''[[The Gospel (film)|The Gospel]].'' China was cast as the character Alexis and her sisters were in the supporting cast.<ref name=\"dc\">{{cite web |url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |title=Disney Channel Bio \u2013 China Anne McClain |publisher=Disney Channel Medianet |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The sisters became more serious about a musical career and formed the girl group the 3McClainGirls. \n\nThey recorded their first song, \"Silly Games\". The song was produced by their father, Michael McClain, and written by their mother, Shontell McClain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ovguide.com/3mcclaingirls-9202a8c04000641f8000000006afa58b# |title=3McClainGirls Music |publisher=OV Guide |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2006 China joined the main cast of ''[[Tyler Perry's House of Payne]]'' (2006-2012)  as Jazmine Payne and Sierra made guest appearances. In 2007 the group starred in the comedy-drama film ''[[Daddy's Little Girls]]'' as the James sisters.<ref name=\"lions\" /> In 2008 the group recorded the song \"Daddy's Girls\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/daddys-girl-mw0001655815 |title=3mcclaingirls! Daddy's Girl |publisher=Allmusic |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> inspired by the movie, and released it exclusively on Myspace.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.myspace.com/mcclainsisters |title=3mcclaingirls Official Myspace |publisher=Myspace |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2008 the group began posting videos on Youtube of the sisters singing covers of songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCksYLtnxiIW0UTegpdbseMQ|title=3mcclaingirls|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== 2009\u20132013: McClain Sisters, ''A.N.T. Farm'' and Hollywood Records ===\nThe group continued posting covers on their Youtube channel while the sisters also made various acting appearances in films and on television. The group originally planned to use the name III as their group name, the number representing the three McClain girls in the group, but that was scrapped.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2011 the group changed their name to the McClain Sisters and signed with [[Hollywood Records]] on June 14, 2011.<ref name=\"hollywoodrecords\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|title=MCCLAIN SISTERS SIGN WITH HOLLYWOOD RECORDS|publisher=Black Celeb Kids|date=June 14, 2011|access-date=February 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126042852/http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> That same year China landed her own show on the [[Disney Channel]] called [[A.N.T. Farm]]. On October 11, 2011, the [[A.N.T. Farm (soundtrack)]] was released on which the group had two songs: \"Perfect Mistake\" and \"Electronic Apology\". The group had plans to release their debut album with the record label<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/11/arts/television/tween-stars-wanted-must-be-primed-for-pressure.html|title=Tween Stars Wanted: Must Be Primed for Pressure|date=2011-05-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but never did. In December the group performed their version of [[Jingle Bell Rock]] at the 2011 [[Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Christmas Parade 2011 McClain Sisters - Celebrity Take with Jake|url=https://video.disney.com/watch/christmas-parade-2011-mcclain-sisters-4bb39f0d70be4a8833003b15|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tigerbeat.com/2011/11/exclusive-bop-and-tiger-beats-photo-shoot-with-china/onerepublic-and-china-anne-mcclain-and-the-mcclain-sisters-perform-for-the-2011-disney-parks-christmas-day-parade/|title=OneRepublic and China Anne McClain and The McClain Sisters Perform for The 2011 Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade {{!}} TigerBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 11, 2012 they performed a new song called \"Rise\" at the [[Mall of America]]. It was written by the McClain Sisters and produced by father Michael McClain, and was the lead promotional single for the [[Disneynature]] film [[Chimpanzee (film)|''Chimpanzee'']]. The song was released on March 23, 2012. The music video premiered on March 25, 2012 during an episode of ''[[Austin & Ally]]''. It was also a featured song for [[Disney's Friends for Change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mallofamerica.com/events/view/126|title=China Anne McClain and McClain Sisters Performance and Singing|publisher=Mall of America|date=March 22, 2012}}</ref> The music video later premiered online on March 26, 2012. \n\nOn November 2, 2012, the McClain Sisters premiered their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/go-single/id573043137|title=Music \u2013 Go - iTunes United States|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> Lauryn and Sierra guest starred and performed the song, alongside China, on November 23, 2012 during the episode \"[[List of A.N.T. Farm episodes#ep41|chANTs of a lifetime]]\" for ''[[A.N.T. Farm]].'' \n\n=== 2013\u2013present: Leaving Hollywood Records, McClain, and hiatus ===\nIn December of 2013, China announced on Twitter that [[A.N.T. Farm]] would be ending after its third season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/chinamcclain/status/416460834571694080|title=It was GREAT filming ANT Farm but after 3 seasons it's come to an end. I'm excited about my secret projects and keeping you guys happy!|last=China\u2077|date=2013-12-26|website=@chinamcclain|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Shortly after this announcement, the McClain Sisters parted ways with [[Hollywood Records]]. After leaving the record label the group changed their name from the McClain Sisters to simply McClain. The group released an official lyric video for their single \"He Loves Me\" on their YouTube on December 14, 2013.<ref>{{Citation|last=mcclainsisters|title=He Loves Me- Lyric Video|date=2013-12-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z21wV7XRaqs|accessdate=2016-06-13}}</ref> The song then became available on iTunes on February 20, 2014. Later that year, McClain released a Christmas song called \"The Holiday Song\". \n\nThe last single the sisters released was \"Feelin' Like\" in 2016 and the group now seems to be on hiatus. All three sisters are pursuing their acting careers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nThe sisters are known for their family-friendly image.<ref name=\"China\">{{cite web|title=China Anne McClain Bio|url=http://www.kidzworld.com/article/25662-china-anne-mcclain-bio|work=kidzworld.com|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> They reside in Los Angeles, California with their family.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of China |url=http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |work=chinaanne.net |accessdate=September 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121125013234/http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |archivedate=November 25, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Disney's Friends for Change#Rise|Rise]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rise-feat.-mcclain-sisters/id509693456|title=Rise \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"He Loves Me\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/he-loves-me-single/id827805733|title=He Loves Me \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Feelin' Like\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/officialmcclain/feelin-like-ode-to-aaliyah|title=Feelin' Like \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=Soundcloud|accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n===Promotional singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Silly Games\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngblackstarz.org/2012/04/03/memory-lane-these-girls-had-no-time-for-silly-games/|title=MEMORY LANE: THESE GIRLS HAD NO TIME FOR \"SILLY GAMES\"|work=Young Black Stars|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref><br><span style=\"font-size:85%; <!--font-weight:normal;-->\">(featuring Tiff Mic)</span>\n| 2005\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Daddy's Girl\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/daddys-girl/id275361079|title=3mcclaingirls! \u2013 Daddy's Girl|work=iTunes|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref>\n| 2008\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust And Pixie Dust#The Great Divide|The Great Divide]]\